text: The patient has a 4.5 cm non-mucinous, papillary adenocarcinoma located in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor exhibits areas of poor differentiation, pleural infiltration, and vascular invasion, with metastases present in the hilar lymph nodes. The tumor is classified as M-8140/3, G3, pT2, pV0, pN2, pMx, indicating a stage IIIA disease. The resection margins are clear (R0).

Diagnosis: The patient presents with a poorly differentiated, non-mucinous pulmonary adenocarcinoma in the upper lobe of the lung, measuring up to 3.2 cm. The tumor is classified as M-8140/3, G 3, pT 2, pV 1, pN 2, pM X, stage III A. Immunohistochemical analysis reveals absence of cytokeratin 5, co-expression of cytokeratin 7 and 20 in some cells, and strong CEA expression. Most cells show nuclear TTF-1 expression. The Mib-1 proliferation index is moderately high at 30%. These findings support the diagnosis of primary pulmonary adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a two-part resection of the right lower lobe, revealing a well-differentiated, non-mucinous, papillary adenocarcinoma measuring approximately 50mm. The tumor extends to the visceral pleura, which is free of tumor cells. The bronchial resection level is also tumor-free. Subpleural scarring and pleural adhesion residues are present. The tumor is classified as M-8140/3, G1, pT 2 2, pN 0, pMX, stage I B. The resection margins (R) are clear (R0).

The patient has a locally advanced, poorly differentiated adenosquamous carcinoma in the right lower lobe, measuring at least 65mm, with almost complete pleural infiltration and penetration of S6. The excision does not extend into healthy tissue and there are tongue-shaped extensions into the peribronchial and hilar fatty connective tissue, with lymph node metastases exhibiting necrotic destruction. There is also multifocal invasion of the blood vessels. Based on these findings, complete removal of the carcinoma is uncertain. The tumor is classified as M-8140/3, G3, pT3, pV1, pN1, pMx, stage III A. R2.

The patient has been diagnosed with a mixed large-cell and clear-cell adenocarcinoma, primarily located in the left upper lobe (S3) of the lung. The tumor is histologically characterized by a predominant solid and small acinar component. The TNM classification based on the available material is pT2 pN0 pMX R0, indicating stage IB of the disease (C34.1; M 8255/3). The carcinoma has locally infiltrated the visceral pleura, however, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all identified and removed lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The patient has a peripheral mixed bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma, characterized by a mucin-forming, tubulopapillary structure with a partial bronchioloalveolar growth pattern. The tumor has focally infiltrated the visceral pleura in the pleural adhesion zone and extends to the basal row of metal clamps. The preliminary TNM classification is pT2 pNX pMX RX (C34.3, M8255/3). Immunohistochemical analysis confirms the diagnosis, with positive markers for cytokeratin 7 and TTF1, focal positivity for cytokeratin 20, and negative for CDX2.

The patient has been diagnosed with mixed bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma, confirmed by the tumor's histoarchitecture and cell morphology. Immunohistological investigations will further validate this diagnosis. The tumor was completely excised via wedge resection from sample 1. The visceral pleura, the right upper lobe from sample 2, including the resection margin of the bronchus and vessels, and all removed lymph nodes are free of tumor. Assuming a bronchopulmonary origin, the tumor is classified as pT1, pNo, R0, stage IA. C 34.1 M 8255/3.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed peripheral bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma, predominantly acinar with a smaller large-cell solid component, located in the right upper lobe of the lung (S2). The tumor, which is at the junction with S1, has infiltrated the retracted visceral pleura, causing enlargement and fibrosis. According to the TNM classification, the tumor is categorized as pT2, pN0, R0, stage IB (C 34.1; M 8255/3). The resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all removed lymph nodes (samples 1 to 7), are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a locally advanced, primarily peripheral, mixed, highly mucigenous adenocarcinoma of the left upper lobe of the lung, predominantly large-cell and polymorphocellular solid and small acinar component, situated at the boundary of segments 1 and 3. The tumor has infiltrated the parietal layer in the pleural adhesion zone and possibly extends into the hilum of the superior lobe, forming a large manifestation involving parabronchial lymph nodes. A separate satellite focus is present in S3. The central tumor has infiltrated the pulmonary venous wall and is in close proximity to the hilar resection margin. Due to the tangential section, it is unclear if the tumor infiltrate forms the margin. A further lymph node metastasis is found in sample 3. The resection margins of bronchus and vessels, the pericardial specimen, and the lymph nodes of samples 4 and 5 are tumor-free. The TNM classification is pT4 pN2 V1 RX, stage IIIB.

The patient presents with an extensive bronchopulmonary mixed adenocarcinoma, predominantly tubulopapillary and bronchioloalveolar in nature, with minor mucin formation and numerous small foci within the parenchyma. Minimal pleural invasion and lymphogenous metastatic spread are observed. Microscopic satellite nodes are detected in the lipsilateral lobe, suggesting a tumor classification of pT4 pN1 R0. However, considering the tumor's presentation and partial bronchioloalveolar differentiation, it could also be a primary multifocal tumor manifestation, corresponding to pT2(m). The main tumor mass is located in segments 6 and 9 of the resected right lower lobe, with the largest regional lymph node metastasis measuring 1.2 mm. The coding is C 34.3; M 8255/3. The stage grouping could be either IIIB or IIB.

The patient presents with a centrally located bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma of mixed differentiation (G3), characterized by a combination of maturing tubuloglandular cells, medium to large cells, and clear cells. The tumor exhibits necrotic changes and has invaded the large pulmonary vessels and the pleura. The tumor is classified as pT2 pN1 V2 RX, stage IIB (C34.2; M 8255/3). Unusually, the tumor has formed lumen-obstructing thrombi in the large pulmonary vessels, extending beyond the resection margin. The carcinoma adheres minimally about 0.5 mm from the resection margin of the vessels. The tumor also invades the pleura, extending focally to the pleural surface. The glandular maturation component is partly reminiscent of the fetal type of bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma. A lymph node with tumor is located in the hilus region, adjacent to one of the tumor-infiltrated large pulmonary vessels. The patient likely had a retrostenotic pneumonia.

The patient has been diagnosed with a locally advanced, peripheral bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung. The tumor is histologically mixed with a predominant large-cell, polymorphocellular and partly clear-cell solid component, and exhibits a bronchioloalveolar growth pattern at the periphery with a very small acinar part, primarily located in S1 with a satellite focus in S3. The TNM classification is pT4 pN3 L1 V1 R0, indicating stage IIIB of the disease. The tumor has a large cicatricial area and has invaded small blood vessels within the tumor and lymph nodes, with metastases found in samples 1 to 4, 6 to 8, and 10. However, the visceral pleura, resection margins of the bronchus and vessels of the main preparation, and the lymph nodes of samples 5 to 9 are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a mixed adenocarcinoma, predominantly acinar, located peripherally in the lower lobe. The tumor also presents a smaller large-cell solid component with a bronchioloalveolar growth pattern at the periphery, slight mucin formation, and significant lymph vessel propagation in the lung tissue and visceral pleura. The tumor has infiltrated the visceral pleura, focally penetrated the surface, and extends to the basal margin of the preparation post metal clamp removal. The tumor classification is pT2 pNX pMX L1 RX, with localization code C34.3 and morphology code M8255/3. Further verification through immunohistological analysis is recommended.

The patient has been diagnosed with a large, histologically mixed, highly mucigenous adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, predominantly bronchiolo-alveolar of mucinous type with a minor acinar and solid part, primarily located in S3. The TNM classification is pT2 pN0 R0, stage IB, C 3 34.1 M 8255/3. There is no evidence of visceral pleura infiltration by the carcinoma and the resection margins of bronchus and vessels, as well as all removed and identified lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed adenocarcinoma of the right lower lobe of the lung, specifically in S8, exhibiting both acinar and papillary components. The tumor, classified as pT2 pN0 V1 R0, stage IB under the TNM classification, has infiltrated the blood vessels within the tumor. However, the visceral pleura, bronchial and vascular resection margins, and all excised lymph nodes are free of tumor cells.

The patient has undergone a pulmonary wedge resection, revealing a peripheral mixed bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma with a focal mucin-forming component. The tumor exhibits a predominantly tubular or acinar structure, with some areas showing a bronchioloalveolar growth pattern and a small solid and papillary component. The tumor has infiltrated the visceral pleura and extends to the basal resection margin, leading to an RX classification. The TNM classification based on these samples is pT2 pNO pMX L1 V1 RX, corresponding to stage IB. Immunohistochemical analysis confirms the bronchopulmonary origin of the tumor, with positive staining for cytokeratin 7 and TTF-1, and negative staining for cytokeratin 20 and CDX-2. Further analysis regarding the tumor's point of origin is pending.

The patient presents with a large-cell and polymorphocellular, partially giant-cell adenocarcinoma of the left lung, with both central and peripheral manifestations and mucin inclusions. The tumor, classified as pT4 pN2 pMX V1 R0, stage IIIB, C34.3 M8255/3, involves both the upper and lower lobes, causing obliteration and stenosis of central bronchus segments and continuous infiltration of parabronchial lymph nodes. A peripheral manifestation is noted in S6, but the visceral pleura remains tumor-free. A further lymph node metastasis is found in sample 3. Tumor invasions are observed in small intratumoral blood vessels. However, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, the hilar resection surface of the main preparation, and the lymph nodes in samples 2, 4, 5, and 6 are all tumor-free.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, specifically in S3, with large-cell, clear-cell, solid and acinar components, and slight mucin formation. The tumor has extended into adjoining segments of S4 and S5 over the oblique fissure of the lung. Based on the TNM classification, the tumor is categorized as pT2 pN0 pMX R0, corresponding to stage IB. Importantly, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all removed lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a locally advanced, peripheral bronchopulmonary, histologically mixed adenocarcinoma of the left lower lobe of the lung, specifically in S8. The tumor exhibits large-cell and clear-cell, solid and acinar components, with mucin formation. The TNM classification is pT3 pN2 pMX V1 R0, indicating stage IIIA disease (C 34.1 M 8255/3). The carcinoma has infiltrated the pericardial fatty tissue and lymph node metastases are present in the hilar region. However, the bronchus and vessel resection margins, pericardial resection material, adhered part of the parietal pleura, and lymph nodes from samples 3 and 5 are all tumor-free.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed adenocarcinoma, predominantly papillary and small acinar, located in the right lower lobe of the lung, specifically segments 7 to 9. The tumor has also extended to S4 of the middle lobe. The TNM classification is pT2 pN0 pMX R0, indicating stage IB lung cancer (C34.3 M8255/3). Notably, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all removed lymph nodes, are free of tumor cells.

The patient has been diagnosed with a well-differentiated mixed adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, classified as peripheral bronchopulmonary. The TNM classification is pT2 pNO R0, stage IB, C34.3 M8255/3. The tumor, primarily tubulopapillary in differentiation, has a compact, low stromal structure with a small bronchioloalveolar component at the margin. It extends to the pleura but has not infiltrated it. The carcinoma has invaded a peripheral bronchus, which is significantly distended and largely obstructed by a tumor plug. This diagnosis is based on immunohistochemical analysis of previous biopsy material.

The patient has been diagnosed with a locally advanced, peripheral bronchopulmonary, histologically mixed adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, specifically in S1 and S2, with an acinar and solid component and slight mucin formation. The TNM classification is pT3 pNO pMX V1 R1, stage IIB, C34.1 M8255/3. The carcinoma has infiltrated the adhesive part of the chest wall, including the soft tissue and the 3rd rib, extending to the outer resection surface at the thoracic skin, which justifies the R1 classification. The tumor has also reached the visceral pleura of the adhesive part, likely from S6 of the upper lobe. However, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, the other resection margins of the resected chest wall material, the lung parenchyma of the resection material likely taken from S6, and all the identified and removed lymph nodes are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a primary peripheral bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma, histologically mixed, located in the middle lobe with pleural invasion. A secondary small focus or satellite nodule of tubular adenocarcinoma with a minor bronchioalveolar growth component and pleural infiltration was also identified. The TNM classification is pT2 pNO pM1 (PUL) V1 RX, stage IV. Immunohistochemical analysis confirmed the tumor as adenocarcinoma of the lung with a predominantly tubulopapillary structural pattern. The secondary small tumor focus is classified as a hematogenous metastasis, based on its structure and lack of fibrous remodeling or cicatricial zone. Vascular invasion is observed in the larger tumor, with tumor spread and endobronchial occlusion in a subsegmental bronchus branch. The R1 classification is due to tumor glands invading the pleura and extending to the outer surface, leaving tumor cells in the pleural space. Both tumor foci are CK7 positive and CK20 negative, with isolated cells staining for surfactant protein B, supporting the diagnosis of lung adenocarcinoma and the metastasis of the smaller focus from the larger primary tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a large, histologically mixed adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, specifically in segments S9 and S10. This tumor exhibits both acinar and solid components, with a partial bronchioloalveolar pattern of spread. Additionally, a small, non-mucinous bronchioloalveolar carcinoma has been identified peripherally in segment S6. Based on the TNM classification, the tumor is staged as pT2(2) pNO pMX R0, indicating stage IB lung cancer. The codes C34.3, M8255/3, and M8252/3 further specify the diagnosis.

The patient has been diagnosed with a large, predominantly undifferentiated mixed large-cell and polymorphocellular adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, classified as pT2 pN1 R0, stage IIB (C34.1 M8255/3, G3). The carcinoma is primarily composed of large-cell and polymorphocellular solid components, with minor sections exhibiting clear-cell characteristics, suggesting potential neuroendocrine differentiation. The carcinoma appears to be a primary peripheral lung tumor that has minimally invaded the overlying visceral pleura and shows central bronchopulmonary and hilar lymph node metastases. However, other hilus and removed lymph nodes are tumor-free. Immunohistochemical analysis confirms the tumor classification of mixed-type adenocarcinoma of the lung, with a high proportion of tumor cells positive for low molecular weight keratins, a small proportion positive for high molecular weight keratins, and a relatively high proportion positive for TTF1. The tumor cells are negative for synaptophysin and NCAM.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed-cell adenocarcinoma of the left lower lobe of the lung, specifically in S6, with a predominant acinar and small large-cell solid component. The tumor exhibits a bronchioloalveolar pattern of spread in its periphery. The TNM classification based on the available material is pT2 pNO pMX R0, indicating stage IB of the disease (C34.3; M 8255/3). Notably, the carcinoma has infiltrated the visceral pleura. However, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all removed lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with a histologically mixed adenocarcinoma, predominantly large-cell with a small acinar component, in the right upper lobe of the lung (S2). The tumor exhibits a bronchioloalveolar growth pattern at the margin and focal mucin formation. The TNM classification is pT2 pN1 pMX RX, indicating stage IIB lung cancer (C34.1; M 8255/3). The carcinoma has infiltrated and perforated the visceral pleura, leading to the RX category, and has metastasized to a hilar lymph node. However, the bronchus and vessel resection margins, the resected middle lobe, the parietal pleura piece, and lymph nodes from samples 4 to 13 are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with peripheral bronchopulmonary mucinous adenocarcinoma, primarily exhibiting bronchioloalveolar differentiation with a minor component showing destructive, infiltrative growth, localized in S10. The TNM classification based on the available material is pT2 pN0 pMX R0, stage IB (C34.3 M 8255/3). Importantly, there is no evidence of carcinoma infiltration into the visceral pleura, and the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, as well as all excised lymph nodes, are free of tumor.

The patient has been diagnosed with an extensive, locoregionally advanced, bronchopulmonary adenocarcinoma of the right lower lobe of the lung, primarily peripheral in nature. The tumor has invaded the pleura and metastasized to both pleural layers and lymph nodes, classifying it as stage IV (pT4 pN1 pM1 (P/E) V1 RX). Histological examination reveals a predominant large-cell solid tumor component with clear-cell characteristics, and glandular tubulopapillary and bronchioloalveolar differentiation in the main tumor margin and surrounding area. No squamous epithelium maturation pattern is evident. Immunohistochemical analysis confirms the bronchopulmonary origin of the tumor, with tumor cells expressing low and high molecular weight keratins (M903 and 902) and TTF1 positive nuclei in the glandular differentiation component. The central bronchus resection line and the resection margins of the large pulmonary vessels and parietal pleura are tumor-free.

As a pathologist, the crucial information extracted from the TCGA Missing Pathology Report Form includes the tumor type of the case, the Biospecimen Core Resource (BCR) location to which the case was originally sent, the date the specimen was received at the BCR, the ICD-0-3 Histology Code, and the ICD-0-3 Site Code. These details are essential for the diagnosis and management of the case. The histology and site codes, derived from the Case Quality Control Form (CQCF), provide specific information about the sample and the overall patient diagnosis.

The patient has been diagnosed with a well-differentiated mixed adenocarcinoma (G1), primarily located in the S1 segment of the left upper lobe of the lung. The tumor exhibits a bronchioloalveolar pattern of spread with a partly pseudopapillary structure, and a small acinar and solid component. Initial infiltration is observed in the partially resected material from S6. However, the resection surface, the resection margins of the bronchus and vessels, and the lymph nodes from samples 2 to 8 are free of tumor. According to the TNM classification (UICC, 7th ed., 2009), the tumor is classified as pT2a pN0 L0 V0 R0, stage IB. The ICD-10 code is C34.1 and the morphology code is M8255/3.

The patient has been diagnosed with Stage 2 Adenocarcinoma of the lung, with a tumor-node-metastasis (TNM) staging of T2, N0, M0, indicating a primary tumor that has grown but not spread to lymph nodes or distant sites. The tumor tissue was obtained from the primary site in the lung and preserved in an OCT block. Additionally, a blood sample was drawn and frozen for further analysis. No treatment has been administered yet. Histological examination reveals that over 50% of the tissue sample consists of tumor cells.

The patient has been diagnosed with primary lung cancer, specifically adeno-squamous carcinoma, which is at TNM stage 2 (T1, N0, M0), indicating the presence of a tumor that has not spread to lymph nodes or distant sites. No treatment has been administered yet. A tumor tissue specimen was obtained and preserved in an OCT block, and a blood sample was also collected and frozen for further analysis. The tumor cell component is estimated to be 75%.

The patient has been diagnosed with primary lung cancer, specifically adeno-squamous carcinoma, which is at a grade 2. The TNM staging is T2, N0, M0, indicating the tumor is of a certain size but there are no signs of lymph node involvement or distant metastasis. The tumor tissue was obtained and preserved in an OCT block. Additionally, a blood sample was drawn and frozen for further analysis. The tumor cell percentage is 74%. Currently, no treatment such as chemotherapy or hormone therapy has been administered.

The patient has a primary tumor located in the upper lobe of the left lung. The histological description reveals a grade 3, non-keratinizing squamous carcinoma. The TNM staging is T2, N2, M0, indicating the tumor size and extent of spread to nearby lymph nodes, but no distant metastasis. The tumor cell percentage is 72%. No treatment has been administered yet. The blood specimen is normal.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a mass. The pathology report reveals a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 5.0 cm in the greatest dimension located in the right upper lobe of the lung. The tumor is markedly pleomorphic and high grade, with rare mucin positive cells. The surgical margins are free of tumor, indicating complete resection. No tumor was identified in the two hilar lymph nodes from the lobectomy specimen, or in the removed lymph nodes from stations 11, R4, and 7. The pleura biopsy showed reactive mesothelial cells, fibrosis, and acute and chronic inflammation, but no tumor. The tumor does not appear to invade the bronchus or pleura. The remainder of the lung tissue appears normal with no other identifiable lesions.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe lobectomy for a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 5.3 cm in diameter. The tumor did not involve the bronchial and pleural margins. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the peribronchial, station 5, L10, and station 11 lymph nodes. The tumor was not found to be invading the bronchus, with the closest distance being 1.1 cm. The tumor was 1.4 cm away from the stapled surgical margin. No satellite tumor nodules were present. The remaining lung was red/tan and diffusely aerated with focal areas appearing consolidated. Histologic assessment confirmed the absence of pleural involvement, in situ carcinoma, and lymphovascular or perineural invasion. The non-tumorous lung showed hemosiderin-laden macrophages and post-obstructive changes.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC). The removed tumor was a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.7 cm in diameter, centrally located, and approximately 2.9 cm from the bronchial margin. There was no evidence of angiolymphatic invasion, pleural involvement, or involvement of the bronchial margin. One out of four peribronchial lymph nodes showed metastatic adenocarcinoma, but without extracapsular extension. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the removed R4 and station 11 lymph nodes. The non-tumorous lung tissue showed anthracotic pigment.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy due to a centrally located mass in the right upper lobe of the lung. The mass was identified as an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5 x 2.4 x 2.3 cm. The tumor does not appear to involve the bronchus or invade the pleura, and the surgical margins are negative for carcinoma. Two small pleural nodules were identified, but no neoplasm was found in the bronchial margin. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in 1 out of 5 hilar lymph nodes, while multiple lymph nodes (2 in R4, 1 in the right mainstem bronchus, 1 in R9, and 1 in station 7) were negative for carcinoma. No extracapsular extension of the tumor in the lymph nodes was identified. The non-tumorous lung tissue showed hyalinized granulomata.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy and chest wall resection due to a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 5.5 cm in diameter, located peripherally in the upper portion of the right lung. The tumor extended through the pleura at the site of pleural adhesions, but did not involve the bronchial and final chest wall surgical margins. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the peribronchial lymph nodes, Station 7 lymph node, right middle lobe nodule, or R4 lymph nodes. The non-tumorous lung showed patchy acute bronchopneumonia and a subpleural fibrous plaque. The tumor was mucin and TTF1 positive, and calretinin negative, indicating adenocarcinoma. No angiolymphatic or perineural invasion was identified.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal papillary architecture, measuring 4.5 cm in diameter, morphologically similar to a previous uterine papillary serous carcinoma. The bronchial margin was not involved, but the pleural margin was focally involved. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the biopsied lymph nodes from stations 7, R9, and R10. The tumor directly involved a medium-sized bronchus and was located 1mm from the visceral pleural surface. The tumor was 9mm from the bronchial margin and 1cm from the stapled margin of resection. No satellite tumor nodules were present and the non-tumorous lung parenchyma was unremarkable. Histologically, angiolymphatic invasion was present, but no perineural invasion or in situ carcinoma was identified.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lung, with the greatest dimension measuring 4.6 cm. The tumor extends to the pleura but does not penetrate it, and vascular space invasion is identified within the main tumor mass. Surgical margins are negative for tumor. No tumor is seen in the lymph nodes from stations 9, 10, 7, 5, and 4L. The non-tumorous lung shows emphysema and scattered lymphoid aggregates.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 5.8 cm at its largest dimension. The tumor extends to, but not through, the visceral pleura, with fibrinopurulent and granulation tissue present. Surgical margins are clear of the tumor. There is extensive recent and old hemorrhage in the non-tumorous lung tissue surrounding the tumor. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is found in two out of seven hilar nodes from the lobectomy specimen. No tumor is observed in the mediastinal lymph nodes at stations 5, 9, 7, and 11, with one, two, one, and one nodes examined respectively. These nodes exhibit follicular hyperplasia and hyalinized granulomas. Similarly, no tumor is seen in three lymph nodes from the pulmonary fissure, which also show follicular hyperplasia and hyalinized granulomas.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 5.5 cm, with visceral pleura and lobar bronchus involvement. The tumor has invaded venous, arterial, and lymphatic structures, with a suspicious focus for perineural invasion. Surgical margins are positive for the pleura, bronchus, and vascular structures. Out of 14 lymph nodes biopsied, 10 are positive for metastatic malignancy, with the largest metastasis measuring 1.3 cm. Extracapsular extension of the tumor in the lymph nodes is present. The AJCC pathologic TNM stage is pT2b pN2 pM N/A. Molecular studies for EGFR and KRAS mutations and cytogenetic studies for ALK gene rearrangements have been requested.

The patient, a female with a history of grade 3 ductal breast carcinoma and positive smoking history, presented with a right upper lobe lung mass. A wedge biopsy of the right upper lobe lesion revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, 2.5 cm in diameter, consistent with a lung primary. There was no evidence of pleural invasion and surgical margins were not involved. Further immunohistochemistry showed immunoreactivity for TTF-1 and HER2, with no reactivity for GCDFP or ER, supporting the diagnosis of a lung primary. Special stains were deferred to exclude metastasis. The gross examination of the lung tissue revealed a subpleural hard white/firm mass, 3.5 X 3.0 X 3.0 cm in greatest gross dimensions.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe wedge resection of the lung, revealing a unifocal invasive lung adenocarcinoma of acinar predominant subtype, measuring 3.2 cm with moderate to poorly differentiated histologic grade. No in situ carcinoma, venous, arterial, lymphatic, perineural, or pleural invasion was identified. Surgical margins were negative and no tumor was seen in the examined lymph node (0/1). The non-tumorous lung showed emphysematous changes, multifocal bronchiolar metaplasia, and focal fibrous remodeling. The AJCC pathologic TNM stage is pT2a pN0. A removed Station 4 lymph node showed benign fibroadipose tissue with no tumor. Molecular studies on the tumor are pending. The gross examination of the resected lung revealed a tan, firm mass with central cavitations, 0.4 cm from the parenchymal margin and abutting the pleura.

The patient underwent a wedge resection of the right lung's posterior segment, revealing a subpleural tumor mass measuring 1.5 cm. The tumor was identified as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with a peripheral bronchoalveolar type growth pattern, confirmed by strong TTF1 positivity, indicating a lung primary. The tumor margins were clear, with no evidence of direct extension, large vessel invasion, or lymphatic invasion. A total of 11 lymph nodes were examined from various levels and all were negative for metastatic disease. The right upper lobe, post prior wedge resection, showed no residual tumor, with bronchial and vascular margins clear. Five hilar lymph nodes were found with anthracosis, all negative for metastatic disease. Mild to moderate emphysematous change was noted in the lung parenchyma. The final diagnosis is a peripheral, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the right lung, with no evidence of metastatic disease in the examined lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy for a pre-operative diagnosis of lung cancer. The post-operative diagnosis remains the same. The resected specimen contained a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.0 cm, which invaded the visceral pleura but had uninvolved resection margins. Large vessel invasion was identified, but no lymphatic invasion was noted. No regional lymph nodes were positive for metastasis. An intraparenchymal lymph node with granulomatous inflammation was identified, but stains for AFB and fungal organisms were negative. A secondary lesion was noted, but biopsy site changes were present. A total of 21 lymph nodes were examined from various stations (2R, 4R, Station 7, Station 9), all of which were negative for metastasis. Granulomatous inflammation was also noted in the Station 7 lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a wedge resection of the left upper lobe due to a pre-operative diagnosis of a lung mass. Gross examination revealed a 2.2 x 2.2 x 1.2 cm firm, rubbery nodule within the lung tissue, which was otherwise spongy and tan-pink with no focal lesions. Histological analysis confirmed the presence of a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal visceral pleural invasion. The tumor was classified as pT2, with no definitive identification of vascular invasion. The resection margins were negative for malignancy, indicating successful removal of the tumor. The status of regional lymph nodes and distant metastasis could not be determined (pNX, pMX). Additionally, focal fibrosis was observed.

The patient, identified by name and medical record number, underwent a wedge resection of the left lower and upper lobes due to a pre-operative diagnosis of lung nodules. The gross examination revealed a well-circumscribed firm tan nodule measuring 1.7 cm in diameter in the left lower lobe and a similar firm tan and black nodule measuring 1.8 x 1.5 x 1.5 cm in the left upper lobe. Both nodules were entirely submitted for further examination. Additionally, tissue fragments from levels 4 to 7 were received and submitted in cassettes. The frozen section diagnosis confirmed adenocarcinoma in both lobes, with negative margins.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with lung and breast cancer. The excisional biopsy of the left upper lobe of the lung revealed a well to moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, with a tumor size of 1.5 cm. The tumor exhibited a focal lepidic growth pattern and was graded 1-2 out of 3, with no mitotic activity observed. The pulmonary margin of resection was free of malignancy, and there was no evidence of vascular invasion. The pleura showed elastosis but was negative for malignancy. Immunohistochemical staining was positive for TTF-1, indicating a lung primary, and negative for BRST-2, ER, and PR. The lymph node biopsy at level 5 showed no evidence of malignancy. The overall pathological staging is pTNM Stage T1 N0.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with right upper lobe lung cancer. The gross examination revealed a large tumor mass in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 8 x 7 x 6 cm, with no involvement of the visceral pleural surface. The bronchial margin was free of tumor. Lymph nodes at level 10, R4, and level 7 were also examined and found to be negative for metastatic carcinoma. Microscopic examination confirmed the presence of a poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma. The tumor did not show any signs of direct extension, venous or arterial invasion, or lymphatic invasion. The resection margins were negative. Therefore, the final diagnosis is invasive poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, with no metastasis to the examined lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe wedge resection due to a pulmonary nodule. The resected specimen revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.5 cm in greatest dimension, with no direct extension of the tumor or large vessel invasion identified. The surgical margins were uninvolved. The right lower lobe lobectomy showed no residual malignancy and two lymph nodes were negative for metastatic disease. Four level 12 lymph nodes showed no evidence of metastasis. Seven level 7 lymph nodes and three level 11 lymph nodes were also negative for metastatic disease. No nodes were identified in the level 9 lymph node tissue.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung and multiple lymph nodes due to a pre-operative diagnosis of lung mass and a history of endocarcinoma of the lung. The gross examination revealed a 6.0 X 4.5 X 4.5 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the lung, extending close to the pleural surface and bronchial stump. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in 1 of 4 level 10 lymph nodes and 2 of 3 peribronchial lymph nodes. No evidence of metastasis was found in the level 7 and R4 lymph nodes. The resection margins were uninvolved, and no large vessel invasion was identified, but lymphatic invasion was present. The distant metastasis could not be evaluated from this specimen.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung due to a diagnosed stage I non-small cell carcinoma. The resected specimen weighed 192 grams and measured 12.5 X 8.0 X 4.5 cm. A moderately well circumscribed, rubbery tan white lesion measuring 4.5 X 3.8 X 2.7 cm was identified, approaching the pleural surface within less than 0.1 cm. Histologically, the tumor was identified as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. The stapled resection margin was free of tumor. There was no evidence of tumor extension into the pleura, large vessel invasion, or lymphatic invasion. Biopsies of the 2R and 4R fat pads and level 7 lymph node were negative for malignancy. Other findings included emphysematous blebs and intraalveolar histiocytes with hemosiderin, but no infectious organisms were identified. The final diagnosis is invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, stage pT2a, with no lymph node involvement or distant metastasis.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a moderately to poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.7 x 2.4 x 2.4 cm. The tumor invaded the visceral pleura but the bronchial and pulmonary resection margins were negative for malignancy. No vascular invasion was observed. A single peribronchial lymph node was examined and found to be free of malignancy. The non-tumorous lung showed bronchiolitis obliterans, endogenous lipoid pneumonia, and acute bronchopneumonia. A nodule in the right middle lobe showed elastosis and chronic inflammation but was negative for malignancy. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 11, 4R, 2R fat pad, and level 7 all showed no evidence of malignancy. The overall staging of the tumor is pTNM Stage: T2 N0.

The patient has been diagnosed with non-small cell lung cancer, specifically poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The primary tumor measures 5.5 cm and is located within less than 0.2 cm of the bronchial margin of excision. The tumor shows multifocal areas of extension up to and focally into the pleura, with vessel invasion present. Metastatic carcinoma is identified in a pericardial reflection node, indicating regional lymph node involvement. However, no metastasis is found in lymph nodes at levels 11, 4R, 2R, and 9. Additionally, the left lower and upper lobes show poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 1.7 cm and 1.8 cm respectively, with no evidence of large vessel or lymphatic invasion. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is found in one lymph node at level 5, measuring 1.5 cm. No metastasis is found in lymph nodes at levels 7 and 4.

The patient's pathology report indicates a poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 2.5 cm with a tumor grade of 3 out of 3 and a mitotic index of 1 mitoses/10 HPF's. The bronchial and pulmonary resection margins, as well as the pleura, are negative for malignancy, with no vascular invasion observed. The attached lymph nodes also show no evidence of malignancy. The non-tumorous lung exhibits mild to moderate emphysema. Biopsies from lymph node levels 10, 7, 3, and R4 all show no evidence of malignancy. The overall pTNM staging is T1b N0.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a right upper lobe lung mass. Pathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.2 cm, invading and ulcerating bronchial tissue. All margins and pleural surfaces were negative for tumor. Two additional lymph nodes were present and negative for metastatic disease. Dissections of level 10, R4, and level 7 lymph nodes on the right side showed multiple reactive lymph nodes with anthracotic pigmentation, all negative for metastatic disease. No distant metastasis could be assessed. Two nonspecific small areas of fibrosis were noted in a subpleural location.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy due to a lung mass. Histopathological examination revealed a moderate to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, confined to the lung, measuring maximally 2.2 cm in size. The tumor did not involve the visceral pleural surface and there was no evidence of direct extension of the tumor. Bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. No venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion was observed. Seven bronchial lymph nodes and all sampled mediastinal lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. Resected lymph nodes at levels 1, 4, 5, 7, and 9 were also negative for malignancy. Distant metastasis could not be assessed.

The patient underwent a wedge resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, revealing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.5 cm, extending to the staple line. No evidence of metastasis was found in the resected level 10 and R-4 lymph nodes, with 6 and 12 nodes examined respectively. A lobectomy of the right lobe of the lung showed residual adenocarcinoma of 1.5 cm at the staple line, with no metastasis in 6 examined lymph nodes. The resected level 7 lymph node also showed no evidence of metastasis in three examined nodes. The margins of resection were uninvolved and there was no evidence of large vessel or lymphatic invasion.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with lung carcinoma. Upon examination of the excised specimens, the right upper lobe of the lung showed an invasive, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 5 cm, which extended to the pleural surface. The tumor was found to be more than 3.8 cm from the bronchial stump margin and showed vessel invasion. Metastatic carcinoma was identified in one of four hilar lymph nodes and two of 10 R4 lymph nodes, with the largest metastasis measuring 0.7 cm and showing extracapsular extension. All other lymph nodes examined, including those from level 3, level 10, middle lobe, and subcarinal, were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The margins of resection were negative for tumor. No distant metastasis was identified.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy due to poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor, measuring 6.8 cm, was confined to the lung (pT2b) and did not extend beyond the visceral pleural surface. The bronchial and vascular margins of resection were free of tumor. Lymphovascular space invasion and medium-sized venous invasion by the tumor were observed. Post-obstructive pneumonitis with pulmonary edema was also present. Eight peribronchial and perihilar lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma (0/8). However, one of the four resected level 7 lymph nodes contained metastatic carcinoma (1/4). The 4R and 2R lymph nodes were negative for tumor (pN2). A benign mediastinal cyst was also identified. The superior vein stump was free of malignancy.

The patient presented with a lung mass. Upon examination, multiple lymph nodes (R4, right, level 10, and level 7) were biopsied and found to be negative for malignancy. The right lower lobe of the lung was resected and found to contain a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5 cm, with a mitotic index of 26 mitoses/10 HPFs. The pulmonary margin of resection, pleura, and vascular invasion were all negative for malignancy. The non-tumorous lung showed benign reactive changes. The pathological staging is pTNM Stage: T2a N0.

The patient underwent a resection of the left upper lobe of the lung due to a lung lesion. The gross examination revealed a single stapled wedge biopsy of lung measuring 9.5 X 6.5 X 5 cm, with a 3.2 X 2.2 X 1.8 cm tan rubbery mass adjacent to the pleural surface. Microscopic examination showed a markedly atypical glandular proliferation with atypical epithelioid cells characterized by ample cytoplasm, irregular nuclei, and prominent nucleoli. These cells were growing in a glandular pattern and focally appeared to grow along alveolar septa. There was cellular crowding with nuclear overlap and focal pseudostratification. These morphologic features are supportive of a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma. The compact architecture and fibrosis suggest an invasive process. Visceral pleural invasion is uncertain and requires further assessment with an elastic stain. The diagnosis is invasive well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 3.2 cm, with negative margins.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for lung cancer. The gross examination of the right upper lobe revealed a 2 cm adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated, located within the inferior portion of the specimen, with no extension to the pleura or involvement of the large bronchi (pT1a). The tumor invades the pulmonary parenchyma, with venous and lymphatic invasion observed. Resection margins were negative for tumor. Two lymph nodes from the hilar region were negative for metastatic tumor. Additional lymph nodes from R4 and level 7 were also negative for metastatic tumor. An area of intraparenchymal pulmonary hemorrhage was noted, possibly secondary to a pulmonary embolus, but no organized thromboembolus was identified adjacent to the hemorrhage. No intraparenchymal metastasis was identified.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with a lung nodule. Upon examination of the resected right upper lobe, a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2 cm was identified. The bronchial resection margin and pleura were negative for malignancy, and there was no evidence of vascular invasion. Emphysema was noted in the non-tumorous lung. Lymph nodes from levels X, XI, XII, 2R, 4R, VII, and VIII were biopsied and all were negative for malignancy. The overall pathological staging is pTNM Stage T1.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a lung lesion, which was diagnosed as a well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma measuring 21 cm in the left lower lobe. The tumor did not extend to the bronchial margin and the pleura was uninvolved. There was no evidence of metastasis in the examined lymph nodes: one from level 9, three from level 10, two from level 11, and four from level 5. The surgical margins were clear. The histological examination suggested a bronchoalveolar carcinoma with multiple foci of invasion. Distant metastasis could not be evaluated from this specimen.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with lung cancer. Upon examination of the right middle lobe, right upper lobe, 2R fat pad, 4R, and right lower lobe wedge resection, the following findings were made: The right middle lobe showed two fibrotic pleural-based nodules with no malignancy identified. The right upper lobe lobectomy revealed a moderately to poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.0 cm in greatest dimension, approaching but not involving the visceral pleura or bronchus, with no angiolymphatic invasion and negative resection margins. The 2R fat pad biopsy showed benign fibroadipose tissue with a focal lymphoid aggregate, with no definitive lymph nodes or malignancy identified. The 4R sample contained benign fibrous tissue with no lymph nodes identified. The right lower lobe wedge resection showed a calcified fibrotic nodule with no malignancy identified. Other findings included emphysematous changes, intraalveolar hemorrhage, and calcified nodules.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with lung carcinoma. Upon examination of the lobectomy specimen from the left lower lobe, a well-circumscribed, mucinous adenocarcinoma of 3 cm in greatest dimension was identified, with no involvement of the pleura or a large stem bronchus (pT1b). The vascular and bronchial resection margins were negative for tumor. No lymphovascular space invasion was identified. A single lymph node was dissected from the left lower lobe and was negative for metastatic tumor. Additional lymph nodes from level 10, the left upper lobe, and the subcarinal region were also negative for metastatic tumor (pN0). Distant metastasis could not be evaluated (pMx). The background pulmonary parenchyma was relatively unremarkable. The lymph nodes showed prominent anthracosis and some histiocytes associated with the anthracosis.

The patient's biopsy results indicate no evidence of malignancy in lymph nodes at levels XI, IX, VIII, and V, with each node consisting of multiple pieces of soft tissue. However, metastatic carcinoma is present in one of two lymph nodes at level VII, measuring 1.8 mm in greatest dimension. The left lower lobe of the lung, weighing 193 grams and measuring 17 x 11.5 x 3.5 cm, shows a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, with a tumor size of 2 cm. The bronchial resection margin, pulmonary margin of resection, and pleura are all negative for malignancy, with no vascular invasion or attached lymph nodes observed. The pTNM stage is T1 N2, and there is a focal endogenous lipoid pneumonia in the non-tumorous lung.

The patient underwent a biopsy of multiple lymph nodes and a resection of the right lung lobe. The R4 and level 7 lymph nodes, as well as the level 10 lymph node, showed no evidence of malignancy. The right lung lobe presented a moderately well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 4 cm with a mitotic index of 12 mitoses/10 HPFs. The bronchial resection margin, pulmonary margin of resection, and pleura were all negative for malignancy, with no vascular invasion observed. The attached peribronchial lymph node also showed no evidence of malignancy. The overall pTNM stage is T2a. The non-tumorous lung was unremarkable.

The patient was preoperatively diagnosed with lung cancer, which was confirmed postoperatively. The excised specimens from the right hilar lymph node, station 4R hilar lymph node, right upper lobe, and station 7 lymph node were examined. The right upper lobe contained a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with a prominent bronchioalveolar growth pattern, measuring 2 cm in greatest dimension and limited to the lung (pT1). The resection margins were negative and no vessel invasion was identified. The lymph nodes showed changes consistent with Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL), confirmed with immunohistochemical stains for CD5, CD20, and CD23. However, all lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. No distant metastasis was identified (pMx).

The patient underwent a left upper lobe wedge resection for lung cancer. The resected specimen weighed 78 grams and measured 15 X 5.5 X 4 cm with a stapled margin of 15 cm. A 1 X 1 cm umbilication was noted in the pleura. Upon sectioning, a 3.5 X 2.5 X 2.4 cm pink tan tumor was identified, showing fibrous stippling and contiguous within the pleural umbilication. The tumor was located 1.5 cm from the sacral margin. The rest of the lung tissue appeared normal. Histologically, the tumor was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5 cm in maximum dimension, limited to the lung parenchyma, and invading into the pleura (pT2). The resection margins were negative and vascular invasion was present. The status of regional lymph nodes and distant metastasis could not be determined (pNX, pMX). A small piece of tissue from the tumor and normal tissue was submitted for the tumor bank.

The patient presented with a lung mass. Upon examination, a nodular tumor mass was found in the lingula of the lung, measuring 2 X 1.5 X 1.3 cm, with no involvement of the visceral pleural surface. The tumor is identified as a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The resection margins are clear of tumor, and there is no evidence of direct tumor extension, large vessel invasion, or lymphatic invasion. The level 5, 7, and 10 mediastinal lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. Distant metastasis could not be assessed. Other findings include emphysematous bullae and a pleural based fibrous scar with old hemorrhage.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy for lung cancer. The resected lung contained two lesions, the larger measuring 6 X 5 X 4 cm and the smaller 3 X 2 X 1.5 cm, both of which were identified as moderate to poorly differentiated adenocarcinomas. The bronchial and vascular margins of resection were free of tumor, as was the visceral pleural surface. No evidence of venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion was found. Two out of six peribronchial lymph nodes contained metastatic adenocarcinoma, while all mediastinal lymph nodes were negative. The R4, L4, level 10, level 5, subcarinal, and level 6 lymph nodes were all negative for malignancy. The possibility of the two lung lesions representing separate primary tumors or intrapulmonary metastasis from the main lung tumor could not be determined from the histology.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, revealing an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.9 cm. The bronchial and vascular margins of resection were free of tumor, and there was no direct extension of the tumor. Lymphovascular invasion was present. Examination of 11 hilar lymph nodes and resected lymph nodes from levels II, V, VI, and VII showed no metastatic carcinoma. The primary tumor was confined to the lung (pT1b), with no venous or arterial large vessel invasion. Lymphatic small vessel invasion was positive. All hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma (pN0). Distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMx). The gross description of the lung lobe and lymph nodes revealed no additional significant findings.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.5 cm in greatest dimension. The surgical margins were uninvolved and there was no evidence of metastasis in the examined lymph nodes (0/5 in regional nodes, 0/3 in R4 nodes, and 0/1 in Level VII node). The tumor did not show any signs of direct extension, large vessel invasion, or small vessel invasion. The remaining lung parenchyma appeared normal. The gross examination of the resected specimen confirmed these findings. The final pathological staging is pT2 pN0 pNX.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing a subpleural, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 3.5 cm in maximum dimension, with arterial invasion but negative bronchial and vascular margins. The tumor is strongly positive for TT F 1, indicating a lung primary. Lymph nodes from levels II, VII, and R4 were excised and found to have anthracosis but were negative for metastatic disease. The primary tumor is classified as pT2a, with negative margins of resection, no direct extension of the tumor, negative venous and lymphatic invasion, but positive arterial invasion. Regional lymph nodes are classified as pN0, indicating no metastatic disease. Distant metastasis cannot be assessed. No other significant findings were noted. The patient has a history of lung and endometrial cancer.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung due to a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.8 cm, which involved the lobar bronchus (pT2a). The bronchial and vascular resection margins, as well as the pleural surface, were all negative for malignancy. Five lymph nodes were evaluated, including two bronchial nodes and one each from levels X, V, and VII, all of which were negative for malignancy. The tumor cells stained strongly positive for cytokeratin 7 and TT F1, with focal mucicarmine positive intracytoplasmic vacuoles, but were completely negative for CK 5/6 and showed less than 50% moderate staining with p63. No venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion was identified. Distant metastasis was not evaluated. Other findings included focal pulmonary hemorrhage, anthracosis, and emphysema.

The patient presents with a right lung mass, identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 15 cm in greatest dimension, with no direct extension of the tumor identified. The surgical margins are uninvolved. There is suspicion of venous, arterial, and lymphatic invasion. However, no evidence of metastasis is found in the examined lymph nodes from levels 4, 7, 9, 11, and 12, and the sixth rib is unremarkable. Distant metastasis cannot be evaluated from this specimen.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy due to the presence of an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.3 cm, confined to the lung and not involving the visceral pleural surface. One of two peribronchial lymph nodes showed metastatic carcinoma. Large venous vessel and lymphatic vessel invasion by the tumor was observed. Emphysematous changes and focal distal infarction were also noted. Resected lymph nodes at levels 3, 4, 7, and 10 were all negative for malignancy.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy for a lung mass, which was identified as a moderate to poorly-differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.5 cm and confined to the lung without visceral pleural involvement. The bronchial margin of resection was free of tumor. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one of seven peribronchial lymph nodes. All other lymph nodes at levels 5, 7, 9, 10, and 11 were negative for malignancy. The patient also exhibited subpleural fibrosis and focal emphysematous changes.

The patient underwent an excision of the right upper and middle lobes of the lung due to a pre-operative diagnosis of a lung mass. The excised lung tissue weighed 197 gm and measured 19 X 11.8 X 3.5 cm. A 3.2 X 2.8 X 2.2 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma was identified within the middle lobe, extending to within 1 cm from the bronchial stump but not involving the pleura. The tumor was classified as pT2a, with no identified pleural invasion, direct extension, or definitive vascular invasion. The resection margins were negative for tumor. Lymph nodes from the hilar region, as well as separately submitted lymph nodes from levels 7, R4, and R2, were all negative for malignancy. Emphysematous changes with bleb formation, bronchiolar metaplasia, and subpleural fibrosis were also noted in the upper lobe.

The patient presented with a cavitary left upper lobe lung lesion. Upon examination, a 2.5 X 2.0 X 1.5 cm mass lesion was identified in the left upper lobectomy specimen, characterized by an irregular border and a gray-white cut surface with incorporated anthrocotic pigment. The diagnosis is a moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.5 cm in greatest dimension, with no direct extension of the tumor or venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion identified. The margins of resection were negative. Five regional lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for malignancy. The carcinoma appears to invade up toward the pleural surface, but does not directly involve the visceral pleura. The excision margins were negative and angiolymphatic invasion was not identified. Additionally, biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 5, 8, 11, and the 9L fat pad were all negative for malignancy. No definite lymph node was identified at level 7, but no malignancy was found in the lymphoid and fibrous connective tissue.

The patient underwent a biopsy of lymph nodes at levels VII and 4, and a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung. The lymph nodes were found to be negative for malignancy. However, the right upper lobe of the lung showed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, with a histologic grade of 3 and a mitotic index of 6 mitoses/10 HPFs. The tumor measured 5 X 3.5 X 3.2 cm. The bronchial resection margin and pleura were negative for malignancy, and there was no vascular invasion. The attached lymph node was also negative for malignancy. The pTNM stage of the tumor was T2a. Non-tumorous lung tissue was unremarkable. Immunohistochemical staining showed TTF-1 positivity and CK5/6 and p63 negativity. The gross examination of the right upper lobe revealed a 305 g lung lobe with a tumor near the apex, measuring 3.5 by 3.2 by (1.5+2 +1.5) cm. The remainder of the lung tissue was grossly unremarkable.

The patient underwent an en bloc resection of the right upper lobe of the lung and adjacent chest wall. The final pathology report reveals an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma extending into the soft tissues of the chest wall. The radial, vascular, and bronchial margins of resection are free of tumor. Four hilar lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. Nonnecrotizing granulomatous lymphadenitis was found in multiple lymph nodes, with special stains for acid-fast and fungal organisms being negative. The third and fourth ribs' medial margins were negative for malignancy. Immunohistochemistry showed positive staining for CEA and TTF-1, and negative for CK 5/6 and P63, indicative of adenocarcinoma. The tumor has extended from the lung through the chest wall into the soft tissue adjacent to ribs (pT3), with venous invasion present but no arterial or lymphatic invasion. All sampled lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for lung cancer. The final pathology report reveals an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.6 cm in diameter and extending into the visceral pleural surface (pT2a). The bronchial and vascular margins of resection are free of tumor, indicating a successful resection. There is no evidence of venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion. All sampled mediastinal lymph nodes, including levels XI, X, R II, R IV, and VII, are negative for metastatic carcinoma (pN0). Distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMx). The gross description of the resected tissues and lymph nodes is provided in detail.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.9 cm with uninvolved surgical margins. No evidence of metastatic disease was found in the 2 examined lymph nodes. A portion of the lower lobe was also resected and showed no signs of malignancy. Additionally, resected level 10, R4, and level 7 lymph nodes showed no evidence of metastasis in a total of 10 lymph nodes. The primary tumor is classified as pT2 with negative margins of resection and no identified direct extension, venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion. Regional lymph nodes are negative (pN0) and distant metastasis cannot be evaluated from this specimen (pMX). The lower lobe showed atelectasis and focal hemorrhage but no malignancy. The gross examination of the right upper lobe revealed a rubbery tan-white tumor mass extending to within 0.3 cm of the inked pleural surface. The remaining parenchyma was spongiform tan-pink-red with no additional mass lesion or abnormality.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with a tumor size of 3.7 cm. The tumor is classified as T2a N0 according to the pTNM staging system. The bronchial resection margin, pulmonary margin of resection, pleura, and attached lymph nodes are all negative for malignancy, indicating no spread of the cancer to these areas. Vascular invasion is absent. The non-tumorous lung shows signs of emphysema. Immunohistochemical staining confirms the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma, with TTF-1 positive, CK5/6 negative, and p63 weakly positive. Biopsies of lymph nodes at R4, level X, and level VII show no evidence of malignancy.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe excision due to a lung mass. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.3 cm at its largest dimension, without definitive pleural invasion (pT2a). There was no evidence of tumor at the bronchial and vascular resection margins or in the hilar lymph nodes. Additionally, lymph nodes from levels 11, 4R, 8, 7, and 2R were excised and found to be negative for tumor. A minor component of squamous cell carcinoma may be present, but it is not a significant part of the tumor. Focal lymphatic invasion is suspected. There are no signs of distant metastasis (pM). Inflammatory changes were observed within the carcinoma.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 5.5 cm, with minimal extension into the pleura and presence in a large vessel. Two out of eight hilar lymph nodes show metastatic carcinoma, with one showing probable direct extension. The tumor is approximately 4 mm from the bronchial margin, with a negative vascular margin. Other excised lymph nodes from levels X, VII, and V are negative for metastatic carcinoma. The status of distant metastasis is undetermined (pMX). The tumor is classified as pT2b and pN1.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, with biopsy of multiple lymph nodes and 2R fat. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the posterior apical segment of the right upper lobe, with a tumor size of 1 cm. The bronchial resection margin, pulmonary margin of resection, pleura, and attached lymph nodes were all negative for malignancy, indicating no evidence of cancer spread. The lymph nodes from levels XI, VII, and X, as well as the 2R fat, were also negative for malignancy. Non-tumorous lung showed signs of emphysema and subpleural elastosis. The overall pTNM stage is T1.

The patient underwent a resection of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.5 cm with eosinophilic cytoplasm and a mitotic index of 17 mitoses/10 HPF. There were histologic features suggestive of vascular invasion. The bronchial resection margin and pleura were negative for malignancy. Additionally, emphysema was noted in the non-tumorous lung. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 4L, VII, IX, V, XI, and XII were all negative for malignancy, as were 10 hilar lymph nodes. The pTNM stage is T1. The patient has a history of tobacco and alcohol abuse. The gross examination of the resected lung lobe showed a palpable mass with overlying pleural puckering, 5.5 cm from the bronchial margin. The cut section of the mass was white and measured 2.5 cm in diameter. An area of red discoloration was noted on one side of the specimen, measuring 1.7 cm in greatest dimension.

The patient underwent an excisional biopsy of the right lower lobe of the lung, which revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, with a histologic grade of 2 and a tumor size of 1.8 cm. The carcinoma was present near the staple line, however, the reexcision of the staple line showed no signs of malignancy. The pleura was also negative for malignancy. There were focal features suggestive of vascular invasion, leading to a pTNM stage of T1a. The gross examination of the specimen showed a firm white mass measuring 1.7 cm in greatest dimension, with a distorted pleural surface over the tumor. The reexcision of the staple line consisted of lung tissue measuring 8 by 1.8 by 1 cm, which was also negative for malignancy.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma of the right lower lung, exhibiting bronchioloalveolar and papillary features. Additional findings include panacinar emphysematous changes and intrapulmonary hemorrhage. A single granuloma was identified in a hilar lymph node. Three pulmonary lymph nodes and bronchial and vascular margins were examined and found to be free of tumor. Special stains for fungi and acid-fast bacilli were negative.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the lung, which revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. The surgical margins were clear of the tumor, indicating successful removal. However, there was evidence of focal vascular invasion within the tumor. The bronchial margin was negative, suggesting no spread of the cancer to the bronchus. Three bronchopulmonary nodes from the specimen were also negative for cancer. A rib was also removed during the lobectomy and was found to be free of tumor. Additionally, a biopsy of the innominate lymph node and associated soft tissue showed no presence of tumor.

The patient has a moderately well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the left lung, lower lobe, measuring 3 cm in greatest dimension with focal bronchioloalveolar features. The carcinoma closely approaches but does not involve the pleura. A total of sixteen lymph nodes were examined and all were negative for tumor involvement. Additionally, all resection margins were free of tumor. Excised lymph nodes from levels 5, 7, and 9 were also negative for tumor.

The patient has metastatic adenocarcinoma, evidenced by the presence of cancerous cells in the anterior mediastinal lymph node and aortic arch lymph node, with extension into perinodal soft tissue. Additionally, a moderate to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma was found in the left upper lobe of the lung, with extensive lymphatic invasion and metastasis to one lymph node. However, the bronchial and vascular margins of resection were found to be tumor-free.

The patient has a moderately-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma of the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.5 cm, with necrotic foci and extension to the pleura. The bronchial and vascular margins are free of tumor. Metastatic carcinoma is present in two out of four regional lymph nodes. The uninvolved lung tissue exhibits hemorrhage, extensive remodeling, subpleural scarring, and acute and chronic inflammation. Additionally, one lymph node from the AP window resection is positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma.

The patient has been diagnosed with infiltrating moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchioloalveolar features in the upper lobe of the right lung, extending into the pleura. The tumor measures 2.8 cm. However, five examined hilar lymph nodes and the bronchial and vascular lung margins are free of tumor. The pathologic stage of the carcinoma is pT2pN0pMX, corresponding to Stage I. Non-neoplastic findings include congestion, edema, and focal hemorrhage.

The patient has undergone a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 5.5 cm at its largest dimension, infiltrating through the visceral pleura. Metastatic carcinoma is present in one out of six examined lymph nodes. Both bronchial and vascular margins are free of tumor. A right upper lobe wedge resection shows a cavitary fibrotic cyst colonized by fungal forms consistent with Aspergillus, but no tumor presence. Another right upper lobe wedge resection reveals a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 1.5 cm.

The excised lymph nodes from AP Window, Station 5, Station 7, Periaortic tissue, and L11 are all negative for tumor, indicating no presence of cancer. The AP Window lymph node exhibits hyalinized inactive granulomas. The excised rib is unremarkable with no notable abnormalities. The lymph nodes from Station 5 and L11, along with their associated adipose tissue, show no signs of tumor. The tissue from Station 7 is characterized by fibroadipose and fibrous connective tissue, again with no evidence of tumor.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 4.0 cm size, which has invaded into the bronchus of the right lung. A right pneumonectomy was performed and the tumor was found to be infiltrating moderately. The neural, bronchial, and vascular margins are free from tumor. Metastatic carcinoma was found in three out of nine examined hilar lymph nodes. There is also evidence of pleural scarring. Two lymph nodes from the R4 region and one from the R9 region, along with their associated fibroadipose tissue, were excised and found to be negative for tumor.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 5 cm in the left upper lobe of the lung, exhibiting characteristics of papillary adenocarcinoma of the lung with a peripheral bronchioloalveolar component. The carcinoma is in close proximity to, but does not involve the pleura, and all margins, including bronchial and vascular, are tumor-free. There is evidence of focal vascular invasion. The surrounding lung tissue displays typical pneumocyte hyperplasia. Metastatic carcinoma is present in one lymph node. However, the excised R4 and Station 7 lymph nodes, along with their associated fibroadipose tissue, are negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right middle lobe. The histological examination revealed an adenocarcinoma, not otherwise specified (NOS), located in the right middle lobe. The tumor's greatest dimension was measured to be 2.0 cm.

The final pathological examination reveals that the excised lymph nodes from stations 5, R11, and L8, along with their associated fibroadipose tissues, are all negative for tumor presence. Additionally, the left upper lobe of the lung, which was subjected to lobectomy, was also examined.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed an adenocarcinoma with mucinous features, moderately differentiated (G2), with a greatest dimension of 5.0cm. The tumor invades the visceral pleura and shows lymphatic invasion, but no venous or arterial invasion. Metastatic carcinoma was found in 1 of 11 lymph nodes. The margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. Additionally, non-caseating granulomas were found in the uninvolved lung, with negative fungal and acid fast bacteria stains. KRAS and EGFR mutation analyses were performed and no mutations were detected. Excised lymph nodes from stations 5, 6, and 7 were negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, solid type with clear cell change, measuring 7.5 cm in greatest dimension. The tumor extends subpleurally but does not involve the pleural surface. The tumor is classified as pT3, indicating a size greater than 7 cm or invasion into the chest wall, diaphragm, mediastinal pleura, or parietal pericardium, or involvement of the main bronchus less than 2 cm from the carina or associated with total atelectasis or a separate tumor nodule in the same lobe. All 17 lymph nodes examined, including those from stations R4, L4, 1, 10R, and 7, were negative for tumor. There was no evidence of venous/arterial (large vessel) or lymphatic (small vessel) invasion. The margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the nearest margin being 4.0 cm (bronchial margin). Immunohistochemistry showed the tumor cells to be TTF-I (diffuse) and Napsin-A (variable) positive. An immunostain for p63 showed patchy, variable staining of the tumor cells. EGFR and KRAS mutation analysis were negative. The background lung showed emphysematous changes and organizing lung injury (fibroblast foci) adjacent to the tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a mixed acinar and bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5cm in greatest dimension. The tumor is moderately to poorly differentiated, with the poorly differentiated component representing less than half of the tumor. Metastatic carcinoma was found in 3 out of 18 lymph nodes. No direct tumor extension was identified and the margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The extent of invasion is classified as pT2a and pN1 according to the 7th Edition of AJCC. Large vessel and small vessel invasion are indeterminate. Additional findings include emphysematous changes with subpleural bulla formation. KRAS mutation analysis was positive, indicating a mutation in either codon 12 or 13 of the KRAS gene, thus EGFR testing is not required.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a focal papillary component in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 4.0 cm (pT2a). Metastatic carcinoma is present in 6 out of 11 lymph nodes, including one subcarinal lymph node (pN2). The tumor margins are clear of invasive carcinoma, with the nearest margin being 4.0 mm away. Large vessel invasion is absent, while small vessel invasion is indeterminate. Emphysematous changes are also noted. Two lymph nodes from station 5 are tumor-free, while one out of two lymph nodes from station 7 shows metastatic carcinoma. The tumor cells are strongly positive for Napsin-A and TTF-1, weakly positive for p63, and negative for CK 5/6, supporting the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma. No mutations were detected in the EGFR and KRAS genes.

The patient presents with hyperplastic lymph nodes and metastatic carcinoma. The excised lymph nodes at levels 7 and 12 show hyperplasia but no metastatic carcinoma. However, the lymph node at R4 exhibits metastatic poorly differentiated carcinoma with capsular penetration. The right upper lobectomy reveals a poorly differentiated tumor of 1.7 cm with metastatic adenocarcinoma to a 2 cm peribronchial lymph node. Angiolymphatic invasion is present, but the margins are uninvolved. There is no evidence of obstructive pneumonia. The anterior mediastinal mass shows metastatic poorly differentiated carcinoma. The lymph node at R/1 is hyperplastic with pending acid-fast and fungal stains. The patient's history of breast carcinoma is noted, but the positive TTF-1 immunohistochemical stain on the lung tumor biopsy suggests a pulmonary primary, excluding a breast primary carcinoma. The AJCC staging is pT1N2MX, stage TITA.

The patient underwent a right middle lobe lung resection and lymph node biopsies, revealing a unifocal, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 4.5 cm. The carcinoma was present at the pulmonary wedge resection margin and extended into the pericardium. Bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by carcinoma, and no lymphovascular invasion was identified. No metastatic carcinoma was found in the eight lymph nodes examined. The tumor was staged as pT3 based on pericardial involvement. Further clinical correlation is necessary to establish whether the tumor in the pericardium is from direct extension.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, which revealed a 2.3 cm adenocarcinoma, 70% acinar and 30% solid, poorly differentiated (G3). Metastatic carcinoma was found in 1 of 11 lymph nodes. The tumor was classified as pT1b, indicating a size greater than 2 cm but less than 3 cm, and pN1, indicating metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial, hilar, or intrapulmonary nodes. Distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMx). The surgical margins were clear of invasive carcinoma, and there was no evidence of venous/arterial (large vessel) invasion. Lymphatic (small vessel) invasion was indeterminate. Excised lymph nodes from stations L8, 6, 7, and L10 were negative for tumor. Molecular analysis revealed a .22352249del .E746 A750del mutation in Exon 19 of the EGFR gene, suggesting potential responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies for non-small-cell lung cancer. ALK FISH analysis was negative, showing no evidence of rearrangement of the ALK gene.
