The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a lung mass. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 1.7 cm, which did not invade the pleura. Bronchial and vascular margins, as well as two hilar lymph nodes, were negative for tumor. Two hyalinized pleural plaques were found in the non-neoplastic lung. Excised lymph nodes from regions R4 and R7 were also negative for tumor. The pathologic stage is T1NoMx. Additionally, a minute focus of adenocarcinoma of the prostate, Gleason grade 3+3=6, was identified. Immunoperoxidase staining for high molecular weight cytokeratin confirmed the absence of basal cells in the atypical glands, supporting the diagnosis of carcinoma.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, confirmed by positive TTF-1 and CK7 immunostains and negative CK20, S-100, and calretinin. The tumor measures 3.0 cm in its greatest dimension and is poorly differentiated (G3). Metastatic carcinoma is present in one out of thirteen lymph nodes examined. The primary tumor is classified as pT2, indicating a size of 3 cm or greater. Regional lymph nodes show metastasis (pN1), specifically in ipsilateral peribronchial, hilar, or intrapulmonary nodes. The status of distant metastasis cannot be assessed (pMx). The surgical margins are clear of invasive carcinoma. Both venous and lymphatic invasion are present. Examination of excised lymph nodes from various stations (R-4, 7, lower R-4, R-11) and a pleural plaque showed no evidence of tumor. The patient's clinical history includes lung cancer.

The patient underwent a wedge resection and completion lobectomy of the left upper lobe, revealing a 3.0 cm adenocarcinoma. The tumor was moderately differentiated (G2) and showed direct extension to the visceral pleura. Metastatic carcinoma was found in 2 out of 17 lymph nodes, indicating regional lymph node involvement (pN2). The tumor's distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMX). The surgical margins were clear of invasive carcinoma, but venous/arterial and lymphatic invasion were indeterminate. Additional findings included respiratory bronchiolitis. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one lymph node at level 10 and one out of five lymph nodes at L4. All other excised lymph nodes were negative for tumor.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the right lung, invading through the pleura into the bone and soft tissues of the chest wall, measuring 7.5 cm. The tumor is within 1 mm of the fascial resection plane. The bronchial margin and chest wall soft tissue margins are negative for tumor. Five peribronchial lymph nodes are negative for metastatic carcinoma, but show scattered hyalinized granulomas. The pathologic stage is T3 N0 MX. Additionally, multiple benign lymph nodes were identified in soft tissue samples "R4", "R10", "R11", and "Station 7", some of which also show scattered hyalinized granulomas. The diagnosis remains unchanged after amendment to clarify the status of the margins.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a 2 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with extensive necrosis. All surgical resection margins including pleural, bronchial, and vascular were found to be negative for tumor. The surrounding lung parenchyma exhibited mild emphysematous changes. Additionally, one lymph node each from R-10, Station 7, and R-4 were excised and found to be negative for tumor. Excised pleural nodules showed dense fibrous tissue with focal acute and chronic inflammation, but were also negative for tumor. The pathologic stage is pT1 N0 MX. The clinical history indicates a right lung mass. Gross examination of the right upper lobe revealed a firm, non-puckered, and normal appearing pleura overlying a gray-white and gritty mass. The mass was well-defined, freely movable, and located 0.6 cm from the pleura surface without apparent bronchus involvement. The remaining lung was pink-red with focal hemorrhage and crepitant. No hilar lymph nodes were present in the specimen.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy due to a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.2 cm, located in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor did not invade the pleura or any vascular structures, and all surgical margins were clear of tumor cells. The pathologic stage is T1N0MX. Two lymph nodes from level 7 and one from 4R, along with associated fibroadipose tissue, were examined and found to be negative for tumor. Immunohistochemical studies confirmed the primary lung origin of the tumor, with tumor cells being immunoreactive for TTF-1 and non-immunoreactive for estrogen receptor, progesterone receptor, and gross cystic disease fluid protein. The gross examination of the lung revealed a peripheral tumor with distinct pleura puckering, and no tumor involvement in the bronchial segments or vascular vessels. The non-neoplastic lung appeared unremarkable. No lymph nodes were found in the hilar area.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a 2.5 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with papillary features. The tumor was found adjacent to the visceral pleura but did not invade it. The surrounding lung tissue showed signs of centrilobular emphysema and several foci of atypical alveolar hyperplasia. All surgical margins, including bronchial, vascular, and stapled parenchymal, were negative for tumor presence. The pathologic stage is T1N0MX. Additionally, six lymph nodes from station 5 and one lymph node from station 7 were dissected and found to be negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy, revealing two separate non-contiguous foci of infiltrating moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.2 cm and 1.0 cm respectively. The tumor did not extend to the pleural surface, and bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were all negative for tumor. Six hilar lymph nodes were also negative for tumor, resulting in a pathologic stage of pT2N0Mx, Stage I. Acute and organizing bronchopneumonia was observed in the area surrounding the tumor, along with emphysematous changes and focal peripheral bulla formation. Two lymph nodes from stations R-4 and 7 were biopsied and found to be negative for tumor. The clinical history indicates non-small cell carcinoma of the lung.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lung's upper lobe, which revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3 cm. The infiltrating carcinoma extends to within 1 mm of the inked pleural margin, but the margin is microscopically negative. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins of resection are also negative for tumor. Eight hilar lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for tumor. Non-neoplastic lung tissue showed signs of centrilobular emphysema and dust macules. The pathologic stage is T1N0MX. An excision of a lymph node at station 5 was also performed, which was negative for tumor. The non-neoplastic lung parenchyma was stained with anthracotic pigment but was otherwise unremarkable.

The patient, a female with right lung cancer, underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed a unifocal adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 3 cm in size. The tumor was moderately to poorly differentiated (G2-G3) and was surrounded by lung tissue, with no evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. No visceral pleural invasion was identified. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma and no treatment effect was identified. Lymphovascular invasion was absent. Three regional lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for tumor. The pathologic tumor stage was pT1b pNo. Immunohistochemical stains for cytokeratin-7, cytokeratin-5/6, TTF-1, and p63 were performed, with the tumor testing positive for cytokeratin-7 and TTF-1 only, confirming an adenocarcinoma. Molecular studies may be indicated.

The patient has an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 6.5 cm, with additional satellite nodules. There is evidence of visceral pleural and angiolymphatic invasion. All resection margins are tumor-free. Metastatic carcinoma is present in the interlobar and anterior hilar lymph nodes. The stage is T4 N1 Mx. The right middle lobe shows atypical adenomatous hyperplasia. No carcinoma is seen in the right upper lobe, 6th rib bone, or subcarinal lymph node. The background lung shows emphysema.

The patient has an invasive, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.5 cm in the right lower lobe of the lung, with evidence of pleural and angiolymphatic invasion. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is present in two sump nodes. All resection margins are tumor-free. The disease stage is T2 N1 MX. The background lung shows emphysema, airspace smoker's macrophages, and bronchiolectasis. Biopsies of the lymph nodes near the right stem bronchus and the 11 basilar vein are benign and reactive, with no tumor seen. The pleura biopsy shows benign fibroadipose tissue and skeletal muscle. Decalcification is pending for the resected fifth and sixth ribs.

The patient has a 2.8 cm invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with angiolymphatic and visceral pleural invasion. There is no evidence of tumor in the surgical resection margins. All examined lymph nodes are benign. The pathological stage is T2N0MX. The bronchoscopic biopsy of the right upper lobe shows respiratory mucosa with submucosal scarring and chronic inflammation. The 5th rib resection is pending decalcification. The background lung shows emphysematous change.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy, which revealed a 2.0 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with clear cell, solid, mucinous, and fetal-like areas. This was associated with visceral pleural and angiolymphatic invasion, and metastases to the level 5 lymph nodes. No significant abnormalities were found in the bronchial mucosa, and no evidence of metastatic carcinoma was found in the level 11 and 12 lymph nodes. The resected rib is currently undergoing decalcification. The lung also showed respiratory bronchiolitis with emphysematous change, multifocal atypical adenomatous hyperplasia, and pulmonary arteries with marked myointimal thickening. All surgical margins were free of tumor. The pathologic stage is T2 N2 Mx.

The patient underwent a left lower lobe wedge resection, revealing a 2.5 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with acinar, papillary, and bronchioloalveolar features. There is focal angiolymphatic invasion, but no evidence of visceral pleural invasion. One of five N1 lymph nodes was involved, but all margins were free. The pathologic stage is T1, N1, MX. Additionally, emphysematous changes and focal organizing pneumonia were noted, along with multiple small carcinoid tumorlets. A separate inferior left lower lobe nodule was identified as a pulmonary hamartoma with free margins. Biopsies of interlobar and AP window lymph nodes showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma, however, one of two posterior hilar lymph nodes showed metastatic adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy, revealing a 6.8 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with micropapillary growth and psammoma bodies, pathologically staged as T2 N1 MX. Biopsies of level 11 and level 7 lymph nodes showed no evidence of malignancy but did present focal psammomatous calcifications. The lobectomy also revealed metastatic adenocarcinoma in three out of thirteen N1 lymph nodes. Additionally, the patient exhibits smoker's bronchiolitis with emphysematous change and subpleural scarring.

The patient has metastatic adenocarcinoma with extracapsular extension in one lymph node each at levels 10 and 5, and in one of five lymph nodes at level 11. A poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma of solid and acinar type with clear cell change, measuring 4.5 cm in diameter, was found in the left upper lobe of the lung, with visceral pleural and angiolymphatic invasion and lymphangitic spread. All margins are clear. Six out of eight N1 lymph nodes are positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The patient also exhibits respiratory bronchiolitis with emphysematous change. The bone specimen from the fourth rib is currently undergoing decalcification, with an addendum report to follow. The pathologic stage is ypT2 N2 M0.

The patient has a primary lung tumor, specifically a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 3.9 cm, with clear-cell type characteristics, located in the right upper lobe. The tumor has focally invaded the visceral pleura but has not penetrated it, and angiolymphatic invasion is present. There is no evidence of perineural invasion. The surgical margins are free of tumor. Six out of twenty-five lymph nodes show metastatic adenocarcinoma. The patient also exhibits emphysematous changes and smoker's bronchiolitis. The pathologic stage is T2, N1, MX. Immunohistochemical stains indicate the tumor is positive for cytokeratin 7 and negative for cytokeratin 20, supporting the diagnosis of a primary lung lesion.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy for a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 3.3 cm. The tumor exhibits potential neuroendocrine differentiation, but chromogranin and synaptophysin stains were negative, ruling out a neuroendocrine origin. The mucin stain was also negative, which is sometimes seen in poorly differentiated adenocarcinomas. Fluorescent in-situ hybridization studies showed amplification of Her2/Neu and Cyclin D1 genes, but not the EGFR gene. The bronchial, vascular, and pleural margins were free of tumor, and six lymph nodes were negative for metastasis. The surrounding lung showed emphysematous changes. The TNM stage is T2; N0; MX.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy, mediastinoscopy, and lymph node dissection due to a right lung mass. The final diagnosis revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchioalveolar features measuring 4.2cm. The neoplasm was found abutting the visceral pleura but did not penetrate it. Bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were free of neoplasm. Emphysematous changes were observed in the non-neoplastic lung. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one of seven perihilar lymph nodes, with no external node spread. The TNM pathologic stage was T2; N1; MX, and the histopathologic grade was G1. Four peribronchial lymph nodes and seven periaortic and periazygos lymph nodes were benign and negative for neoplasia. The neoplastic cells were strongly positive for cytokeratin 7 and negative for cytokeratin 20 and thyroid transcription factor. The histologic features and pattern of immunostaining are compatible with a primary adenocarcinoma (mucinous BAC) of the lung. No invasion of the elastic layer of the visceral pleura was observed.

The patient has a poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma in the left lung, specifically a moderate to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma predominantly in the left lower lobe with contiguous spread to the left upper lobe. The tumor, measuring 13.2 cm, extends into but not through the visceral pleura. A microscopic focus of the tumor is present in the arterial wall at the vascular margin of resection, but bronchial and all other vascular margins are free of neoplasm. The non-neoplastic lung shows changes of emphysema. Six perihilar lymph nodes are free of neoplasm. A microscopic focus of metastatic carcinoma is present within the vessel wall of a nodule on the aortic arch. No secondary carcinoma is seen in the lymph nodes from various locations. The pathologic stage is PT4, N2, Mx with a grade of G2.

The patient underwent a left upper division segmentectomy, revealing a 3.0 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with papillary differentiation, originating from a scar. No evidence of visceral pleural or angiolymphatic invasion was found, and all sampled lymph nodes were benign. The surgical resection margins were clear of tumor. The pathologic stage is T1N0Mx. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization studies on the adenocarcinoma showed no EGFR amplification in the targeted region. An EGFR Exon 19 mutation was identified, but no KRAS Exon 1 or EGFR Exon 21 mutations were found. The background lung showed emphysematous change and respiratory bronchiolitis. The patient's underlying diseases include emphysema, parenchymal scar, and smoker's bronchiolitis.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe due to a mucinous adenocarcinoma with acinar bronchiolar alveolar micropapillary features, measuring 6.0 cm in maximum dimension. The tumor involved the overlying visceral pleura and extensively infiltrated the angiolymphatic channels. There was no evidence of malignancy in the bronchial and vascular margins. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in four out of six identified hilar lymph nodes, with prominent extracapsular extension. The TNM stage is T2, N2, MX. Molecular Anatomic Pathology testing identified a KRAS Exon 1 mutation (Gly12Cys), but no EGFR Exon 19 or 21 mutations. FISH studies showed no EGFR amplification. The patient also has underlying emphysema.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe apical segmentectomy, revealing a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, acinar and solid type, arising in pulmonary parenchymal scar with angiolymphatic and visceral pleural invasion. The tumor measures 3.4 cm in diameter, with all margins free and a mild host lymphocytic response. Pathologic staging is T2 N0 Mx. Four segmental lymph nodes show anthracosilicotic nodules with no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, multifocal atypical adenomatous hyperplasia and respiratory bronchiolitis with emphysematous change are noted. Molecular Anatomic Pathology Testing shows no KRAS codon 12/13 mutation or EGFR Exon 19 and 21 mutations, but EGFR amplification is identified. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization studies indicate EGFR amplification in the targeted region. No evidence of malignancy is found in the resected portion of the 3rd rib. The patient's underlying diseases include atypical alveolar hyperplasia, emphysema, parenchymal scar, and smoker's bronchiolitis.

The patient underwent a right lung resection and left thyroidectomy due to a right lung mass and left thyroid nodule. Pathological examination revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with squamous differentiation in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.2 cm. The carcinoma invaded the visceral pleura and showed angiolymphatic invasion. There was also evidence of centrilobular emphysema and metastatic carcinoma in one of two peribronchial lymph nodes with extracapsular extension into the peribronchial connective tissue. The resection margins were negative. The right upper lobe orifice biopsy showed benign bronchial mucosa. Metastatic carcinoma was found in one lymph node at right level 11 and three lymph nodes at right level 4. The left thyroid showed nodular hyperplasia with adenomatoid and Hurthle cell nodules. The TNM stage was pT2a N2 cM0. The tumor was located in the right upper lobe, measured 2.2 cm, and was poorly differentiated. There was no surgical margin involvement. The number of N1 and N2 lymph nodes positive were 3 out of 5 and 3 out of 10 respectively. The underlying disease was classified as pT2a pN2.

The patient was diagnosed with right lung cancer and underwent a right anterior thoracotomy and bronchoscopy. The final diagnosis revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with papillary features and lepidic growth, measuring 2.8 cm in the right upper lobe anterior segment of the lung. The carcinoma did not involve the visceral pleura and there was no definitive angiolymphatic invasion. Surgical resection margins were negative. Mild centrilobular emphysema was also noted. Biopsies from the right secondary carina, gastrointestinal junction, and stomach fundus were negative for any malignancy or Helicobacter pylori organisms. Excisions from right level 10, 11, 4, and 7 lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The tumor was classified as pT1, pNO, pMX with no identified extrapulmonary parenchymal extension or invasion of the tumor. The patient also has underlying emphysema.

The patient was diagnosed with a pulmonary nodule in the right upper lobe, which was confirmed post-operatively. A bronchoscopy, biopsy, lavage, and right video-assisted thoracic surgery were performed. The final diagnosis revealed a well-differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma, acinar type with focal bronchoalveolar features, measuring 1.4 cm. All surgical margins were free of tumor and no lymphovascular space permeation was observed. The visceral pleura was also free of tumor. Other findings included apical cap fibrosis, focal small parenchymal scars, and mild emphysematous changes. The AJCC pathologic tumor stage was pT1 N0 MX. The fifth rib bone excised was benign. The completion lobectomy of the right lung showed focal small parenchymal scars and mild emphysematous changes, with all surgical margins free of tumor. The primary lung tumor was located in the right upper lobe, with a maximum dimension of 1.4 cm. The histologic grade was G1, well differentiated. No extrapulmonary parenchymal extension or invasion of the tumor was identified. The underlying diseases included emphysema, parenchymal scar, and apical cap fibrosis. The pathologic T stage was pT1, N stage was pN0, and M stage was pMX.

The patient has a 1.7 cm invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, associated with visceral pleural invasion. No angiolymphatic invasion is identified. All sampled lymph nodes are benign and free of tumor. The pathologic stage is T2N0Mx. The nasopharynx shows mild chronic inflammation. The lung also shows emphysematous change and respiratory bronchiolitis. The tumor cells are positive for cytokeratin 7, and negative for cytokeratin 20, TTF, mammoglobin, and GCDFP. The surgical margins are clear. Ancillary studies include histochemical stains, immunohistochemical stains, FISH studies, and molecular studies.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the superior segment of the left lower lobe of the lung, with clear cell change and amyloid-like stroma. The tumor measures 8.0 cm in diameter and shows angiolymphatic invasion and association with visceral pleura, but no involvement of N1 or N2 lymph nodes. The tumor is pathologically staged as T2N0MX. Biopsies of lymph nodes at various levels show no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The patient also exhibits mild emphysematous change. Histochemical stains reveal abundant cytoplasmic glycogen and positive PAS-D and mucicarmine stains for mucin, indicating pleural invasion. Congo Red stains are negative.

The patient has a 5.0 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe basilar segment of the lung, with clear cell change and CDX2 positivity, indicating visceral pleural and angiolymphatic invasion. No EGFR amplification was detected in the targeted region, with a ratio of EGFR gene to the centromere of chromosome 7 of 0.88. The rate of hyperploidy for the centromere of chromosome 7 was 41% of the analyzed cells. The surgical margins and lymph nodes were free of cancer. The tumor was pathologically staged as T2, N0, MX. The patient also has underlying emphysema and smoker's bronchiolitis. Given the CDX2 positivity and absence of TTF1, it is recommended to exclude an extrathoracic primary site of origin, particularly in the GI tract, before confirming this as a primary lung adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 1.3 cm in diameter, with angiolymphatic invasion. There was no evidence of visceral pleural invasion and all margins were clear. The tumor involved both N1 and N2 lymph nodes. Pathologic staging was T1 N2 Mx. Molecular Anatomic Pathology Testing revealed no KRAS codon 12/13 mutation, no EGFR Exon 19 or 21 mutations, and no EML4/ALK rearrangement, but EGFR amplification was identified. The lung showed marked emphysematous change with respiratory bronchiolitis. Six out of thirteen N1 lymph nodes and two out of fourteen N2 lymph nodes were positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The bronchial margin was free of carcinoma, but carcinoma extended within 1-2 mm of this final margin. The underlying disease was emphysema.

The patient underwent a left VATS procedure due to a lung mass. Molecular Anatomic Pathology Testing revealed no identified mutations in KRAS codon 12/13, EGFR Exon 19, EGFR Exon 21, EGFR amplification, and EML4/ALK rearrangement. The posterior segmentectomy showed a 2.5 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with angiolymphatic and parietal pleural invasion. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in posterior and apical segment level 11, level 10, and level 5 lymph nodes. The surgical resection margins were free of tumor, indicating a pathologic stage of T3N2Mx. The final diagnosis includes poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left pleura and metastatic adenocarcinoma in various lymph nodes. The primary lung tumor was located in the left upper lobe, with a maximum dimension of 2.5 cm. The tumor showed angiolymphatic invasion and up to 50% necrosis. The patient also has underlying emphysema and smoker's bronchiolitis. The pathologic staging is T3N2Mx.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for lung cancer. Pathological examination revealed a 2.4 cm poorly differentiated mucin-producing adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe, with angiolymphatic and visceral pleural invasion. The tumor also involved the right paratracheal lymph nodes, but all margins were free. The pathological stage is T2 N2 MX. Molecular Anatomic Pathology Testing identified EGFR amplification but no KRAS codon 12/13 mutation, EGFR Exon 19 mutation, EGFR Exon 21 mutation, or EML4/ALK rearrangement. The adenocarcinoma showed both moderate and poorly differentiated areas, with focal squamous differentiation. No evidence of malignancy was found in the interlobar, subcarinal, and right tracheobronchial angle lymph nodes. However, metastatic adenocarcinoma with extracapsular extension was found in three of seven fragments of the right paratracheal lymph node. The patient also has underlying emphysema.

The patient, diagnosed pre-operatively with right lung cancer, underwent a bronchoscopy, mediastinoscopy, and thoracotomy. Molecular Anatomic Pathology Microdissection Genotyping Testing revealed no mutations in KRAS Exon 1, EGFR Exon 19, and EGFR Exon 21. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization studies showed no EGFR amplification in the adenocarcinoma. The final diagnosis revealed a 2.5 cm invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe superior segment, associated with visceral pleural and angiolymphatic invasion. All sampled lymph nodes were benign and surgical resection margins were free of tumor. The pathologic stage is T2N0Mx. Additionally, a 0.6 cm typical carcinoid was found in the right middle lobe, along with numerous carcinoid tumorlets and diffuse neuroendocrine cell hyperplasia. The patient also showed signs of emphysema and parenchymal scar.

The patient has a 1.6 cm invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with no evidence of angiolymphatic or visceral pleural invasion. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization studies indicate low-level amplification of Her2/Neu and high-level amplification of cyclin-D1 and EGFR genes. Surgical resection margins are clear of tumor and all sampled lymph nodes are benign, with anthracotic pigment present. The background lung shows emphysematous change and respiratory bronchiolitis. The pathologic stage is T1 N0 MX.

The patient underwent a superior segmentectomy of the right lower lobe of the lung. Pathological examination revealed a 2.0 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchovascular margin positive for adenocarcinoma and evidence of perineural invasion. There is a focal suggestion of angiolymphatic invasion. The stapled parenchymal margin is free of carcinoma. Emphysematous changes were also noted. The tumor is staged as pT1 N0 MX according to AJCC. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 4, 7, 8, 10, and 11 showed anthracotic changes but no carcinoma. Immunohistochemical staining was positive for TTF-1 in the malignant cells, with rare cells positive for p63, and negative for cytokeratin 5/6, supporting the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma. The carcinoma exhibited acinar and solid patterns.

The patient has a 3 cm acinar predominant adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with angiolymphatic invasion but no visceral pleural invasion. All examined lymph nodes are negative for malignancy. The tumor is moderately differentiated (G2) with no extrapulmonary extension. Surgical margins are clear with the closest margin being 25 mm away from the invasive tumor. The tumor is pathologically staged as T1bN0 according to AJCC. Molecular testing reveals a positive KRAS exon 2 (G12A) mutation, while EGFR exons 18, 19, 20, 21 and BRAF exon 15 mutations are negative. ALK rearrangement, c-MET amplification, and FGFR1 amplification are also negative. The patient has underlying emphysema and smoker's bronchiolitis.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy, revealing a 7.5 cm moderately differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma with angiolymphatic and visceral pleural invasion. No involvement of N1 or N2 lymph nodes was found and all margins were free, resulting in a pathologic stage of T3 N0. Multiple lymph node biopsies showed reactive changes with no evidence of malignancy. The adenocarcinoma exhibited a variety of architectural patterns with lepidic and papillary patterns predominant. Molecular anatomic pathology testing identified a KRAS codon 12 mutation (p.G12C, c.34G>T), but no EGFR or BRAF mutations were found. ALK rearrangement, ROS translocation, and c-MET amplification were all negative. The patient also showed mild emphysematous change.

The patient has a moderately differentiated invasive papillary adenocarcinoma located in the right upper lobe posterior segment of the lung, measuring 2.0 x 2.0 x 1.8 cm. The tumor is negative for visceral pleura and lymphovascular invasion, with a clear surgical parenchymal margin of resection. Emphysematous changes are present. The tumor is staged as pT1a N0 according to AJCC TNM classification. Molecular studies show the tumor is EGFR, KRAS, and BRAF negative, but ALK FISH studies are positive. Additionally, multiple lymph nodes were biopsied and found to be benign and free of tumor, with anthracotic pigment deposits present in some. The patient also has underlying emphysema.

The patient underwent a right thoracotomy for a lobectomy of the right upper lobe due to a suspected cancer. Pathologic examination revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 6.2 cm in greatest dimension, which penetrated the visceral pleura. However, the tumor did not reach the soft tissue margin. The tumor was staged as pT2, N0, MX, indicating a tumor size greater than 3cm, no regional lymph node metastasis, and an unassessable metastasis status. All margins were free of tumor, with the closest margin being the soft tissue (chest wall) at a distance of 2mm. No venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion was observed. Multiple lymph nodes from various locations (intra lobar, parabronchial, paraesophageal, tracheal angle, subcarinal, inferior pulmonary, and distal paratracheal) were examined, all of which showed no malignancy. Additionally, biopsies from the visceral pleural nodule and right superior lobe segment showed bronchioloalveolar hyperplasia but no carcinoma.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy for a pulmonary lesion. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 1.2 cm in the right upper lobe nodule, with vascular invasion but free margins. The overlying pleura was free of tumor. The right upper lobe lung showed subpleural fibrosis and a bronchial margin free of tumor. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one lymph node at the right tracheobronchial angle. The subcarinal lymph node showed necrotizing granulomatous hyalinization with no malignancy. No malignancy was seen in the right distal peritracheal lymph node and the inferior pulmonary lymph node. The final staging was pT1 N1 MX. Special stains for acid-fast bacilli and fungi were negative.

The patient underwent a right lobectomy due to a lesion in the right upper lobe. Pathologic examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 1.5 cm in greatest dimension, with multiple microscopic foci of bronchioalveolar carcinoma present, including in the stapled resection margin. No tumor was seen in the segment of bronchus. The visceral pleura was not involved by the tumor, and there was no evidence of venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion. Five regional lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. The pathologic staging is PT1 N pNO pMX. The margins could not be assessed. The patient also exhibited atypical pneumocyte hyperplasia in the right upper lobe.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a unifocal, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of acinar histologic type, measuring 4.5 cm in its greatest dimension. The tumor showed visceral pleural invasion and lymph-vascular invasion, but the bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. One of four lymph nodes examined showed metastatic carcinoma. The pathologic staging is pT2a, N1, Mx, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but less than 5 cm, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial and/or ipsilateral hilar lymph nodes, and intrapulmonary nodes. EGFR and KRAS mutational analysis are pending. No distant metastasis was identified.

The patient, previously diagnosed with left lung cancer, underwent a surgical procedure involving a wedge resection of the left upper lobe. The gross examination of the resected specimen, measuring 9 x 6 x 1.5 cm, revealed a circumscribed white tan firm nodule of 2 cm in diameter, located 0.1 cm from the pleural surface and extending 1 cm from the resection margin. The frozen section diagnosis confirmed the presence of a large cell carcinoma with clear margins. The final diagnosis, however, identified a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.0 cm in greatest diameter, extending up to but not through the pleura, with tumor identified within endothelial lined lymphovascular space and areas of fibrosis. No lymph nodes were resected. The adenocarcinoma grows along alveolar spaces, but the presence of fibrosis excludes the possibility of a bronchoalveolar carcinoma. The tumor focally extends up to the pleural surface but does not invade it.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe due to a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.7 cm in greatest dimension and confined to the lung. The tumor did not extend to the pleural surface and was 0.1cm away from it. No lymphovascular, venous, or arterial invasion was observed. Thirteen regional lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. Distant metastasis could not be assessed. The surgical margins were free from invasive carcinoma. A biopsy of the level 7 subcarinal lymph node revealed metastatic poorly-differentiated carcinoma in one of nine lymph nodes, with no extranodal extension identified. Three benign lymph nodes were found in the level 4 biopsy. The pathologic stage is pT2 pN2 pMX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung due to a mass. The histopathological examination revealed a moderately-to-poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a clear cell component, measuring 2.0 cm in maximum dimension without involvement of the overlying pleura. The bronchial and vascular resection margins were negative for tumor, and there was no evidence of blood/lymphatic vessel invasion. Examination of the subcarinal, inferior pulmonary ligament, proximal bronchial, and AP window lymph nodes showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The neoplastic cells showed strong nuclear positivity for TTF-1, indicating primary lung carcinoma. Distant metastasis was not assessed.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a lung mass. Post-operative diagnosis confirmed lung carcinoma. The specimen consisted of a single lobe of lung, with a well-circumscribed mass measuring 5 X 5 X 4.5 cm. The mass was found to be a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, with evidence of lymphovascular space invasion. The vascular and bronchial margins were free of tumor. However, metastatic carcinoma was found in one of the twenty-two evaluated lymph nodes, indicating regional lymph node involvement (pN1). No distant metastasis could be assessed (pMX). The surrounding lung parenchyma showed emphysematous changes with areas of congestion. Other lymph nodes biopsied, including the inferior pulmonary ligament, hilar, tracheobronchial angle, subcarinal, and proximal bronchial, showed anthracosis but no evidence of malignancy.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung. The invasive carcinoma is primarily composed of cell sheets with scattered glandular structures. The neoplastic cells exhibit prominent nucleoli and do not resemble small cell carcinoma, grade II neuroendocrine carcinoma, or large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma. Immunohistochemical staining reveals positive results for cytokeratin CK7 and TTF-1, but negative for CK20, high molecular weight keratin SK, and p63, supporting the diagnosis of primary lung adenocarcinoma. Weak staining for synaptophysin is observed, but it does not suggest a neuroendocrine tumor. It is recommended to determine EGFR and KRAS mutation status to guide TKI therapy selection. ALK gene rearrangement should also be considered due to its association with TKI resistance and favorable response to Crizotinib. Bronchial washing from the right bronchus shows no malignant cells, with the presence of respiratory epithelial cells, squamous cells, and macrophages.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a suspected malignancy. The final pathologic diagnosis confirmed a low-grade (1/3) adenocarcinoma with mucinous and bronchoalveolar features, measuring 3.0 x 2.0 x 2.0 cm, located peripherally and unifocal. The tumor was confined to the lung with no evidence of visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor was 2.5 cm away from the bronchial and parenchymal margins and less than 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. Seven lymph nodes were examined, none of which contained metastatic carcinoma. The pTN stage was pT1, N0. Additionally, levels 10, 11, and 4 lymph nodes showed benign hyperplasia. The neoplastic cells were positive for CK7 and TTF, and negative for CK20 and CDX2.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lung biopsy, revealing an adenocarcinoma measuring 3.5 cm with direct extension into the visceral pleura, classified as pT2. The tumor was Grade II and showed weak to moderate intranuclear positivity for thyroid transcription factor-1 (TTF-1), indicating a lung primary. No regional lymph node metastasis was identified, classified as pNO. The status of distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMX). The tumor was present at the visceral pleural surface, but no venous or arterial invasion was identified. A subcarinal lymph node excision and a hilar lymph node biopsy were both negative for tumor. The completion lobectomy specimen showed residual adenocarcinoma with surrounding obstructive/lipoid pneumonia, an uninvolved bronchial margin, and a spindle cell carcinoid tumor measuring 8mm. A subpleural bulla was also noted. The inferior pulmonary ligament biopsy showed benign lung parenchyma and adherent fibrofatty tissue, consistent with parietal pleura, with no evidence of tumor involvement.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy due to a malignant neoplasm in the bronchus/lung. A total of six lymph nodes were excised from various levels, none of which showed metastatic carcinoma. The lung tumor was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, located in the left upper lobe, measuring 4.5 cm, and was unifocal. The tumor was confined to the lung, with visceral pleural invasion and lymphovascular space invasion present. The tumor was 4.5 cm away from the bronchial margin and was present at the pleural surface. One lymph node showed metastatic carcinoma with extracapsular extension and invasion of the adjacent artery wall. The pTNM stage was pT2aN1MX. No other significant findings were noted. It is recommended to determine EGFR and KRAS mutation status to guide treatment selection.

The patient presented with right lung masses and underwent a biopsy of level 9 and level 7 lymph nodes, as well as a wedge resection of the right lower lobe of the lung. The lymph nodes showed anthracosis and reactive change, with no malignancy detected. The lung tissue, however, revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with extensive necrosis, measuring 1.6 cm at its greatest dimension. The malignancy was found to be within 0.1 mm of the free pleural surface, but the stapled surgical margin was free of malignancy. No definite lymphovascular space invasion was identified. The malignancy was present in sheets in some areas with focal gland formation. The small cell component was not identified. The frozen section diagnosis was confirmed.

The patient, a male, underwent surgical excision of lymph nodes from various locations (AP window, posterior hilar, intralobar, hilar) and the left upper lobe of the lung. Pathological examination revealed no evidence of malignancy in the excised lymph nodes. However, a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 3.5 cm was identified in the left upper lobe of the lung. The tumor did not involve the pleura and was 1.2 cm from the bronchial resection margin. No malignancy was found in the three peribronchial lymph nodes and there was no evidence of lymphovascular space invasion. The adjacent lung tissue showed emphysematous changes. The bronchial margin was negative for malignancy. The gross description of the lung lobe revealed a firm white to gray ill-defined mass with scalloped borders in the area of pleural retraction. The remaining lung parenchyma showed dilated air spaces, most marked in the superoposterior aspect of the lung.

The patient has been diagnosed with Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer. The histopathological examination of the right lung tissue and right upper lobe revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, predominantly of the papillary variant, measuring 3.5 X 3.0 X 2.0 cm. The tumor is classified as pT2, indicating a size greater than 3 cm. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one right pulmonary lymph node and one of two lower paratracheal lymph nodes at station 8, classifying the regional lymph nodes as pN2. The bronchial margin is involved by invasive carcinoma with extensive lymphatic invasion. No distant metastasis could be assessed (pMX). No venous or arterial invasion was observed. The paraesophageal lymph node at station 8 was negative for tumor. The final pathologic stage is pT2N2MXG2.

The patient underwent a left lower lobe lobectomy due to a preoperative diagnosis of lung cancer. The excised lung tissue revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.3 x 3.0 x 2.7 cm, located in the left lower lobe. The tumor was 2.8 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.1 cm from the pleural surface, with no evidence of pleural or lymphovascular space invasion. Fourteen lymph nodes were examined, including one inferior pulmonary ligament node, three hilar nodes, four interlobar nodes, one peribronchial node, two AP window nodes, and three subcarinal nodes. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in any of the examined lymph nodes. The pTNM stage of the tumor is pT2 N0 Mx.

The patient presented with a right lung mass, which was diagnosed as a well-differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma with bronchoalveolar component, measuring 4.5 cm in maximum dimension (pT2). The tumor did not show any signs of invasion into the pleura or lymphovascular space. The resection margins, including pleural, parenchymal, bronchial, and vascular, were all negative for tumor. Examination of the right hilar and N1 lymph nodes, as well as a perihilar lymph node, revealed benign anthracotic lymph nodes with no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The TNM stage is pT2 N0 MX.

The patient underwent a surgical procedure for a left lung mass, which was confirmed post-operatively. The left lower lobe of the lung was received with a large palpable mass, which was inked and sectioned. The mass was necrotic and grossly involved the pleura. Cytosmear indicated non-small cell carcinoma, favoring squamous, pending pathology review. The bronchial margin was negative for tumor. The mass measured 6.5 X 6.0 X 6.0 cm and was composed of tan-white firm tissue with focal necrosis. Three hilar lymph nodes were identified with moderate anthracosis. Microscopic examination revealed no evidence of tumor involvement in the bronchial and vascular margins. However, the lymph nodes showed extensive replacement by non-oat cell carcinoma. The tumor demonstrated extensive necrosis and intrapulmonary lymphatic and vascular invasion. The final diagnosis was adenocarcinoma with minor areas of squamous and bronchioloalveolar differentiation, with a histologic grade of GII-III. The tumor was classified as pT2, with clear vascular and bronchial margins. Blood/lymphatic vessel invasion was present, and metastatic carcinoma was identified in three of three hilar lymph nodes. Additional pathologic findings included patchy COPD.

The patient has a unifocal, poorly differentiated, non-small cell carcinoma of pulmonary origin, located in the middle lobe of the right lung, with a maximum gross tumor size of 5.5 x 5.0 cm. The tumor extends into the fissure, but there is no visceral pleural invasion or bronchial margin involvement. All vascular parenchymal parietal pleural margins are negative for carcinoma. There is presence of tumor-associated pneumonia/fibrosis. Lymph vascular invasion is indeterminate but favored, and twelve lymph nodes, including parts A through E, block F1, are negative for carcinoma. The pathologic stage is nT26MOMY. The immunoprofile supports the diagnosis of a very poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma rather than metastatic urothelial carcinoma, with negative CK5/6, p63, CK7, CK20, and uroplakin staining, and patchy positive TTF-1 staining. Further characterization of the tumor type is pending immunoevaluation.

The patient, a female, underwent a surgical procedure involving the left lung. Pathological examination of the specimens revealed an old calcified granuloma in the left lower lobe (Specimen A), benign lymph nodes in level 2 (Specimen B), level 6 (Specimen D), and level 9 (Specimen E). The left upper lobe (Specimen C) showed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 4.1 cm at its greatest dimension, confined to the lung with no distant metastasis. The tumor margins were clear of invasive carcinoma, but lymphovascular invasion was present. One of six lymph nodes was positive for metastatic carcinoma. The pathologic stage is pT2, pN1, pMX.

The patient underwent a resection of the right lower lobe of the lung due to a nodule. The post-operative diagnosis confirmed the presence of a well-differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma of bronchoalveolar type, with a maximal diameter of 1.5 cm (pT1). The tumor was confined to the lung with no vascular invasion or penetration of the visceral pleura. The bronchial resection margin was free of tumor. The surrounding lung showed changes of mild chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Additionally, lymph nodes from the inferior pulmonary ligament, tracheal N2, and subcarinal were examined and showed sinus histiocytosis with anthracosis, but no metastatic tumor was present. The status of distant metastasis is unknown.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung due to a pre-operative diagnosis of a left lung mass. Post-operative diagnosis confirmed the presence of a moderately-poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, histologically consistent with pulmonary origin. The tumor measured 2.5 x 2.0 cm and was located 1 mm from the inked hilar pleural surface. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor, but minute tumor emboli were noted within lymphatic spaces of the bronchial margin. Extensive lymphvascular invasion was observed through grossly uninvolved lung and subpleural lymphatics. Ten out of twelve regional lymph nodes, including the subcarinal lymph node, were involved by metastatic carcinoma. All margins were negative, and there was no evidence of distant metastasis or direct extension of the tumor.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with lung cancer. Histopathological examination of multiple specimens including lymph nodes from various stations, lung biopsies, and right lower lobe of the lung was conducted. The lymph nodes were found to be benign. The bronchial margin was free of tumor. However, a non-small cell carcinoma was identified. Gross examination revealed a calcified nodule in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor was 3.5 cm in size, located in the lower lobe of the right lung, and was classified as a poorly differentiated Grade III adenocarcinoma. The tumor had extended to the visceral pleura and had invaded both arterial and venous large vessels as well as lymphatic small vessels. Metastases were found in ipsilateral peribronchial and hilar lymph nodes. The surgical margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being 5 mm away. Additional findings included a calcified granuloma in a peribronchial lymph node.

The patient has a well to moderately differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 8.5 cm in maximal dimension (pT2). Metastatic carcinoma is present in one out of three hilar lymph nodes and two out of six proximal bronchial lymph nodes. No evidence of metastatic carcinoma was found in the inferior pulmonary ligament lymph node and subcarinal lymph node. The bronchial and vascular resection margins are negative for tumor. Small vessel (lymphatic) invasion is present, but large vessel (venous) invasion is not identified. The tumor extends to the visceral pleura but does not penetrate through it. Non-neoplastic lung tissue shows multifocal nodular areas of bronchiolar pneumonitis with a BOOP-like pattern. Immunostains show positive staining for CK7 and TTF-1, and negative for CK20, indicating primary lung carcinoma.

The patient was diagnosed with lung cancer, specifically moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, located in the left lower lobe of the lung. The tumor mass measures 4.5 x 3.5 x 3.5 cm, indicating a pT2 stage. The bronchial and vascular resection margins and pleural surface are free of carcinoma. However, lymphovascular invasion is present. Two out of nine peribronchial lymph nodes tested positive for metastatic carcinoma. The inferior pulmonary ligament, subcarinal, hilar, pulmonary artery, proximal bronchial, and A-P window lymph nodes were all negative for carcinoma. Distant metastasis could not be assessed.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a greatest dimension of 2.0 cm. The tumor invades the visceral pleura but the margins are uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. There is no lymphovascular, venous, or arterial invasion. Seven regional lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. Distant metastasis cannot be assessed. The pulmonary ligament node, P A window node, and hilar lymph node were all negative for malignancy. The lung specimen was a lobectomy. The gross description of the lung shows a tan-to-gray mass in the central portion, close to but not penetrating the pleural surface. The remaining lung parenchyma is red-to-tan with no additional masses or nodules seen. The pathologic stage is pT2pN0pMX.

The patient underwent a right lobectomy for a pre-operative diagnosis of lung cancer. Gross examination of the right lower lobe of the lung revealed a tan firm mass measuring 2.5 x 2.0 x 2.0 cm, located 5 cm from the bronchial margin. Histopathological examination identified this as an invasive adenocarcinoma with bronchioloalveolar features, graded I-II, indicating it is well to moderately differentiated. The tumor invades the visceral pleura (pT2) but no regional lymph node metastasis was found in the examined peribronchial and paraesophageal lymph nodes (pN0). Distant metastasis could not be assessed (pMX). The surgical margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma and there was no identified venous, arterial, or lymphatic invasion. Additional findings included a central scar associated with the adenocarcinoma. The paraesophageal and interlobar lymph nodes showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma.

The patient underwent a wedge biopsy of the left lower lobe of the lung due to a pre-operative diagnosis of a lung mass. Post-operative diagnosis remains the same, pending pathology. The gross examination revealed a well-defined subpleural mass measuring 2.4 x 2.2 x 1.8 cm, located 2.0 cm from the staple line. The mass was composed of tan-white firm tissue. The remaining lung showed tan-pink congested pulmonary parenchyma with emphysematous changes. Microscopic examination confirmed the mass as a poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring about 2.2 cm in maximal dimension, with evidence of lymphovascular invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were clear of tumor. The remaining lung tissue showed moderate emphysema. No evidence of metastatic carcinoma was found in the AP window and subcarinal lymph nodes. The final diagnosis is a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the left lower lobe of the lung, with a TNM classification of pT1.N0.MX.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy for a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 62mm in diameter, with visceral pleural invasion and satellite tumor nodules adjacent to the main mass. The bronchial margin is free of tumor, with the tumor present 50mm from the bronchial margin. Emphysematous changes and respiratory bronchiolitis were observed in the lung tissue. Metastatic carcinoma was found in one of three peribronchial lymph nodes. A benign glandular epithelial inclusion and focal noncaseating, hyalinized granulomatous inflammation were also noted within the peribronchial lymph node. Two lymph node biopsies, designated "N8R" and "N9R", showed anthracotic changes but were negative for malignancy. The pathologic staging is IIIA, with the primary tumor classified as pT3 due to the presence of separate satellite tumor nodules in the same lobe of lung, and regional lymph nodes classified as pN1 due to metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial lymph nodes.

The patient was diagnosed with right lung adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.2 x 2.0 x 1.8 cm, moderately to poorly differentiated, with lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor was located 2.8 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.2 cm from the parenchymal margin, with no carcinoma identified at the parenchymal margin. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the examined lymph nodes at levels 7, 9, and 10 of the right chest, or level 4, which showed reactive sinus histiocytosis and anthracosilicosis. Emphysematous changes and subpleural fibrosis were also noted. The pathological stage is pT1 N0. Clinical correlation and follow-up are recommended. The diagnosis was reviewed and concurred by another pathologist.

The patient has multifocal adenocarcinoma in the right middle and upper lobes of the lung, with the largest tumor measuring 7.5 x 5.5 x 3.8 cm. The tumors are moderately to poorly differentiated and have invaded the lymphovascular space, but are limited to the pulmonary parenchyma. There is also a hamartoma measuring 1.1 cm in the right middle lobe. The surgical margins are close to the tumor, with the bronchial margin being 0.2 cm away and the pleural surface less than 0.1 cm away. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is present in three out of five lymph nodes examined, including one level 8 node. The pTNM stage is pT3 N2. The presence of bronchioloalveolar carcinoma associated with invasive adenocarcinoma suggests the need for EGFR and KRAS mutation status determination for potential Tyrosine-Kinase Inhibitor (TKI) therapy.

The patient underwent a bi-lobectomy with regional lymphadenectomy of the right middle and lower lobes of the lung. Pathology revealed multifocal invasive adenocarcinoma with a predominant bronchioloalveolar pattern. The tumor in the middle lobe measured 2 cm with no identified visceral pleural invasion, classified as pT1a, stage IA. The tumor in the lower lobe measured 15 cm, also with no identified visceral pleural invasion, classified as pT3, stage IIB. All surgical margins were negative and sixteen lymph nodes were examined, all negative for metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, non-necrotizing granulomatous inflammation was noted. Special stains for acid fast bacilli (AFB), and fungi (GMS, PAS) were negative. The granulomas are likely secondary to extravasated mucin.

The patient presented with a right lung upper lobe nodule. A wedge biopsy revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, solid type, measuring 2.0 x 2.0 x 1.3 cm, extending to within 0.2 cm of the surgical margin. The pleural surface was negative for carcinoma and there was no lymphovascular space invasion. A subsequent right upper lobectomy showed benign lung tissue with no residual carcinoma, and the bronchial margin was free. Two peribronchial lymph nodes were examined and found to be free of tumor. Additionally, mediastinal lymph node biopsies at levels 7 and 10 were benign. The pathologic stage is pT1a pN0.

The patient, a female with a history of renal cell carcinoma, underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a suspicious lesion. The histopathological examination revealed a unifocal, subpleural adenocarcinoma of 2.5 x 1.5 x 1.5 cm size, moderately differentiated (grade 2). The tumor was located less than 0.1 cm from the parenchymal stapled margin and 0.4 cm from the pleural surface, with no evidence of visceral tumor invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. Seven lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastatic carcinoma. Immunohistochemical staining was positive for CK7 and TTF1, and negative for CK20 and RCC, suggesting a primary pulmonary adenocarcinoma rather than a metastasis from the kidney. The tumor was staged as pT1b, N0. However, the malignancy was found to involve the inked margin at the stapled parenchymal surgical margin, suggesting possible residual disease. Clinical correlation is recommended.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy and segmentectomy, with a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma identified measuring 3.5 x 3.5 x 2.9cm. The tumor did not involve the visceral pleura, but the soft tissue margin adjacent to the bronchial and vascular margins was positive for tumor, although the bronchus and vascular wall were not involved. The wedge margin was negative for tumor. Six lymph nodes were benign. Immunohistochemical stains were positive for TTF-1, Napsin-A, and CK7, supporting the diagnosis of primary lung adenocarcinoma. The tumor was staged as pT2a, with no regional lymph node involvement (pN0) and unknown distant metastasis (pMX), resulting in a pathologic stage of IB. The margin status was R1, indicating the presence of tumor at the resection margin. No lymphovascular or visceral pleural invasion was identified. Despite the bronchial and vascular margins being negative, the peribronchovascular connective and alveolar tissue was positive for tumor, suggesting a positive bronchovascular margin.

The patient underwent a right thoracotomy, with specimens taken from the right upper lobe and R4 and subcarinal lymph nodes. Gross examination revealed two nodules in the upper lobe, with puckering of the pleural surfaces. Histological analysis identified these as invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, with some areas showing clear cell patterns and others having eosinophilic cytoplasm. The tumor extended into the visceral pleura and a thick-walled blood vessel, likely a vein. However, the bronchial resection margin was negative for tumor. The parabronchial lymph node was also negative for metastatic disease. The R4 and subcarinal lymph nodes showed reactive changes but no metastatic disease. The tumor was approximately 4.3 cm in size, with a "dumbbell" shape indicating a single tumor focus. The patient also had emphysema. The pathological TNM staging was pT2a PL2, pN0.

The patient has a history of left lung cancer. Upon examination, a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma was identified in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a tumor size of 1.2 X 1.0 X 0.8 cm. The carcinoma has invaded into, but not through, the visceral pleura. However, the lung parenchymal resection margin and lymphovascular space were found to be negative for carcinoma. Additionally, biopsies of the 4R, level 7, 4L, 2R, level 5, and level 6 lymph nodes were all negative for malignancy. The pathologic stage of the cancer is classified as pT2a PL1 pNO.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy due to a preoperative diagnosis of lung cancer. The postoperative pathological examination revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, subpleural in location, unifocal, with a size of 1.5 x 1.5 x 1.4 cm. There was no evidence of visceral pleural invasion, lymphovascular space invasion, or tumor extension. The tumor was 4.3 cm from the bronchial margin, 3.8 cm from the parenchymal (stapled) margin, and 0.2 cm from the pleural surface. Ten lymph nodes were examined, including two each from levels 11, 12, 8, and 7, all of which were negative for malignancy. The pTNM stage was determined to be pT1a, N0. Despite the well-differentiated nature of the tumor, it exhibited a distinct tumor stroma and did not spread along alveolar walls in the manner of a classic bronchoalveolar carcinoma.

The patient underwent a left lower lobectomy due to a mass in the left lower lobe of the lung. The resected lung lobe, weighing 130 grams and measuring 13.2 x 10.8 x 5 cm, contained a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.9 cm with intralymphatic tumor invasion. The tumor was 1.5 cm away from the bronchial resection margin and did not penetrate the pleural surface. The bronchial and vascular resection margins were free of malignancy. The lung parenchyma away from the tumor was also free of lesions. Three lymph nodes (L9, L10 intralobular, and L7) were excised and found to be negative for metastatic carcinoma. The final pathologic staging is pT1b pNO Stage IA.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe lobectomy and regional lymphadenectomy for a lung nodule. Pathological examination revealed a 2.0 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma (Grade 2) in the left upper lobe. The tumor was 4.6 cm away from the closest margin (bronchial margin), which was negative for tumor involvement. Lymphovascular and perineural invasion were identified. Six out of 22 regional lymph nodes (peribronchial and para-aortic) were positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The visceral pleura was not involved by the tumor. Immunohistochemical staining supported the diagnosis of lung adenocarcinoma. The pathological staging was pT1a, pN2, pMX, and stage IIIA. The tumor was unifocal and did not extend into extra-pulmonary structures. No treatment effect was noted.

The patient, diagnosed with lung cancer, underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe. The gross examination revealed a well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5 x 3.2 x 1.6 cm, located in the left upper lobe. No visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion was identified. The bronchial margin was free of carcinoma with a tumor distance of 2.3 cm. No carcinoma was identified on the pleural surface. A total of one bronchial lymph node was examined with no metastatic carcinoma identified (0/1). Additionally, biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 7, 10, 9, and 5 of the left lung showed reactive sinus histiocytosis, lymphoid hyperplasia, and anthracosilicosis, with no metastatic carcinoma identified. The tumor was staged as pT2a N0. Immunohistochemical stains were equivocal, suggesting the possibility of a metastatic lesion. Clinical correlation and follow-up is recommended.

The patient underwent a thoracotomy with lobectomy due to a right lung mass. The postoperative diagnosis confirmed the mass as a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 6.0 cm at its greatest dimension, with focal involvement of the pleural surface. No lymphovascular or perineural invasion was identified. The bronchial and vascular resection margins were negative for malignancy. Examination of the lymph nodes from various locations (peribronchial/hilar, interlobe, hilar, and lower paratracheal right) revealed no metastatic malignancy. The non-neoplastic lung showed congestion and mild chronic inflammation. The pathologic staging was pT2a, pNO, pMX.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper and lower lobes of the lung, as well as in the pleura, as confirmed by wedge excision and biopsy. The tumor cells are positive for TTF-1, CK7, Napsin-A, MOC-31, and ER, and negative for calretinin, CDX2, CK20, CK 5/6, GCDFP-15, mammaglobin, p63, PAX-8, vilin and S-100, indicating a primary lung adenocarcinoma. The tumor was found to be within 0.2 cm of the surgical margin in the upper lobe and abutting the overlying pleura. Two nodular areas were also identified in the lower lobe. The histomorphology and immunohistochemistry staining pattern are consistent across all specimens.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe of the lung due to a lung mass. The tumor was unifocal, measuring 2.4 cm in diameter, and was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The carcinoma extended up to, but not into the visceral pleura, with the closest margin being less than 1 mm from the pleural margin. No lymphovascular space invasion or metastatic carcinoma was identified in the bronchial surgical margin, pleural margin, or in any of the examined lymph nodes. The patient also exhibited subpleural fibrosis, interstitial fibrosis, interstitial chronic inflammation, and emphysematous changes. The final stage of the tumor should be determined in conjunction with clinical information. The patient is recommended for clinical correlation and follow-up.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy with regional lymphadenectomy for a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 4.5 cm in maximum dimension. The tumor showed visceral pleural invasion, but margins were negative, with the closest vascular margin at 0.5 cm. Bronchial margin was uninvolved by carcinoma. Atypical adenomatous hyperplasia and a focal necrotizing granuloma with rare fungal organisms, consistent with Histoplasma species, were also identified. One out of twenty-four lymph nodes was positive for metastatic carcinoma. Pathologic staging was IIA, with lymphovascular invasion present. Elastic stain confirmed the presence of visceral pleural invasion and fungal stain confirmed the presence of rare fungal organisms. Acid-fast bacilli stain was negative.

The patient underwent a surgical resection of the left lower lobe of the lung, revealing a 7 cm pulmonary adenocarcinoma. The tumor did not penetrate the lung pleural surface and the bronchial margins of the surgical excision were free. No lymphovascular invasion was identified. Four peribronchial lymph nodes, one subaortic lymph node, two pulmonary ligament lymph nodes, one para-aortic lymph node, three paraesophageal lymph nodes, and one subcarinal lymph node were all negative for malignancy. The pathological AJCC stage is T2b, N0. Tissue from the tumor, paranormal, and normal were submitted for genomics studies. The gross description of the lung revealed a soft, gray-tan, friable mass abutting the pleural surface and coming within 5 cm of the bronchial margin. The remaining lung parenchyma was red-brown and markedly congested with no additional lesions or areas of interest identified.

The patient was diagnosed with a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the right middle lobe of the lung, measuring 1.7 x 1.7 x 1.6 cm. The tumor was unifocal and confined to the pulmonary parenchyma, with no evidence of visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor was 3.4 cm from the bronchial margin, 0.3 cm from the parenchymal margin, and 1 mm from the pleural surface. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the examined lymph nodes. The patient also exhibited signs of organizing pneumonia. The pathological stage was pT1aNo.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, which revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.8 x 2.7 x 2.4 cm. The tumor was unifocal and confined to the left lower lobe, with no evidence of visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. Surgical margins were clear with the tumor 0.7 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.5 cm from the parenchymal (stapled) margin. Biopsies of level 5 and level 15 lymph nodes were negative for malignancy. Molecular testing showed no EGFR or KRAS mutations and no ALK gene rearrangement, although there was a gain of the ALK region. The tumor was positive for TTF1, consistent with a lung primary. The TNM staging is pT1b. The clinical significance of the ALK region gain is unknown and should be considered in combination with other clinical and laboratory data.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.4 x 2.3 x 1.8 cm, which is moderately differentiated (Grade II). The tumor is unifocal and does not show visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor is 0.2 cm away from the stapled margin and less than 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. Six out of six lymph nodes from Level 4L show metastatic carcinoma. No EGFR mutations were detected, but a KRAS mutation (K-Ras codon 12 GGT>TGT (G12C)) was identified. FISH analysis for ALK gene rearrangement was negative, suggesting a gain of the ALK region. The patient's pTNM stage is pT1bN1. The clinical implications of these findings should be considered in the context of other clinical and laboratory data.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung due to a mass. The mass was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, grade 3, measuring 7.8 x 6.2 x 4.6 cm. The tumor was unifocal and extended to the visceral pleura, but did not extend beyond it. The closest bronchial margin was 3.5 cm away from the tumor. No lymphovascular space invasion was observed. Five lymph nodes were examined, including three excised nodes and two peribronchial nodes within the specimen, none of which showed metastatic carcinoma. The patient also exhibited moderate pulmonary emphysema. The final stage was pT3N0. The diagnosis was confirmed by immunohistochemical stains.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma forming a mass measuring 2.6 x 2.4 x 1.7 cm. The tumor abuts but does not infiltrate the visceral pleura and is situated 0.6 cm from the nearest inked stapled parenchymal resection margin. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 9L, 5, 6, 7, and 12L showed benign anthracotic lymph nodes with no evidence of metastatic adenocarcinoma. The lobectomy of the left upper lobe showed no residual adenocarcinoma, benign bronchial and vascular resection margins, and patchy interstitial fibrosis with nonspecific emphysematous changes within the pulmonary parenchyma. The final TNM staging is pT1bN0M0, indicating stage IA lung cancer. The tumor is a solid adenocarcinoma, poorly differentiated (G3 of G4), with no identified visceral pleural invasion or lymphatic vascular invasion. The tumor is unifocal and the closest margin is 4.5 cm away. There is no evidence of distant metastasis. The patient's sample does not meet criteria for reflex EGFR and ALK testing.

The patient underwent a surgical panel with biopsy of multiple lymph nodes and wedge resection of the left lung. The lymph nodes at levels 9, 7, and 5 on the left side showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma and were benign. The left lower lobe of the lung had a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with papillary features, forming a mass of 2.5 X 2.2 X 1.6 cm. The resection margin and visceral pleura were free of involvement. Two benign peribronchial lymph nodes were identified, and emphysematous changes were present in the surrounding non-involved pulmonary parenchyma. The left upper lobe showed severe emphysematous changes with subpleural bullous formation, apical fibrous scar, and no evidence of active inflammation or neoplasia. The final TNM stage was IA. The tumor was unifocal, with no identified visceral pleural invasion or lymphatic vascular invasion. The closest margin to the tumor was 1.5 cm. The pathologic staging was pT1bN0M0, indicating a tumor greater than 2 cm but 3 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with no regional lymph node metastasis or distant metastasis. The histologic type was papillary adenocarcinoma. No fresh tissue was available for ancillary testing.

The patient, previously diagnosed with lung cancer, underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe. The gross examination revealed a 4.0 cm adenocarcinoma with associated fibrosis, extending into but not through the visceral pleura. The carcinoma was found to be less than 1 mm from the visceral pleural surface, but did not extend to that margin. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the examined lymph nodes from levels 4, 7, 8, 9, 10, and 11 of the right chest, which showed anthracosilicosis and mild reactive lymphoid hyperplasia. The peribronchial lymph nodes also showed anthracosilicosis and a calcified fibrous nodule. The final staging is pT2a N0. The diagnosis was confirmed by a second pathologist.

The patient, a male with a preoperative diagnosis of right upper lung cancer, underwent excision of lymph nodes at levels 12, 10, 9, and 2/4 in the right upper lobe, as well as resection of the right upper lobe. The lymph nodes showed anthracosis and reactive changes, with no malignancy detected. The resected lung tissue revealed a unifocal, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 1.8 x 1.7 x 1.3 cm, located peripherally and subpleurally. No visceral pleural invasion, lymphovascular space invasion, or tumor extension was identified. The tumor was 8.0 cm from the bronchial margin, 4.0 cm from the parenchymal margin, and less than 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. A total of at least eleven lymph nodes were received, none of which contained metastatic carcinoma. The pTNM stage is pT1a, N0. Immunohistochemical staining was strongly positive for CK7, but negative for CK5/6, TTF-1, and p63, supporting the diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. EGFR/KRAS/ALK mutation studies have been requested.

The patient, a male with a history of nonsmall cell carcinoma, underwent a right thoracoscopy for a right lower lobe lung mass. The gross examination of the specimen, a 5 x 4 x 2.5 cm wedge of lung, revealed a solid tan-white mass measuring 2.5 x 2 x 2 cm. The sutured margin was negative, 3 mm from the tumor, however, the serosal surface appeared to be involved by the tumor. The frozen section diagnosis confirmed the presence of adenocarcinoma. Microscopic examination showed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma (2.5 cm) limited to the lung and associated with a subpleural scar. The resection margins were negative for tumor, but lymphovascular invasion was present. The tumor cells were morphologically similar to those in a previous biopsy from the left lower lung. The diagnosis was reviewed and confirmed by Dr. [Name].

The patient was diagnosed with moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the subpleural right lower lung lobe, measuring 2.0 x 2.0 x 1.6 cm. The tumor appears to focally involve the overlying pleura, but no lymphovascular space invasion was observed. The tumor was 2.8 cm from the bronchial margin and less than 0.5 cm from the pleural surface, microscopically involving the pleura. The surgical margins were clear. Lymph nodes from stations 4R, 4L, 11, 12, and 7 were negative for neoplasm. The final staging was T2N0.

The patient underwent a right thoracotomy and lobectomy due to lung cancer. The gross examination of the right upper lobe revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 7.7 cm in greatest dimension, with invasion into the visceral pleura. The bronchial margins were negative for tumor, indicating successful removal of the tumor. However, lymphovascular invasion was positive, suggesting the tumor has spread to the lymphatic or vascular system. Multiple lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for tumor. The pathologic TNM staging is T3 N0 MX.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy for left lung cancer. The tumor was located in the left upper lobe, measuring 4.0 x 3.5 x 3.0 cm, and was unifocal with pleural puckering. The vascular and bronchial margins were uninvolved. Three peribronchial lymph nodes were examined and found to be uninvolved. The tumor was diagnosed as adenocarcinoma, grade 3/4, with no evidence of direct tumor invasion or lymphatic/capillary invasion. The tumor was ERCC1-positive, indicating that the patient may not benefit from adjuvant cisplatin-based chemotherapy. The tumor will be submitted for EGFR and ALK molecular studies. No lymphoid tissue was present in the lymph node biopsies. The patient also had a left cerebellar cystic tumor, which was excised and found to be metastatic pulmonary adenocarcinoma. The pathologic stage was pT2b pNO pM1b(cerebellum).

The patient, a female with a history of smoking and COPD, underwent a resection of the lateral segment of the left upper lobe due to a lung nodule. The pathology report reveals a unifocal adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated, measuring 3.8 x 2.8 x 2.5 cm, located in the lateral segment of the left upper lobe. The tumor is within 0.7 cm of the bronchial and parenchymal (stapled) margins and involves the pleura, indicating visceral pleural invasion. However, there is no evidence of lymphovascular space invasion. Two excised lymph nodes, level VI and IX, were negative for malignancy. The tumor is staged as pTNM T2. Tissue has been submitted for lung cancer mutation studies. The gross description of the specimen reveals a gray-white mass abutting the pleura and approaching the inked parenchymal margin. The remainder of the lung tissue shows signs of emphysematous change. No additional masses or discrete lymph nodes were identified.

The patient was diagnosed with a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the medial aspect of the apex of the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.0 x 1.5 x 1.5 cm. The tumor is unifocal and confined to the lung parenchyma, with no identified visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor is 4.8 cm from the bronchial margin and less than 1 mm from the pleural surface. No treatment effect was identified.
