Three peribronchial lymph nodes and two other lymph nodes (level 9 and 11) were negative for malignancy. The patient also exhibits emphysematous change and calcified granulomata, with no acid fast or fungal organisms identified. The tumor is staged as pT1a N0.

The patient underwent a wedge biopsy of the right lower lobe of the lung, revealing a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.3 cm in diameter, with associated fibrosis and emphysematous changes. The carcinoma extends up to, but not through, the visceral pleura and is highly suspicious for lymphovascular space invasion. The carcinoma is within 1 mm of the staple line on the wedge resection. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the examined lymph nodes (level 7, 9, and 4). The lobectomy specimen of the right lower lobe showed no residual carcinoma. The final pathological staging is pT1b N0. Clinical correlation and follow-up are recommended to rule out the possibility of metastasis.

The patient has a poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma, consistent with adenocarcinoma, located in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a tumor size of 2.7 x 2.0 x 1.2 cm. The carcinoma invades the visceral pleural surface, but there is no evidence of lymphovascular space invasion. Emphysematous changes are also observed. The stapled surgical margin of resection is negative for carcinoma. The mediastinal lymph nodes at levels 7, 4L, 4R, 6, and 10 are all negative for carcinoma. The pathologic stage is pT2a PL2 pNO.

The patient, a female, underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy due to lung cancer. The histopathological examination revealed a unifocal, subpleural adenocarcinoma of grade III (poorly differentiated) measuring 6.5 x 5.7 x 4.5 cm. The tumor was located 2.5 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.3 cm from the pleural surface. No visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion was identified. Eight lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastatic carcinoma. An area of central scarring was noted in the malignancy. The tumor was staged as pT2b, N0. An excised level 8 lymph node was negative for malignancy. The histologic appearance is consistent with a previous biopsy identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. No additional mutation studies were performed on the current specimen.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy, revealing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma forming a mass measuring 2.3 x 2.2 x 2.2 cm. The tumor was found abutting, but not invading, the visceral pleura, with benign bronchial and vascular resection margins. Three benign variably anthracotic lymph nodes were identified, with histologically unremarkable surrounding pulmonary parenchyma. An excised hilar lymph node showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The final TNM staging is pT1bN0M0, indicating a stage IA lung cancer. The tumor was unifocal, with no identified visceral pleural invasion or lymphatic vascular invasion. The closest margin to the tumor was 4 cm. Four regional lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastasis. No distant metastasis was identified. The patient's sample did not meet criteria for reflex EGFR and ALK testing.

The patient has a well-differentiated, acinar predominant invasive adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 4.0 x 3.8 x 2.2 cm. The proximal bronchial resection margin and pleural surface are negative for carcinoma, indicating no direct extension of the tumor or visceral pleura invasion. Lymphovascular space is also negative. No additional pathologic findings were identified. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 2, 4, 7, 10, and 11 on both left and right sides, as well as an additional level 11 node, were all negative for carcinoma. The pathologic stage is pT2a pN0.

The patient underwent a resection of the right upper lobe of the lung, revealing a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3 cm at its largest dimension, confined to the lung. No lymphovascular invasion was identified and both bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor involvement. Two negative peribronchial and intraparenchymal nodes were found. The tumor did not show any neoadjuvant treatment effect. The AJCC pathologic stage is T1b,N0. The gross examination of the resected lung showed a 114 gram, 15.5 X 12.5 X 4 cm upper lobe with a palpable mass adjacent to a sutured area. The tumor abutted the overlying pleural surface and was 1.5 cm away from the bronchial margin. The remaining lung tissue showed signs of atelectasis and emphysematous change at the apex. No additional masses were noted.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe of the lung due to a mass. The mass was found to be a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.0 x 2.8 x 2.7 cm, located posteriorly and laterally in the right lower lobe. The tumor extends through the elastic layer of the visceral pleura but does not penetrate it, and is 3.5 cm away from the bronchial margin. Multiple foci suspicious for vascular invasion were identified. No treatment effect was noted. The surgical margins were clear of tumor. One peribronchial lymph node was examined and found to be free of metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, lymph nodes from levels 9, 4, and 10 were excised and found to be benign. The overall stage of the tumor is pT2aNO. Minimal emphysematous change was also noted in the lung parenchyma. The diagnosis was confirmed by a second pathologist.

The patient underwent a right VATS procedure for a preoperative diagnosis of a right lung mass. Postoperative diagnosis revealed a pulmonary adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe, moderately to poorly differentiated, with a tumor size of 1.2 cm. The tumor was found to invade into, but not through, the visceral pleura, with a focus suggestive of lymphatic invasion. No venous invasion was detected. A total of 7 lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. All surgical margins were free of tumor. The TNM staging was pT2, pNO, pMX. The tumor cells were positive for cytokeratin 7, cytokeratin 20, Napsin-A, and showed strong nuclear staining with TTF-1. No significant fibrosis or inflammation was observed in the uninvolved lung. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. The patient is recommended for EGFR and KRAS mutation status determination for potential TKI therapy.

The patient has a history of right lower lobe lung non-small cell carcinoma and renal mass. Examination of multiple mediastinal lymph nodes (2R, 4R, level 7, 8, 9, 10) and right lower lobe wedge biopsy revealed invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of size 1.6 x 1.3 x 1.1 cm in the lung, with no direct tumor extension or lymphovascular space invasion. The visceral pleura is negative for carcinoma. One level 7 mediastinal lymph node was positive for metastatic carcinoma with a metastasis size of 0.2 cm, but no extracapsular extension was observed. The remaining lymph nodes and bronchial margin were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The pathologic stage is pTla pN2. No residual adenocarcinoma was identified in the completion lobectomy of the right lower lobe.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy with en bloc chest wall resection. The resected specimen revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of size 7x6x5cm, which extended through the parietal and visceral pleura into the chest wall. However, the surgical margins were free of tumor. No lymphatic or vascular invasion by the tumor was observed. A total of 16 lymph nodes were examined, including 13 N1 nodes and 3 N2 nodes, all of which were negative for metastasis. Immunohistochemical staining confirmed the histology as adenocarcinoma. The tumor was staged as pT3N0M0, corresponding to stage IIB. No distant metastasis was identified. EGFR alteration L858R was detected, indicating increased responsiveness to TKIs, while ALK gene rearrangement was not detected. The final diagnosis is poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the right upper lobe of the lung, stage IIB (pT3N0M0).

The patient underwent a wedge excision of the right upper lobe of the lung, revealing a 1.5 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, which is adjacent to but not invading the pleura, classified as AJCC stage T1a,N0. No residual carcinoma was identified in the excised lobe and the margins were free of neoplasm. A reactive hilar lymph node was found, but it did not contain metastatic neoplasm. The gross examination of the lung lobe showed no additional masses or lesions.

The patient has been diagnosed with pulmonary adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, characterized by diffuse mucin production. The primary tumor measures 3.7 cm and does not involve the overlying pleural surface. A secondary nodular area of pulmonary adenocarcinoma, similar in histology to the primary tumor, is located 1.2 cm from the main mass and measures 0.8 cm. The bronchial margin is free from surgical resection. Out of five peribronchial lymph nodes examined, one tested positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The pathological stage is T2a,N1. The interlobar lymph node tested negative for malignancy. The gross description of the lung mass and lymph node are also provided.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, characterized as poorly differentiated and unifocal, with a tumor size of 4.5 x 3.0 x 2.5 cm. The tumor is limited to the pulmonary parenchyma with no identified visceral pleural or lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor is 0.2 cm away from the bronchial and parenchymal margins and 0.7 cm away from the pleural surface. No metastatic carcinoma was identified in the excised lymph nodes from Station 10, interlobar, right paratracheal, and subcarinal regions. The tumor tested positive for cytokeratin 7 and TTF, and negative for cytokeratin 20 and p63, supporting the diagnosis of lung adenocarcinoma. The pTNM stage is pT2a N0. A lung cancer molecular panel is pending.

The patient has a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, arising within the background of bronchial alveolar carcinoma. The unifocal tumor measures 1.7 x 1.5 x 1.1 cm and is limited to the pulmonary parenchyma with no identified visceral pleural invasion. However, lymphovascular space invasion is present. The tumor is 2.6 cm from the bronchial margin, 4.1 cm from the parenchymal margin, and 0.8 cm from the pleural surface. Of the eight lymph nodes received, two contain metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, metastatic carcinoma is present in one of the three excised level 9 lymph nodes. The lung cancer molecular panel is pending. The pTNM stage is pT1 N1.

The patient was diagnosed with lung cancer, specifically a poorly differentiated carcinoma with features of adenosquamous carcinoma located in the left upper lobe of the lung. The tumor size was 3.7 x 3.5 x 3.3 cm and confined to the lung parenchyma with no identified visceral pleural invasion or unequivocal lymphovascular space invasion. The tumor was 3.2 cm from the bronchial margin and 1 mm from the pleural surface. No treatment effect was identified. The surgical margins were clear of tumor. Five lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The tumor cells were strongly positive for CK5/6 and CK7, with the majority of nuclei positive for p63 and approximately 10% positive for TTF1. The tumor demonstrated histologic and immunohistochemical features overlapping both adenocarcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma. The patient's pTN stage was pT2a N0. Emphysematous change was also noted.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy due to a right lung mass. The gross examination revealed a 9.5 x 8.5 x 6.5 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the middle lobe, with lymphovascular space invasion and tumor extension confined to the middle lobe. The tumor was found 2.6 cm from the bronchial margin and less than 1 mm from the pleural surface. Out of 10 lymph nodes received with the pneumonectomy specimen, 5 were found to contain metastatic carcinoma. Additionally, one out of three lymph nodes from level 7 showed metastatic carcinoma involvement. The tumor cells were positive for TTF1 and CK7 and negative for CK20, supporting the diagnosis of primary lung malignancy. The final stage is pT3N2.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy and thoracic lymphadenectomy due to a history of adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung. Pathological examination revealed a moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe, measuring 4 cm with negative margins. No malignancy was found in the peribronchial lymph node. A total of 16 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were benign. The final TNM staging is pT2aN0M0, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but less than 5 cm, with no regional lymph node metastasis or distant metastasis, classifying the cancer as stage IB. No visceral pleural invasion or lymphatic vascular invasion was identified. The tumor was unifocal and located 1.4 cm from the parenchymal staple line and 3.5 cm from the bronchial margin. No fresh tissue is available for ancillary testing.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a tumor size of 1.9x1.8x1.5cm. The tumor is unifocal and moderately to poorly differentiated (Grade II-III). No visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion was identified. The tumor is 2.5 cm from the parenchymal margin and 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. One level VII lymph node was found to be positive for metastatic carcinoma, while four lymph nodes from levels V and VI were negative for metastatic disease. The pTNM stage is pT1a N1.

The patient underwent a wedge excision of the left lower lobe of the lung, revealing a unifocal adenocarcinoma measuring 2.0 x 1.8 cm. The tumor is well differentiated, with no identified lymphovascular space invasion. Visceral pleura involvement is present, but the bronchial margin, stapled margin, and pleural margin are all negative for malignancy. No metastatic malignancy was found in the six examined lymph nodes. The completion lobectomy of the left lower lobe was negative for residual malignancy. Immunohistochemical stains were performed to exclude the possibility of renal carcinoma metastasis, with results supporting the diagnosis of lung adenocarcinoma. Despite the carcinoma's invasion of the visceral pleura, the actual pleural margin appears negative. The patient's clinical history includes a preoperative diagnosis of a left lower lobe lung mass, with the postoperative diagnosis confirming malignancy.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung due to a unifocal adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated, measuring 2.6 cm in diameter. The carcinoma extends up to, but not through, the visceral pleura, with the closest margin being less than 1 mm from the visceral pleural margin. No visceral pleural invasion or tumor extension was identified. The bronchial margin was free of carcinoma. One of two peribronchial lymph nodes showed presence of carcinoma, resulting in a staging of pT1b N1. The level 10, 7, 5, and 6 lymph nodes of the left lung showed reactive sinus histiocytosis and anthrasilicosis, but no metastatic carcinoma. Emphysematous changes were also noted. The diagnosis was reviewed and confirmed by Dr. [Name].

The patient was diagnosed with a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 5.5 x 5.5 x 5.4 cm. The tumor is confined to the lung, with no unequivocal lymphovascular space invasion identified. It penetrates through the elastic layer into the pleura but does not reach the pleural surface. The tumor is 1.6 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.2 cm from both the parenchymal margin and pleural surface. No metastatic carcinoma was found in the examined lymph nodes (0/7). The pathological stage is pT2b N0. An elastic stain was performed to support the diagnosis.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy due to a diagnosis of right upper lobe lung cancer. The postoperative pathological examination revealed a unifocal adenocarcinoma, poorly differentiated with solid, micropapillary, and papillary architecture, measuring 2 cm in greatest dimension, located in the right upper lobe. The tumor was confined to the lung with no identified visceral pleural invasion, but lymphovascular space invasion was present. The tumor was 7.2 cm from the bronchial margin and less than 1 mm from the pleural surface. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in multiple lymph nodes: one of one in level 11, four of four in level 10, one of one in the suprapulmonary vein, four of four in left level 7, and three of eleven in level 4. The total number of lymph nodes received was one, with one containing metastatic carcinoma. The background lung showed mild respiratory bronchiolitis. The pTNM stage was pT1a N3 MX. No acid-fast or fungal microorganisms were detected in the hyalinized granulomas.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the periphery of the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 5.5 x 4.3 x 3.8 cm. The tumor is unifocal and confined to the lung, with suspicious findings for lymphovascular space invasion. No visceral pleural invasion or treatment effect was identified. The tumor is 1.5 cm from the bronchial margin, 2.0 cm from the parenchymal (stapled) margin, and 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. Two lymph nodes were examined, none of which contained metastatic carcinoma. Other significant findings include patchy fibrosis and chronic inflammation. The tumor is staged as pT2b, N0. A mutation panel evaluation for lung carcinoma is pending.

The patient underwent a lobectomy and lymph node excisions of the left lower lobe of the lung. Two synchronous primary tumors were identified, diagnosed as pulmonary adenocarcinoma, with moderate and poorly differentiated grades. The larger tumor measured 2.7 cm and the smaller one 1.4 cm. Pleura was uninvolved and all margins were negative for malignancy. Nineteen lymph nodes were excised and all were benign. Pathologic tumor staging was pT1b (2) for the primary tumor, pNO (0/19) for regional lymph nodes, and the pathologic stage was IA. A single focus of large vessel invasion was noted. Immunohistochemical analysis confirmed the tumors as primary lung origin and excluded metastasis. Additional pathologic finding included distal emphysematous change.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe wedge excision, subsequent lobectomy, and lymph node excisions. The final pathology report revealed a moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma of 1.2 cm in greatest dimension, confined to the lung with no identified visceral pleural invasion. The tumor margins were negative, indicating no residual tumor at the surgical boundaries. Nineteen lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for metastatic carcinoma. Hyalinized nodules consistent with old granulomas were found in peribronchial and hilar lymph nodes. The pathologic tumor staging was classified as IA, with no lymphovascular invasion identified. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were uninvolved by carcinoma. Additional pathologic findings included emphysematous changes and hyalinized nodules within peribronchial and hilar lymph nodes, consistent with old granulomas.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a 3.2 cm nonsmall cell carcinoma, specifically adenocarcinoma, that was poorly differentiated. The tumor did not show pleural involvement and the resection margin was negative. No evidence of malignancy was found in the lymph nodes from various stations (7, 4R, 12) and peribronchial resection. The final TNM staging was pT2aN0M0, indicating a stage IB cancer. The tumor was unifocal and there was no evidence of visceral pleural invasion or lymphatic vascular invasion. The histological grade was G3 out of G4. No distant metastasis was identified. The tissue block is available for ancillary testing.

The patient underwent a lung lobectomy for a right lung mass. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 3.5 x 3.0 x 1.0 cm, located peripherally and unifocal. No visceral pleural invasion, lymphovascular space invasion, or tumor extension was identified. The tumor was 1.5 cm away from both the bronchial and parenchymal margins and less than 0.1 cm from the pleural surface. Eight lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastatic carcinoma. Non-caseating granulomatous inflammation was observed in several lymph nodes, suggesting possible sarcoidosis or infection. The EGFR mutation was not detected, but a KRAS mutation (G12D) was identified. No ALK rearrangement was found, but additional copies of the ALK region were observed in 80% of cells. The clinical significance of this is unclear. The patient's pTNM stage is pT2, N0. Further clinical correlation is suggested.

The patient underwent a wedge biopsy of the right lower and upper lung lobes. The right lower lobe showed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.7 x 2.5 x 2.0 cm, with visceral pleural invasion but no lymphovascular space invasion or tumor extension. The tumor was 0.8 cm from the stapled margin. The right upper lobe showed a poorly differentiated squamous carcinoma, measuring 1.0 x 0.9 x 0.7 cm, with no visceral pleural invasion, lymphovascular space invasion, or tumor extension. The tumor was 0.4 cm from the parenchymal stapled margin and 0.8 cm from the pleural surface. Excisional biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 4 and 7 were negative for tumor. The adenocarcinoma was positive for CK7 and TTF1, and negative for CK20 and p63, while the squamous carcinoma was positive for p63 and negative for CK7, CK20, CDX-2, and TTF1. The findings suggest a primary pulmonary origin for the adenocarcinoma, and a poorly differentiated nature for the squamous carcinoma.

The patient was diagnosed with a right lung upper lobe nodule. Upon examination, an adenocarcinoma of moderate differentiation was found in the posterior apex, subpleural region of the right upper lobe, measuring 2.5 x 2.3 x 1.6 cm. The malignancy extends to, but not through, the visceral pleura, with no lymphovascular space invasion identified. The tumor is 5.2 cm away from the bronchial margin and less than 1 mm from the pleural surface. No treatment effect was identified. At least 20 lymph nodes were received, none of which contained metastatic carcinoma. The lymph nodes showed reactive hyperplasia and scattered noncaseating granulomata. Acid fast bacilli and fungi tests were negative. The pTN stage is pT1b N0. The malignancy has a prominent fibrous stroma with a central area of scarring.

The patient has a 2.0 x 2.0 x 2.5 cm adenocarcinoma in the lower lobe of the left lung, with a mixed subtype that includes kribriform, solid, micropapillary, and bronchioloalveolar carcinoma (BAC) features. The cancer has infiltrated the visceral pleura and has resulted in lymphangiosis carcinomatosa. The tumor is classified as pT2, indicating its size and extent, and pN2, indicating the involvement of 21 out of 33 regional lymph nodes. The presence of metastasis in the pericardium is denoted as pM1. The grade of the tumor is G3, indicating a high degree of abnormality in the cancer cells.

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring approximately 5.0 cm in diameter, with acinar, papillary, solid, and bronchioloalveolar carcinoma (BAC) components. The tumor has infiltrated the visceral pleura and there are several tumor nodules present in the same lobe. The pathological staging is pT4, pN0 (0/24 lymph nodes involved), pMx, G2, indicating a locally advanced tumor with no detected regional lymph node involvement. The EGFR mutation analysis, performed via Sanger sequencing of exons 18 to 21, was negative. It should be noted that according to the current TNM classification, the tumor would be classified as pT3.

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma of the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 3.7 X 2.8 X 3.0 cm, with components of papillary, acinar, and mucinous histology. The tumor has infiltrated the parietal pleura, classifying it as pT3. No lymph nodes are involved out of the 42 examined (pN0). The presence of distant metastasis is not determined (pMx). The tumor is moderately differentiated (G2).

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 10.0 X 8.0 X 7.0 cm, with partial neuroendocrine characteristics. The tumor has infiltrated the visceral pleura and is staged as pT2, pN2 (10/35 lymph nodes positive), pMx, G3. Immunohistochemistry reveals the tumor cells are positive for CK7, CK18, CEA, and partially positive for TTF1, NSE, and Chromogranin A. The tumor cells are negative for synaptophysin and CD56.

The patient has a 4.0 X 3.0 X 5.0 cm adenocarcinoma tumor, primarily papillary with some acinar features, located in the upper lobe of the left lung, which measures 19.0 X 11.0 X 7.0 cm. The tumor is classified as pT2, indicating its size and extent, and pN2, indicating the presence of cancer in 7 out of 30 regional lymph nodes. The distant metastasis cannot be assessed (pMx) and the tumor grade is G2, indicating moderately differentiated cells.

The patient has a 2.5 X 2.5 X 1.5 cm adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype (acinar, papillary, solid, BAC) in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 15.0 X 9.0 X 6.0 cm. The cancer has infiltrated the visceral pleura, classified as pT2, pN2 (8/28 lymph nodes involved), pMx, G3. Supplementary EGFR mutation analysis reveals a positive result, specifically p.E746_A750del (c.2235_49del) mutation.

The patient has a 6.0 X 5.5 X 4.5 cm adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung, with visceral pleural infiltration, classified as pT2, pN0 (0/22), pMx, G3. Immunohistochemistry shows the tumor cells are positive for CK7 and CEA, with some cells positive for TTF1 and Vimentin, but negative for Chromogranin A, Synaptophysin, NSE, CK13, CK14, and CD56. The Ki-67 proliferation index is 40-50%.

The patient has a 6.0 cm adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, predominantly papillary with partial acinar and bronchioloalveolar carcinoma (BAC), located in the upper lobe of the left lung, measuring 17.0 x 16.0 x 5.0 cm. The tumor is classified as pT2, pN0 (0/7 lymph nodes involved), pMx (metastasis cannot be assessed), and G2 (moderately differentiated).

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma (predominantly papillary, partially solid, acinar, and bronchioloalveolar carcinoma) in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 4.0 X 3.5 X 2.0 cm within a lung tissue of 15.0 X 10.0 x 7.0 cm. The tumor has infiltrated the visceral pleura, classified as pT2. No regional lymph nodes are involved (pN0, with 0 out of 20 nodes affected), and the presence of distant metastasis is not determined (pMx). The tumor is moderately differentiated (G2).

The patient has a papillary adenocarcinoma located in the upper lobe of the left lung, measuring 8.0 X 7.0 X 4.0 cm within a lung mass of 22.0 X 15.0 X 7.0 cm. The cancer has infiltrated the visceral pleura. The tumor is classified as pT2, pN0 (0/37 lymph nodes involved), pMx (metastasis cannot be assessed), and G2 (moderately differentiated). The site code is C34.1.

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma (partially papillary, acinar, solid) in the right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 4.8 X 3.5 x 3.0 cm within a total lung size of 14.5 X 11.0 X 6.0 cm. There is no infiltration of the visceral pleura. The tumor is classified as pT2, pN1 (with 2 out of 54 lymph nodes involved), pMx, and G3.

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma (partially papillary, micropapillary, acinar, solid) in the lower lobe of the left lung, measuring 3.3 X 3.2 X 2.9 cm within a lung mass of 17.0 X 12.0 X 10.0 cm. The cancer has infiltrated the visceral pleura, classified as pT2, pN0 (0/11 lymph nodes involved), pMx (metastasis cannot be assessed), and G3 (high grade).

The patient has a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma, predominantly papillary and micropapillary, partially solid, located in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor measures 3.5 X 3.1 X 2.9 cm within a lung tissue of 12.0 X 13.0 X 4.0 cm. The cancer has infiltrated the visceral pleura. The pathological staging is pT2, pN2 with 37 out of 39 lymph nodes involved, and the distant metastasis status is unknown (pMx). The tumor grade is G3, indicating a high degree of abnormality.

The patient has a predominantly acinar adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 6.5 x 5.0 x 4.5 cm, with visceral pleural infiltration. The tumor is classified as pT2, pN0 (with 0 out of 14 lymph nodes involved), and pMx, indicating that the presence of distant metastasis cannot be assessed. The tumor grade is G2.

The patient has a 6.5 x 6.5 x 5.0 cm adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, classified as pT2b, pN1 (6/28), pMx, G3. The tumor does not infiltrate the visceral pleura. Immunohistochemistry shows the tumor cells are positive for CK7, but negative for CK5/6, CK14, SP-A, TTF1, CD56, Chromogranin A, and Synaptophysin. The Ki-67 proliferation index is 40%.

The patient has two adenocarcinomas in the right lower lobe of the lung, with the larger tumor measuring 2.5 x 2.2 x 2.1 cm and the smaller one measuring 1.5 x 1.4 x 1.3 cm. The larger tumor has infiltrated and breached the visceral pleura, indicating a pathological stage of pT3. There is no evidence of regional lymph node involvement (pN0), but the presence of distant metastasis is undetermined (pMx). The tumors are grade 3, indicating a high degree of abnormality.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. Biopsies were taken from various sites and a portion of the right 6th rib was excised. Lymph nodes from levels 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, and 4R were also excised. The biopsies and the rib showed no specific pathologic abnormality and no tumor was seen. All lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. A lobectomy of the right lower lobe revealed a poorly-differentiated non-small cell carcinoma measuring 2.5 cm with a predominantly solid architectural pattern and abundant areas of necrosis. No angiolymphatic space invasion was identified and the visceral pleura, bronchial and vascular margins were negative for tumor. The peribronchial and intrapulmonary lymph nodes were also negative for metastatic carcinoma. The final staging is pT1 N0 MX.

The patient has been diagnosed with lung cancer. The pathological examination of the excised right 6th rib showed no tumor. The right upper lobe wedge resection revealed a subpleural scar with no tumor. The right lower lobe lobectomy showed a grade III, 4 cm acinar type adenocarcinoma invading the visceral pleura, with bronchial and vascular margins free of tumor. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in two out of four lymph nodes. The uninvolved lung showed mild emphysema. The level 7 lymph node excision revealed metastatic adenocarcinoma in one out of five lymph nodes. No tumor was seen in the excised level 4, 10, and 3 lymph nodes. The cancer is staged as pT2,N2,Mx.

The patient, diagnosed with Lung CA, underwent a biopsy of multiple lymph nodes and a lobectomy of the right middle lobe. The biopsy of the 4R, additional 4R, level 7, 4L, 2R, level 11, and 10R lymph nodes showed no presence of tumor in any of the examined nodes. The lobectomy of the right middle lobe revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 6 cm, with no evidence of visceral pleural invasion or lymphovascular space invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. Three peribronchial lymph nodes were also examined and found to be free of tumor. The pathological staging is pT2NoMx.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. The resected 6th rib shows bone and hypercellular bone marrow with trilineage hematopoiesis and lymphoid aggregates. The excised level 9 and 4R lymph nodes show no signs of tumor. The lobectomy of the right lung's upper lobe reveals a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with necrosis, measuring 2.0 cm in greatest dimension, with an acinar growth pattern. Lymphovascular invasion is present, but the tumor does not invade into the visceral pleura. The bronchial and vascular resection margins are free of tumor. Seven hilar and peribronchial lymph nodes show no signs of tumor. The excised pre-carinal lymph node is positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The excised level 7 lymph node shows no signs of tumor. The pathological staging is pT1 N2 Mx.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. The pathology report indicates metastatic carcinoma in multiple lymph nodes: five out of fifteen in level 7, two out of three in 10R, one out of eight in level 11, and one out of nine in 4R. The right middle and lower lobe of the lung show adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, with the 8.0 cm moderately differentiated middle lobe carcinoma featuring acinar, papillary, and lepidic growth patterns. The carcinoma invades into the visceral pleura and lymphovascular invasion is identified. However, surgical resection margins are free of carcinoma. No tumor was seen in the portion of the 6th rib and level 9 lymph node. The final pTNM staging is T2 N2 M1.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. Examination of multiple lymph nodes (10R, level 8R, 11R, 4R, 2R, level 7, and 10R) revealed no presence of tumor. A well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.5 cm was identified in the unspecified lobectomy of the right lung, with no angiolymphatic invasion detected. The visceral pleura, bronchial and vascular margins were found to be free of tumor. The final staging is pT1 N0 Mx, indicating a localized tumor with no lymph node involvement or distant metastasis.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. The pathological examination of the excised tissues revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with clear cell changes, measuring 7 cm, in the right lung. The tumor did not invade the visceral pleura and the bronchial and vascular margins were negative. No tumor was detected in the excised portion of the 6th rib, mediastinal lymph node level 9, right level 4 lymph nodes, level 7 lymph nodes, and fifteen peribronchial lymph nodes.

The patient has been diagnosed with lung adenocarcinoma, a type of lung cancer, which has resulted in a malignant pleural effusion. The tumor has invaded the chest wall and skin, causing a fistula in the chest wall. The tumor is positive for CK7, TTF-1, Cam 5.2, cytokeratin AE1/AE3, and vimentin, and negative for MA903, CK20, CD31, CD34, CD45, CD20, Calretinin, EMA, Melan A, HMB-45, and S-100 protein, supporting the diagnosis of primary lung adenocarcinoma. The tumor is classified as pTNM: T4 N0 Mx, indicating its size and extent of spread.

The patient has been diagnosed with right lung cancer. A lobectomy was performed on the right upper lobe, revealing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, non-mucinous bronchioloalveolar subtype, measuring 3.7 cm in greatest dimension. The tumor has invaded into the visceral pleura, indicating a T2 classification. Vascular invasion was identified, but arterial invasion was absent. The margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. A total of 84 regional lymph nodes were examined across various levels, none of which showed any signs of tumor metastasis. The final pTNM staging is T2 N0 Mx.

The patient has been diagnosed with left lung adenocarcinoma, WHO acinar subtype, which is poorly differentiated and measures 8.5 cm. The carcinoma does not invade the visceral pleura, but angiolymphatic invasion is identified. The surgical resection margins are free of carcinoma. Metastatic carcinoma is found in 4 out of 12 peribronchial lymph nodes and 7 out of 53 regional lymph nodes. No tumor is seen in the portion of the 6th rib, level 9, 12, 8, 7, and 6 lymph nodes, and the new bronchial margin. The diaphragmatic adhesion is fibrous. The pTNM staging is T2 N2 Mx.

The patient has been diagnosed with lung cancer. The pathological examination of the right upper lobe revealed a 6.5 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, which does not involve the pleura surface and shows no angiolymphatic invasion. The surgical resection margins are free of carcinoma. A total of 52 regional lymph nodes were examined, including nodes from the 6th rib, 10R, 11R, level 7, and level 4R, all of which showed no evidence of tumor involvement. The final pathological staging is pTNM: T2 N0 Mx, indicating a primary tumor of significant size without regional lymph node metastasis and an undetermined distant metastasis status.

The patient has been diagnosed with lung cancer. The pathology report indicates the presence of an invasive poorly differentiated adenosquamous carcinoma, measuring 6.5 cm, located in the upper lobe of the right lung. The carcinoma has invaded through the visceral pleura, but angiolymphatic invasion is not identified. The bronchial and vascular margins are free of carcinoma. Metastatic carcinoma was found in two out of two 10R lymph nodes. No tumor was seen in one level nine lymph node, seven level seven lymph nodes, one level 11 lymph node, one level 11 lymph node at the bifurcation of the middle and lower lobe, and five parabronchial lymph nodes. The final staging is pT2 N1 Mx.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy for lung cancer. The final pathology report revealed a 2.8 cm adenocarcinoma confined to the lung, with no extension to the pleura or other structures. The tumor was moderately differentiated (Grade 2). All margins, including bronchial, parenchymal, and vascular, were uninvolved. No venous or arterial invasion was identified. A total of 12 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for tumor involvement. Additional findings included atypical adenomatous hyperplasia, mild emphysema, and pleural fibrosis with focal calcifications. The pathological staging was pT1 N0.

The patient underwent a left lung lobectomy due to lung cancer. The gross examination revealed a 2.5 cm adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, which was moderately to poorly differentiated and confined to the lung with no identified extension to the pleura or other structures. The bronchial, parenchymal, and vascular margins were uninvolved, with the tumor 4 cm from the bronchial margin. No venous or arterial invasion was observed. Multiple lymph nodes were examined and all were negative for tumor. The pTNM stage was pT1 N0. Fine needle aspiration biopsy confirmed the presence of malignant cells, indicative of non-small cell carcinoma with features of adenocarcinoma of the lung. Immunohistochemistry was positive for cytokeratin 7, and negative for CK20, CK5/6, and P63. TTF-1 was also negative.

The patient has a history of right lung cancer. The biopsy of the right diaphragmatic nodule showed fibroadipose tissue with mesothelial proliferation and chronic inflammation, but no malignancy was identified. Three lymph nodes from the right superior hilar were negative for tumor. The lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal papillary features. A matted lymph node from the right upper node and a lymph node from the right posterior superior hilar were both negative for tumor. The tumor from the right upper lobe of the lung was 4.3 cm in size, invaded the visceral pleura, but did not extend to other structures. All margins were uninvolved and there was no venous or arterial invasion. No lymph nodes were involved. The tumor was staged as pT2 N0 according to the AJCC 6th edition. The needle aspiration biopsy of the right upper lobe of the lung was positive for adenocarcinoma, consistent with a lung primary. The tumor showed gland formation and was moderately differentiated. A TTF-1 stain was positive. The tumor morphology was dissimilar to the tumor in the kidney. Multiple lymph nodes from various locations were negative for tumor and showed anthracosis.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with left lower lobe lung cancer. Post-operative examination of multiple lymph nodes (Level 9L, Level 6, Level 5, Posterior Hilar, and Superior Segmental) revealed no presence of tumor. The superior segment of the left lung lower lobe showed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma spanning 1.5 cm in dimension and focally penetrating the visceral pleura. The inked surgical margin of resection was negative for tumor. The final diagnosis was a pT2, pNo, MX stage adenocarcinoma of the lung. A fine needle aspiration biopsy of the left posterior lung confirmed the presence of a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, supported by strong CK7 and TTF-1 positivity, faint P53 positivity, and negative mesothelial markers. A noncontrast chest CT revealed a noncalcified soft tissue mass density in the left lower lobe, suggestive of neoplasm.

The patient has a history of left lung cancer and underwent a lobectomy. The frozen section diagnosis showed no tumor presence. The resected 5th and 6th rib necks were also negative for tumor, showing hematopoietic marrow. The left lower lobe of the lung showed an infiltrating, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal bronchoalveolar features measuring 3.3 x 3 x 1.5 cm. The tumor closely approached but did not invade the visceral pleura, and no vascular invasion was seen. Bronchial and vascular margins, as well as seven lobar lymph nodes, were negative for tumor. The background lung showed scattered small non-caseating granulomas associated with fragments of weakly polarizable material. No organisms were identified on special stains. The pTNM stage is pT2a pNO MX (Stage IB).

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy for adenocarcinoma. The tumor measured 3.8 cm and was moderately differentiated, confined to the lung with no extension to the pleura or other structures. All margins were uninvolved, with the closest being 3.5 cm from the bronchial margin. No venous or arterial invasion was observed. Two out of three N1 lymph nodes were involved, specifically the level 10 node and a perihilar lymph node on the lobectomy specimen. However, no N2 or N3 lymph nodes were involved. No separate tumor nodule or pleural invasion was identified. The uninvolved lung was unremarkable. The final pathological staging was pT2 N1 MX.

The patient has a history of right lung cancer. Surgical resection of regional lymph nodes and right lower lobe of the lung was performed. Gross examination revealed multiple anthracotic lymph nodes in various regions, all of which were negative for tumor. The right lower lobe of the lung showed a well-differentiated bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, Grade I, with a maximum diameter of 12.5 cm and an additional smaller multinodular area of histologically identical tumor. The tumor was confined to the lung, extending to but not invading the pleural surface. The bronchial and vascular margins, as well as a single hilar lymph node, were free of disease. The final pathological staging is pT3 N0 MX.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with broncho-alveolar features. The tumor measures 4 cm in maximum dimension, extends to the pleural surface with pleural puckering, but does not involve the visceral pleura and is 4 cm from the bronchial margin. The uninvolved pulmonary parenchyma shows small non-caseating granulomata, negative for pathogenic organisms, and mild emphysematous changes. All surgical margins are negative for tumor. Multiple intralobar and superior segmental lymph nodes were examined, all of which were anthracotic and negative for tumor. The pathologic stage is pT2a N0 MX.

The patient underwent a right middle lobe lobectomy due to a mass. The resected lung specimen measured 10 x 4.5 x 2.5 cm with a tumor of 1.8 x 1.3 x 0.9 cm, which was identified as a moderately differentiated gland forming and papillary adenocarcinoma, Grade II. The tumor was confined within the lung, approaching within 4 mm of the parenchymal margin and over 2 cm from the bronchial margin. Vascular margins and four hilar lymph nodes were free of disease. Two lymph nodes from the right middle and lower lobes showed no evidence of malignancy. The final pathological staging is pTla NO MX.

The patient underwent a lung lobectomy for left lung cancer. Frozen section analysis of lymph nodes from levels 9L, 5, and 6, as well as a posterior interlobular node, showed no evidence of tumor. An anterior mediastinal mass was identified as an epithelioid thymoma, with classification pending permanent sections. The left upper lobe lobectomy specimen revealed a 2.5 cm adenocarcinoma, with a 0.3 cm focus of metastatic carcinoma involving one of five hilar lymph nodes. The tumor was 0.4 cm from the parenchymal resection margin and 0.9 cm from the bronchial margin. The tumor was staged as pT2a pN1. The thymoma was classified as Type AB with microscopic transcapsular invasion and involved margins. The lung showed mild emphysema.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe, with biopsy of various margins and lymph nodes. The peribronchial soft tissue, mediastinal, right upper lobe, bronchial, and pulmonary vein margins were all negative for neoplasm. The right lower lobe showed adenocarcinoma with predominantly acinar (60%) and micropapillary (40%) patterns, atypical alveolar hyperplasia, and centrilobular emphysema. Nine peribronchiolar lymph nodes showed scattered calcified granulomas but were negative for neoplasm. Lymph nodes at levels 11, 10R, 7, and 4R were also negative for neoplasm. The tumor was located in the right lower lobe, measured 5 cm, and showed no vascular or lymphatic invasion. The tumor invaded the mediastinal pleura, but the inked surface was negative for neoplasm. The pathologic stage was pT3 N0, Stage 2B. A GMS stain revealed rare yeast forms consistent with Histoplasma in the peribronchiolar lymph nodes. The tumor will be sent for EGFR mutational analysis.

The patient underwent excision of lymph nodes from various locations (4R, #7, L4, R2, L9, level 6, level 7), all of which were negative for neoplasm. A lobectomy of the left lower lobe revealed invasive adenocarcinoma of the acinar type, with two separate foci of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia, organizing acute fibrinous pneumonia, pleural fibrous adhesions, focal bronchiectasis with calcified and hyalinized granulomas, and peribronchial lymph nodes negative for neoplasm. Excision of "granuloma content" showed necrotizing granulomas with calcification, negative for neoplasm. Further lymph node excisions (level 12, L11) revealed calcified hyalinized nodules, negative for neoplasm. A wedge excision of the left lower lobe showed patchy organizing fibrinous pneumonia and features of airway remodeling. Excision of a portion of the seventh rib showed no significant pathologic changes. The tumor was located in the left lower lobe, measuring 4.5 X 3.2 x 3.2 cm, with no identified vascular or lymphatic invasion, and negative bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins. The pathologic stage is Stage IB (T2a NO MX). Further tests are pending.

The patient has a secondary malignant neoplasm in the right lung, specifically in the right middle lobe. The tumor is an adenocarcinoma of mixed type with papillary, bronchioloalveolar, and acinar patterns, measuring 2.1 x 1.2 x 0.5 cm. There is no evidence of vascular or lymphatic invasion, and all margins (bronchial, vascular, parenchymal, and pleura/soft tissue) are negative for neoplasm. Four peribronchiolar lymph nodes show anthracosis but are negative for neoplasm. Additionally, lymph nodes #7, #8, #11, #10 are benign anthracotic. The pathologic stage is pT1b N0 M0, corresponding to Stage IA. The gross examination of the right middle lobectomy specimen reveals a yellow firm mass with a focal area of necrosis, not involving the bronchus. The remaining lung parenchyma appears normal.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed an adenocarcinoma with acinar and bronchioloalveolar components, measuring 2.2 cm at its greatest dimension. The tumor was located in the anterior segment, abutting the pleura and segmental bronchi, but was not found to invade any vessels or lymphatics. The bronchial, vascular, parenchymal, and pleura/soft tissue margins were all negative for carcinoma. Two peribronchiolar lymph nodes were also negative for carcinoma. Mild centrilobular emphysema was noted. Excised lymph nodes at levels 10 and 11 were negative for neoplasm. The tumor will be sent for EGFR mutational analysis. The pathologic stage is Stage IA (pT1b N0).

The patient underwent a right lung lobectomy with wedge excisions from the upper and lower lobes. The upper lobe wedge (Part A) revealed an adenocarcinoma with acinar, micropapillary, and bronchioloalveolar cell carcinoma components, a pulmonary parenchyma hamartoma, and centrilobular emphysema. The lower lobe lobectomy (Part B) also showed adenocarcinoma with similar components, centrilobular emphysema, and negative peribronchial lymph nodes. Excised lymph nodes (Parts C, E-G) were negative for neoplasm. The lower lobe wedge (Part D) showed centrilobular emphysema with focal organizing pneumonia, chronic bronchiolitis, foreign body giant cell reaction, and focal atypical adenomatous hyperplasia. The tumors were predominantly invasive, located in different pulmonary lobes, and classified as p stage IIIA (T4 N0 MX). EGFR mutation analysis is pending.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right middle lobe of the lung, with multiple lymph nodes and tissue margins excised. Pathological examination revealed adenocarcinoma in the middle lobe, characterized by solid (60%), acinar (20%), and cribriform (20%) patterns. The tumor measured 4.1 x 4 x 3.7 cm and was located less than 0.1 cm from the pleura, 0.2 cm from the parenchymal margin, and 0.3 cm from the bronchial margin. No vascular or lymphatic invasion was observed. Atypical cells were found in the pulmonary arterial and vein margins, but were interpreted as negative for neoplasm. The bronchial margin and additional lower lobe margins were negative for neoplasm. The lymph nodes excised showed anthracosis but were negative for neoplasm. Immunohistochemical analysis showed the tumor cells were positive for CAM 5.2 and TTF-1, with focal positivity for synaptophysin, and negative for chromogranin, p63, and CD56. The tumor will be sent for EGFR mutational analysis. The pathological stage is pT2a N0, Stage IB.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed an adenocarcinoma with solid, acinar, and bronchioloalveolar cell carcinoma components. The tumor measured 3.5 X 2.8 X 2.5 cm and was located in the left upper lobe. It invaded the visceral pleura but did not show vascular invasion. Lymphatic invasion is still pending. The bronchial and vascular margins were negative for tumor cells. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in peribronchial lymph nodes and 11L, #5 lymph nodes, but 10L and 12L lymph nodes were negative for neoplasm. The tumor cells were immunoreactive to TTF-1 and p-63. No EGFR alteration was detected. The patient also had centrilobular emphysema, pulmonary hemosiderosis, and necrotizing granulomas in peribronchial lymph nodes. The pathologic stage is p stage IIIA (pT2a N2 MX).

The patient underwent excision of multiple lymph nodes (#7, L4, R4, R2, #10, R4, level 7) which were all found to be negative for neoplasm. A lobectomy of the right upper lobe revealed an adenocarcinoma of mixed type with solid, acinar, and bronchioloalveolar cell carcinoma patterns and clear cell features, measuring 6.3 x 2.9 x 2.0 cm. The tumor infiltrates through the visceral pleura and is present at the pleural surface, with vascular invasion present but no lymphatic invasion identified. The bronchial and vascular margins were negative for neoplasm. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one peribronchial lymph node and centrolobular emphysema was also noted. The tumor cells were immunoreactive to TTF-1 and negative for p63. The pathologic stage is p stage IIB (T2b N1 MX). EGFR mutation analysis is pending.

The patient underwent a series of lymph node excisions and a partial chest wall excision, all of which tested negative for malignancy. The right upper lobe lobectomy revealed an invasive acinar type adenocarcinoma, with surgical margins negative for neoplasm, two lymph nodes negative for carcinoma, and emphysematous changes. The tumor, located in the right upper lobe, measured 3.2 X 3.1 x 2.1 cm, with no identified vascular or lymphatic invasion. The bronchial, vascular, parenchymal, and pleura/soft tissue margins were all negative. The pathologic stage is pT2a pNO pMX Stage 1b. The clinical diagnosis is lung cancer. The gross description of the specimens revealed various sizes of tan-brown and yellow-tan soft tissue fragments, with the largest being a right upper lobectomy specimen measuring 15 X 11 X 3 cm. The tumor was poorly circumscribed, firm, gray-white with central necrosis, and caused retraction of the overlying pleura without gross invasion. Severe emphysematous changes were noted, mostly in the upper portion of the lung.

The patient underwent a right lung lobectomy, with a wedge excision of the lower lobe and removal of lymph nodes #4, #7, #11, and 10R. The lower lobe and lymph nodes were found to be negative for neoplasm. However, the upper lobe exhibited an adenocarcinoma with a lipidic pattern, measuring 2.5 cm at its largest dimension. No vascular or lymphatic invasion was observed, and all margins were negative. The tumor was located in the right upper lobe and was classified as Stage IIA (T1b N0 M0) according to the AJCC. The gross examination revealed two nodules in the lower lobe and a tumor in the upper lobe abutting the pleural surface. The lymph nodes resembled tan-black nodules and were totally submitted in cassettes.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma in the right lung's superior segment, characterized by a micropapillary predominant pattern. The tumor measures 2x2x1cm and is located in the right lower lobe. There is evidence of lymphatic invasion, but no vascular invasion was identified. All margins, including bronchial, vascular, parenchymal, and pleura/soft tissue, are negative. The pathologic stage is IIA (T1a N1 MX). Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in the R11 SUMP lymph nodes, but the R7 and R11 lymph nodes were negative for neoplasm. The adenocarcinoma is composed of 65% micropapillary, 30% acinar, and 5% lepidic patterns. The bronchial margin is negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lung resection due to a mass. The final diagnosis revealed a papillary predominant adenocarcinoma with acinar (30%), micropapillary (10%), and lepidic (10%) patterns. Other findings include centrilobular emphysema and organizing pneumonia. The tumor size is 5.5 X 3 x 2 cm and the parenchymal margin is negative for neoplasm. Further assessment of pleural invasion will be conducted with Movats stains and EGFR mutational analysis will be performed on the tumor. The gross description of the resected lung lobe revealed a tan gelatinous area of consolidation with a friable cavity, a lobulated mass within this area, and a separate small tan firm nodule. The lung parenchyma showed areas of atelectasis and hemorrhage.

The patient underwent a wedge excision of the right lung, upper lobe, revealing a 1.6 cm adenocarcinoma with solid predominant (40%), acinar (40%), and lepidic (20%) patterns. No invasion into or through the pleura was observed and the parenchymal margin of excision was negative for neoplasm. Mild centrilobular emphysema was also noted. A lymph node excision at level 10R showed a hylanized lymph node, negative for neoplasm. Further studies will be conducted to determine the origin of the adenocarcinoma. The clinical diagnosis was lung nodules. The gross description of the lung revealed a stellate tan-gray firm nodule in a puckered area of the pleura, with no other masses, lesions, or nodules present. The lymph node was tan-black and measured 0.4 X 0.3 X 0.2 cm.

The patient's right lower lobe, superior segment of the lung was found to have a mucinous adenocarcinoma, acinar-predominant, measuring 7.5x6.4x4.7cm. The tumor invades into the visceral pleura but is not present at the pleural surface. No vascular invasion was observed, but lymphatic invasion is present. All margins, including bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal, were negative. The pathologic stage is p Stage IIIA (T3 NO MX). Additionally, centrilobular emphysema with fibroelastosis, extensive chronic bronchiolitis with rare ill-formed non-necrotizing granulomas, and organizing acute fibrinous pleuritis were noted. Lymph nodes from various locations were excised and found to be negative for neoplasm. The pleura adjacent to the right lower lobe also showed signs of organizing acute fibrinous pleuritis.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, with multiple lymph nodes also excised. Pathological examination revealed an adenocarcinoma in the upper lobe, with two separate tumor nodules, the largest measuring 3.7 cm. The tumor did not invade the visceral pleura or show lymph-vascular invasion. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being the parenchymal margin at a distance of 3.4 cm. No malignancy was found in the lymph nodes. The pathological staging is Stage IIB (pT3, pNO). Additional findings include centrilobular emphysema. EGFR mutational analysis was performed and no EGFR alteration was detected. The clinical diagnosis is lung nodules.

The patient has an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the left lower lung lobe, measuring 6.0x3.4x2.5cm, with a background of multifocal bronchioloalveolar carcinoma. Angiolymphatic invasion is present, and the visceral pleural margin is positive for tumor. However, the bronchial margin and two peribronchial lymph nodes are negative for tumor. The hilar margin is also negative for tumor, but the surrounding lung is positive for adenocarcinoma in a background of bronchioloalveolar carcinoma. The 10L lymph node is negative for metastasis. The 6th rib shows orderly hemopoiesis and is negative for malignancy. The pathologic stage is pT2N0Mx, indicating the absence of metastasis to lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a pneumonectomy, with specimens taken from various locations including the subcarinal and right distal paratracheal lymph nodes, superior segment of the right upper lobe, 6th rib, and right lung. The adenocarcinoma, predominantly moderately differentiated with some poorly differentiated areas, was found in the right lung, spanning both the upper and lower lobes, measuring 9.0 cm in greatest dimension. The tumor was 1.5 cm from the bronchial margin, which was negative for invasive carcinoma. Angiolymphatic invasion was present. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in two of twelve peribronchial lymph nodes. The non-neoplastic lung showed emphysematous changes. No malignancy was identified in the subcarinal and 10R lymph nodes. The pathologic stage is pT2 N2 MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a left upper lung tumor. The biopsy of the 4R and 4L lymph nodes showed no signs of carcinoma. The wedge biopsy of the left upper lobe revealed an invasive, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of mixed types (acinar and bronchioloalveolar), measuring 2.0 cm in maximum dimension. No carcinoma was identified in the second wedge biopsy of the left upper lobe, which showed mild emphysematous changes. The lobectomy of the left upper lobe showed no residual carcinoma, and the bronchial margin was free of tumor. Nine lymph nodes were negative for carcinoma. The pathological staging is pT1N0MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for non-small cell cancer of the right upper lobe lung. The pathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe, measuring 2.0 x 1.7 x 1.5 cm, located 4.0 cm from the bronchial margin and 0.4 cm from the pleural surface. The bronchial margins were uninvolved and there was no angiolymphatic invasion or visceral pleural involvement. Four hilar lymph nodes and three mediastinal lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for tumor. Additionally, one contralateral mediastinal/hilar lymph node was also negative for tumor. Non-neoplastic lung showed signs of pneumonia and atypical alveolar cell hyperplasia. The final pathological staging was pT1 MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe due to a lung mass. The pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with micropapillary features, measuring 4.2cm in greatest dimension and 3.5cm x 3cm in additional dimensions. No pleural invasion or angiolymphatic invasion was identified. The bronchial margins were negative for tumor. Emphysematous changes were noted in the lung. Metastatic carcinoma was found in one of eleven peribronchial lymph nodes, with extranodal extension. No malignancy was identified in the lymph nodes at levels 4L, 4R, 2R, 5, and 9. The lung attached to the mediastinum showed emphysematous changes but no malignancy. The pathological staging is pT2N1MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe, with multiple lymph nodes excised. No malignancy was identified in any of the lymph nodes. The lobectomy specimen revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 3.5cm in greatest dimension, with additional dimensions of 2.8cm x 2.5cm. The tumor was located peripherally in the upper lobe, with no angiolymphatic invasion, no visceral pleural involvement, and no satellite tumors. The bronchial margin was uninvolved with a tumor distance of 2.2cm. The non-neoplastic lung showed emphysematous changes. The tumor morphology was similar to the patient's previously diagnosed brain metastasis. Pathological staging was N0M1. The bronchial margin was confirmed to be negative for tumor in the intraoperative consultation.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 10.0 x 9.0 cm. The bronchial margin was free of tumor, however, peribronchial lymph nodes were positive for carcinoma (3/14). No tumor was found in the excised 4L, level 7, 2R, level 11, additional level 11, level 7, and level 5 lymph nodes, which were reactive. The excised rib showed no pathological abnormalities or presence of tumor. The visceral pleural involvement was present, indicating a pT2 stage, but based on the 7th edition AJCC staging, the stage should be pT3. The non-neoplastic lung showed emphysematous changes. The final pathological staging was pT3, N1, MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe due to non-small cell lung carcinoma. The excised lung tissue revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, 2.0 cm in greatest dimension and 1.0 x 0.8 cm in additional dimensions, invading into the visceral pleura. The bronchial margin was tumor-free, with a distance of 8 cm from the tumor. Angiolymphatic invasion was present, and metastatic carcinoma was found in four out of five peri-bronchial lymph nodes, with extranodal extension. Emphysematous changes were also noted in the non-neoplastic lung tissue. However, no malignancy was identified in the excised 4L and 4R lymph nodes, as well as the mediastinal lymph nodes 4R and 2R. The pathological staging based on the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 7th Edition, is pT 2a, N 1, M X.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, with multiple lymph nodes and pleural plaques also resected. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the lung, measuring 3.0 x 2.5 x 1.5 cm, focally invading into the visceral pleura. The bronchial margin was free of tumor. No angiolymphatic invasion was identified. Emphysematous changes and hyalinized granulomas were also noted in the lung. All resected lymph nodes (total 9) and pleural plaques were negative for malignancy. Special stains for microorganisms in the granulomas were negative. The pathological staging based on the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 7th Edition, is pT2aN0MX.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe of the lung, with excision of multiple lymph nodes. Pathological examination revealed two separate tumors in the right lower lobe, consistent with synchronous primary tumors. The larger tumor, measuring 2.5cm in greatest dimension, was identified as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchioloalveolar features. The smaller tumor, measuring 0.9cm, was identified as adenocarcinoma of bronchioloalveolar type. Both tumors were negative for angiolymphatic invasion and the pleural and bronchial margins were free of tumor. No malignancy was identified in the excised lymph nodes. The non-neoplastic lung showed mild emphysematous changes. The pathological staging was pT1bN0MX, based on the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 7th Edition.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy, with multiple lymph nodes biopsied. All lymph nodes, including 4R, 2nd 4R, 4L superior, 4L inferior, level 7, 2R, 2L, level 4R, and level 7 nodes, were benign. The right upper lobe of the lung showed an infiltrative moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3cm, with no involvement of the bronchial margin. The tumor was located peripherally in the upper lobe, with no angiolymphatic invasion, visceral pleural involvement, or satellite tumors. Non-neoplastic lung showed emphysematous changes and atelectasis. Pathological staging was pT 2a, Mx, based on the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 7th Edition.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy with en bloc chest wall resection. The pathology report reveals an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right lung, invading into the chest wall, measuring 9.2 cm in greatest dimension. The bronchial margin, soft tissue resection margin, and bone resection margins are all negative for carcinoma. Nineteen peribronchial lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for carcinoma. Additionally, multiple 4R lymph nodes and level 7 and 8 lymph nodes were biopsied and found to be negative for carcinoma. Portions of the 7th and 8th ribs were resected and are pending decalcification. The pathological staging is pT3 Mx, based on the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 7th Edition. Non-neoplastic lung shows emphysematous changes and a hematoma in the right lower lobe. Chronic inflammation was also noted.

The patient has undergone a vascular resection procedure, with the collection of perivascular soft tissue at the resection margin. The histopathological examination reveals two distinct tumours. The first tumour is classified as T2, NOS with N1 stage, indicating the presence of regional lymph node metastasis. The second tumour is an adenocarcinoma, also classified as T2, NOS with N1 stage. Both tumours have tested positive for the unspecified marker. Further clinical correlation and management is advised based on these findings.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma, a type of cancer. The tumor was resected in its entirety, specifically from the right lower lobe (RLL). The tumor size was 6.00 cm, and it was classified as T2, NOS (Not Otherwise Specified), and M0, indicating that it is a primary tumor that has not spread to other parts of the body. The histology grade is 3, suggesting a moderately differentiated tumor. The sample components included a buffy coat. No additional pathological comments were provided.

The patient has been diagnosed with adenocarcinoma, a type of tumour, which was identified through a resection procedure. The tumour was located in the right upper lobe (RUL) and measured 2.00 cm in size. The histological grade of the tumour is 3, indicating a high degree of abnormality. The tumour is staged as T2,NOS, indicating that it is a primary tumour of a significant size but without specific details provided. The patient is at stage I of the VALCSO stage, suggesting early stage of cancer. The patient is also classified as M0, indicating no distant metastasis. The sample was prepared using the buffy coat method.

The patient's tissue sample was collected from the right upper lobe (RUL) and was resected for histological examination. The tumour size was 4.00 cm. The histological grade was not specified (NOS) but the tumour was classified as T2, indicating that it has grown into the lung's main bronchus or the inner layer of the lung's lining. There was no regional lymph node involvement (N0) and no distant metastasis (M0), placing the patient at stage II of the VALCSG staging system. Further comments on the histology of the tumour are not provided.

The patient's tissue sample, collected via resection, originates from the lower left lobe (LLL) of the lung, measuring 3.90 cm. The histological examination reveals an adenocarcinoma of micropapillary type. The pathological staging is T2,NOS indicating the tumor has grown into the main bronchus or the inner layer of the lung, and N1 indicating the cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes. The clinical M stage is M0, suggesting no distant metastasis. The tumor differentiation grade is II. The VALCSG stage is not specified. Further comments on the histology are not provided.

The patient's sample was collected from a tumour located in the upper lobe (RUL). The histological examination revealed a grade 3 differentiation, with a tumour size of 6.00 cm. The pathological staging is T2,NOS, indicating the tumour has grown into nearby tissues but the exact extent is not specified. The lymph node status is N1, suggesting that the cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes. The metastasis status is M0, indicating no distant metastasis. The clinical stage is II. The procedure involved resection of the tumour.

The patient underwent a resection procedure on the left upper lobe (LUL) and left lower lobe (LLL) of the lung. The histological examination of the resected tumour revealed a grade 3 differentiation, with a size of 3.4 cm. The pathological staging is T2,NOS, indicating the tumour has grown into the outer layer of the lung but the exact extent is not specified. There is no regional lymph node involvement (N0) and no distant metastasis (M0), suggesting the cancer is localized. The clinical stage is stage I, which corresponds to early-stage lung cancer.

The patient, aged 16, underwent a resection procedure at the lower left lobe (LLL) of the lung. The histological examination of the tumour revealed a size of 3.5 cm. The tumour was graded as 3, indicating a high level of differentiation. Pathological staging was determined as T2,NOS and M0, suggesting the tumour has grown into nearby tissues but there's no evidence of distant metastasis. The clinical stage was identified as stage III. No additional comments were made regarding the procedure or diagnosis.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy due to a well-differentiated bronchiolo-alveolar carcinoma, measuring 40mm in diameter, located near the hilum. The tumor did not invade the pleura and the excision margins were clear. The lung tissue away from the tumor appeared normal. Two intrapulmonary lymph nodes (N11L) were examined and found to be negative for tumor. Additionally, two other sets of lymph nodes (No. 7 and 5L) were also examined and found to be negative for tumor.

The patient, a female ex-smoker, presents with shortness of breath and a history of squamous cell carcinoma in the right middle lobe. Examination of four specimens reveals a metastatic non-small cell carcinoma in a plaque-like area of the right pleura, measuring 23 x 8 mm. A moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, 25 mm in maximal dimension, is found in the right middle lobe, showing invasion of the visceral pleura, vascular, lymphatic and perineural structures, and extending to the bronchial resection margin. Peribronchial lymph nodes show extensive metastatic carcinoma. A separate metastatic adenocarcinoma is found in a vascular fibrous connective tissue. However, no malignancy is detected in the sump lymph node. The pathological stage is T4N1MX. The adjacent lung tissue shows mild emphysema.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy due to bronchogenic carcinoma. Macroscopic examination revealed a large tumor in the lateral basal segment of the inferior lobe, measuring 55 x 38 x 25 mm, with metastatic involvement of the hilar lymph nodes. The tumor was solid, cream-colored, with a central necrotic area and a well-circumscribed margin. Microscopic examination confirmed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with blood vessel, lymphatic, and pleural involvement. The tumor was clear of the bronchial resection margin, which showed signs of acute bronchitis. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was also found in the lymph nodes of the lower lobe bronchi and in a separately submitted detached nodule. The non-tumor lung tissue showed mild emphysema. Additionally, one of the four lymph nodes in the inferior pulmonary ligament was involved by metastatic adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for a fine needle aspiration biopsy-proven adenocarcinoma. Macroscopic examination of the right upper lobe revealed a firm cream nodule measuring 45mm in greatest dimension, located deep to a puckered area on the lateral pleural surface. The lesion abuts the overlying pleura and is 21mm from the nearest parenchymal resection margin. Microscopic examination confirmed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, invading into but not through the visceral pleura, with no evidence of blood vessel, lymphatic or perineural invasion. A peribronchial lymph node metastasis of adenocarcinoma was identified. Additionally, a carcinoid tumourlet was found abutting the carcinoma. The adjacent lung showed mild centriacinar emphysema. Examination of the hilar lymph node showed reactive changes only, with no evidence of malignancy. The final staging is T2N1MX.

The patient has a well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 43mm at its largest. The tumor exhibits a predominantly bronchioloalveolar pattern with areas of stromal invasion and a papillary architecture. Lymphatic permeation is present, with metastatic carcinoma found in some peribronchial lymph nodes. However, there is no evidence of blood vessel invasion, perineural permeation, or pleural invasion. The tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin. The adjacent lung shows signs of emphysema. Metastatic mucinous adenocarcinoma is present in the peribronchial lymph node, but lymph nodes No. 5 and No. 6 show only reactive changes with no signs of malignancy. The staging of the cancer is T2N1MX.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy, revealing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 75mm in diameter, with a significant component of non-mucinous bronchioloalveolar carcinoma. The tumor abuts the pleura but does not invade it, and the bronchial and mediastinal resection margins are clear of malignancy. No vascular or lymphatic invasion is identified. Several satellite nodules are present in the lung parenchyma inferior to the main tumor mass, presumably representing spread through airways. No evidence of metastatic adenocarcinoma is found in the peribronchial lymph nodes or in the fragments of the hilar lymph node. The pathological stage is T4 N0.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy with lymph node sampling, revealing a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 70mm in diameter. The tumor was located in the apex of the left lower lobe, abutting but not invading the pleura. No vascular or perineural infiltration was observed. Metastatic carcinoma was found in the intraparenchymal and hilar lymph nodes, but not in the peribronchial lymph nodes. Other findings include extensive tumor necrosis, anthracosis, upper lobe emphysema, and pleural fibrosis. The pathological stage is T2 N1.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy, revealing a well to moderately differentiated mucin-secreting adenocarcinoma of 40mm diameter with a predominant papillary and lepidic architecture. The tumor invades the overlying pleura but shows no vascular, lymphatic, or perineural invasion. The bronchial resection margin is clear of malignancy and the peribronchial lymph nodes do not contain metastatic adenocarcinoma. Additionally, a sampled lymph node showed no evidence of malignancy. The remaining lung tissue exhibits emphysema and organising pneumonia. The pathological stage is T2 N0.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring approximately 47mm in maximal dimension. The tumour exhibits mucinous and papillary differentiation and invades into an area of subpleural elastotic scarring. Blood vessel invasion is present, but no lymphatic or perineural invasion is detected. The tumour is clear of the bronchial margin, and no lymph node metastases are observed. Squamous metaplasia with severe dysplasia is noted at the right middle lobe bronchial resection margin. Special stains confirm no pleural invasion. The tumour cell nuclei stain strongly with TTF 1, indicating a pulmonary primary. The pathological staging is T2N0MX.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe lobectomy, revealing a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 40mm in diameter, with invasion into the parietal pleura but clear of the soft tissue resection margin. No vascular invasion was initially identified. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in the peribronchial and No. 5 lymph nodes, with perineural and intraneural invasion in the hilar soft tissue. The bronchial resection margin was clear of malignancy but showed squamous metaplasia and low-grade dysplasia. Distant lung parenchyma showed signs of organising pneumonia, congestion, and emphysema. Supplementary elastic stains confirmed vascular invasion by the tumour. The pathological stage is T3 N2.

The patient has a moderate to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the upper lobe of the left lung, measuring 80mm at its largest dimension. The tumor is subpleural, infiltrating the overlying pleura with vascularized pleural adhesions, and distorting the pleural surface. However, there is no evidence of pleural surface involvement or tumor presence at the pleural margin. Blood vessel invasion is present, but no lymphatic invasion or perineural permeation is identified. The tumor is clear of the bronchial and stapled surgical resection margins. The lymph nodes show reactive changes but no evidence of metastatic disease. The adjacent lung tissue shows signs of emphysema and respiratory bronchiolitis. The pathological stage is T2N0.

The patient has a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the left lung, with multiple separate lesions involving both the upper and lower lobes. The largest tumor deposit measures 165mm in diameter. There is focal involvement of the visceral pleura, but no surface involvement, lymphatic invasion, vascular invasion, or perineural permeation were identified. The bronchial resection margin is clear, but the peri-hilar margin is closely approached. One perihilar lymph node is involved by direct extension of the tumor, while the remaining hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes are not involved. Non-neoplastic lung tissue shows emphysema and foci of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia. The pathological stage is T4 N1 M1.
