The patient has a moderately differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring at least 70mm in maximal dimension, with extensive involvement of the surrounding lung tissue. The tumor exhibits blood vessel and lymphatic invasion, but no perineural permeation. Visceral pleural invasion is identified and the bronchial margin is involved due to mucosal lymphatic permeation. Metastatic adenocarcinoma is present in all sampled lymph nodes, including the pulmonary vein, No. 9 and No. 10 lymph nodes. The immunohistochemical profile, showing strong staining for TTF 1 and patchy positivity for progesterone receptor markers, supports a diagnosis of primary pulmonary adenocarcinoma. The staging of the cancer is T4N2MX.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe wedge resection due to a mass. The macroscopic examination revealed a well-defined, yellowish-white tumor mass, 25mm in diameter, located 2mm deep to the pleura, with small areas of yellowish necrosis. The tumor was clear of the stapled surgical margin by at least 25mm. The uninvolved lung showed severe emphysema. Microscopic examination revealed a peripherally located, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with predominantly acinar and focal solid architecture. The tumor was positive for CK7 and TTF1 and negative for CK20. No lymphatic, vascular, or perineural invasion was identified. Adjacent alveolated lung parenchyma showed organising pneumonia and acute bronchopneumonia. The remaining lung showed emphysema with areas of pleural and subpleural fibroelastotic scarring. The pathological stage is T1.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy for a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 70mm at its largest dimension, located in the lower lobe of the lung. The tumor exhibits prominent lymphatic permeation, but no blood vessel or perineural invasion. The tumor is very close to the hilar soft tissue margin and lymphatic permeation is identified at the bronchial margin. No definite pleural invasion was identified. Metastases are present in the peribronchial, hilar, subcarinal, and upper 'medial sternal' lymph nodes. Non-neoplastic lung shows lymphangitis carcinomatosa and mild emphysema. The overall staging is T4N2M1.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a tumour size of 91mm. The tumour exhibits acinar and papillary patterns, with a smaller component of lepidic and solid, and extensive necrosis. It invades the visceral and parietal pleura but no vessel or perineural invasion is identified. The bronchial margin is clear of invasive carcinoma, but the adenocarcinoma focally extends to the hilar soft tissue margin. No evidence of metastatic adenocarcinoma in hilar or other lymph nodes. The pathological stage is pT3N0. Non-neoplastic lung shows lipoid pneumonia and pulmonary oedema adjacent to the tumour, with moderate emphysematous change and eccentric intimal thickening of blood vessels.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy due to a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, possibly alveolar cell carcinoma, previously identified via fine-needle aspiration biopsy. The excised lobe measured 23 x 12 x 8 cm and contained an irregularly shaped grey mass of 4 cm in diameter. Several peribronchial lymph nodes were present, the largest being 1.5 cm. Microscopic examination revealed invasive neoplastic tissue in the pulmonary parenchyma, consisting of atypical epithelial cells with a tendency to form papillae. The cells tested positive for PAS-diastase, PAS/Alcian blue, and CEA. These findings are consistent with a diagnosis of bronchiolar-alveolar carcinoma. Additionally, a 1 cm hilar lymph node was examined, which showed chronic inflammatory changes but no evidence of malignancy.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy, revealing a well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma of 40mm diameter, abutting the pleura with a mucoid grey appearance. The tumor exhibits a lepidic growth pattern and focal central necrosis. The excision margins are clear of malignancy and ten lymph nodes from the 11R group are also free of malignancy. While the tumor is consistent with a lung primary, the possibility of a metastatic tumor cannot be ruled out.

The patient has a well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 75mm in maximum dimension. There is no evidence of blood vessel, lymphatic, or perineural invasion, and no pleural invasion was identified. The tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin, but squamous metaplasia and severe dysplasia are present at the resection margin. Metastases of adenocarcinoma are found in the hilar, lingular, and No. 11 lymph nodes, classifying the cancer as T2N1MX. A separate piece of lung shows no involvement of the tumor, but centriacinar emphysema is present. Elastin stains confirm no invasion of the visceral pleura.

The patient underwent a left pneumonectomy due to a well-differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe, measuring 65mm in diameter. The tumor extended across the interlobar fissure into the left upper lobe and extensively infiltrated the lingula. A separate deposit of identical papillary adenocarcinoma was found in the posterolateral aspect of the upper lobe, possibly a metastasis or a synchronous primary tumor. No vascular or lymphatic invasion was identified, and no metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in the peribronchial lymph nodes or the separately submitted lymph nodes. The pathological stage is T2 N0 ?M1.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy due to apical lung carcinoma. Macroscopic examination of the left upper lobe revealed a subpleural tumor measuring 30mm in diameter, with a fibrofatty adhesion at the apical surface. Microscopic examination showed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with pleural and vascular invasion. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was also found extensively in peribronchial lymph nodes with transcapsular extension and tumor emboli in surrounding lymphatics. The bronchial resection margin was clear of malignancy. A lymph node labelled "number 5" was also examined, revealing multiple foci of metastatic poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The final pathological diagnosis is a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with vascular and pleural invasion and lymph node metastases, staged as T2N2.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 72mm in maximum dimension. The tumor is subpleural and shows potential signs of pleural invasion, although no tumor is present on the pleural surface. Special stains are being performed to further assess pleural invasion. No vascular invasion or lymphatic permeation is observed, and the bronchial resection margin is clear of the tumor. No lymph node metastases are detected in the pulmonary vein node, interlobar node, number 5 node, and number 10 node, which only show reactive changes. The adjacent lung shows signs of emphysema. The carcinoma appears to extend just through the elastic laminae of the pleura, but there is no extension onto the pleural surface. The tumor is classified as T2N0MX.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 48mm in maximal dimension. The tumor is subpleural with focal invasion into the pleura, but clear of the bronchial margin. There is no blood vessel or perineural invasion, but lymphatic permeation is present. Metastases are found in the peribronchial, hilar, and mediastinal lymph nodes. The surrounding lung tissue exhibits severe centriacinar emphysema with bulla formation and evidence of obstructive pneumonitis distal to the tumor. The tumor cells contain mucin, consistent with adenocarcinoma, but are negative for neuroendocrine markers. The staging is T2N2MX.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy, revealing a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 65mm in maximum dimension, located predominantly in the apical segment of the right upper lobe. The tumor exhibits a prominent bronchioloalveolar component with a marked papillary pattern, and is characterized by tall, columnar cells with variable cytoplasm. No pleural invasion, blood vessel invasion, lymphatic permeation, or perineural permeation is identified. The tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin but appears to extend to a diathermied margin. No lymph node metastases are present in the examined hilar lymph nodes. The surrounding lung parenchyma shows signs of emphysema and a localized necrotic lesion. Special stains for microorganisms within the lung granuloma revealed no microorganisms. The pathological staging is T2N0MX.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe, measuring 52mm in maximal dimension, with 30% lepidic, 30% acinar, 35% papillary, and 5% micropapillary growth. The tumor exhibits blood vessel and probable lymphatic invasion, but no perineural invasion. Visceral pleural invasion is identified, but the tumor is clear of the bronchial margin. No lymph node metastases are found in the No. 10 and 11 lymph nodes, which only show reactive changes and prominent sinus histiocytosis. The non-neoplastic lung shows mild emphysema and patchy mild inflammatory changes, with some features suggesting extrinsic allergic alveolitis. The tumor staging is T2bN0Mx. Special stains confirm the presence of invasion through the elastin layers of the visceral pleura, but no tumor is present on the surface.

The patient underwent a left lower lobe lobectomy due to bronchoalveolar carcinoma. The macroscopic examination revealed a tumour measuring 50 x 60 x 45 mm, infiltrating the anterior basal and posterior lateral basal segments, and abutting the pleural surfaces. Microscopic examination showed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with a prominent mucinous bronchiolo-alveolar carcinoma component, with no evidence of vascular or perineural invasion or lymph node metastases. The bronchial resection margin was free of tumour. A back lipoma was also identified, with no evidence of malignancy. Special stains confirmed no pleural invasion. The final staging is T2N0Mx.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy, with the removed lung measuring 100 X 100 X 40 mm and containing a mass of 50 X 30 X 30 mm. The mass was located 40 mm from a 55 mm staple line. No other focal lesions were found in the remaining lung tissue. Microscopic examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, with some areas showing multinucleated giant cells and growth along the preexisting alveolar septa. There was no involvement of the visceral pleura and the bronchial resection margins were free of tumor. The residual lung showed signs of subpleural emphysema. Lymph nodes showed necrotic and reactive changes but no malignancy. A right middle lobe (RML) nodule measuring 14 x 9 x 5mm was also examined, revealing a lymph node with reactive changes but no malignancy.

The patient has three foci of moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe, measuring 20mm (acinar), 12mm (papillary), and 5mm (bronchioloalveolar) in maximal dimension. There is extensive blood vessel invasion and probable lymphatic permeation, but no perineural permeation. Visceral pleural invasion is identified overlying the acinar pattern carcinoma, but the bronchial margin is clear. No lymph node metastases are found. The non-neoplastic lung shows mild emphysema. The tumour staging is T2 N0 for the acinar pattern carcinoma and T1N0 for the papillary and bronchioloalveolar pattern carcinomas. Both tumours are pulmonary in origin, indicated by positive staining for CK 7 and TTF 1, and negative for CK 20, suggesting they represent synchronous tumours.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe, which revealed a subpleural mass measuring 23 X 18 mm, characterized by a white cut face with black speckling. The mass did not involve the overlying pleura or the adjacent bronchus. Microscopic examination confirmed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, with clear resection margins. Scarring and emphysema were observed in the adjacent lung tissue. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one of five peribronchial lymph nodes. Examination of the left mediastinal, left peribronchial nodes, left bronchial stump, and left hilar lymph node showed no evidence of malignancy. Electron microscopy confirmed the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe and chest wall resection for cancer. Histopathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 58mm in maximum dimension, with a cavitating mass and an ill-defined lobulated appearance. The tumor invaded the visceral pleura and chest wall fibrous connective tissue, with blood vessel invasion but no lymphatic or perineural invasion. The bronchial resection margin was clear of the tumor. No lymph node metastases were identified. The surrounding lung showed signs of obstructive pneumonitis and emphysema. Examination of the chest wall and ribs showed no residual malignancy or involvement of the rib bone. The lymph nodes showed reactive changes only, with no evidence of malignancy. The final staging is T3N0MX. Further examination of the chest wall and ribs will be conducted.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 27mm in maximum dimension. The tumor exhibits acinar, papillary, and cribriform patterns with scattered psammoma bodies and an extensive lepidic component. No pleural invasion, blood vessel invasion, lymphatic permeation, or perineural permeation is identified. The tumor is clear of the bronchial resection margin and no lymph node metastases are observed. The adjacent lung shows signs of emphysema and focal respiratory bronchiolitis. Non-necrotising granulomas are present in the uninvolved lung and peribronchial lymph nodes, possibly indicative of sarcoidosis, but further investigation is recommended to rule out other causes. The lymph nodes show reactive changes only, with no evidence of malignancy. The overall staging is T1N0MX. No micro-organisms are identified within the sarcoidal granulomata with special stains.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe apical segmentectomy and hilar lymph node sampling. Pathological examination revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 33mm in diameter, located in the apex of the right lower lobe. The tumor was found to abut and focally invade the overlying pleura, with evidence of vascular and lymphatic invasion. However, no perineural invasion was observed. The surgical and bronchial resection margins were clear of malignancy. Mild emphysema was noted in the distant lung parenchyma. Additionally, metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in the sampled hilar lymph nodes. The pathological stage is T2 N1.

The patient, a female with a history of bronchitis and smoking, underwent a right upper lobectomy due to a mass in the right upper lobe. Macroscopic examination revealed a 27mm cream-colored nodule, identified as a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a central fibroelastotic scar. The tumor invaded the visceral pleura on the medial aspect but was clear of the bronchial resection margin and the lateral pleural surface. No lymphatic, vascular or perineural invasion was identified. The adjacent lung tissue showed signs of emphysema. Examination of the hilar and intrapulmonary lymph nodes, as well as lymph nodes number 3, 4, and 10, showed no evidence of malignancy. The pathological stage is T2N0MX.

The patient, aged at the time of diagnosis, underwent a resection procedure for a primary tumour located in the right upper lobe (RUL) of the lung. The histological examination revealed adenocarcinoma with a tumour size of 2.50 cm. The tumour was graded as 03, indicating a certain level of differentiation. Pathological staging was determined as T2,NOS and M0, indicating the size and/or extent of the primary tumour and no distant metastasis, respectively. The clinical stage was identified as stage I. The tissue was prepared using a Buffy coat method. The sample was collected in the year indicated in the data. The patient's condition was monitored for a certain number of days post-diagnosis and post-procedure. Further details and comments can be found in the provided slide URL.

The patient presents with a left upper lobe (LUL) lung mass, which upon histological examination, is identified as an adenocarcinoma. The tumor measures 3.20 cm and is classified as stage III according to the TNM staging system. The tumor is further characterized as T2, indicating its size and extent, but the nodal status (N) is not specified (NOS). The patient has no distant metastasis (M0). The recommended treatment is resection.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe lobectomy due to a lung mass. The resected specimen revealed a 2.5 cm invasive, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, with no evidence of vascular invasion. The tumor was located 1 cm from the closest margin and did not invade through the elastin fibers. A total of 9 lymph nodes were examined, including 1 from the lobectomy, 4 from level 10, 2 from level 7, 1 from level 8, and 1 from level 9. All lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The pathologic TNM stage is IA (T1 NO MX). The final diagnosis is moderately differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma of the left upper lobe of the lung, with no lymph node involvement or distant metastasis.

The patient underwent a pneumonectomy for a lung tumor, which was histologically identified as a poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, measuring 3 X 2.5 X 2 cm. Metastasis was found in 2 out of 12 examined hilar lymph nodes. Further details regarding tumor extent, presence of other tumor nodules, lymphatic and venous invasion, surgical margins, evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment, and additional pathologic findings were not specified.

The patient has a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the left upper lobe of the lung, with both acinar and solid growth patterns. The tumor measures 2.5 X 2.2 cm and extends to the subpleura. Angiolymphatic invasion is present. The bronchial margin is free of tumor, but a peribronchial lymph node at the resection margin contains metastatic tumor with extranodal extension into peribronchial soft tissues. The parenchymal margin is involved by carcinoma, but vascular margins are free of tumor. One of two peribronchial lymph nodes is positive for metastatic tumor. The largest metastatic deposit measures 1.3 cm. The TNM classification is pT1b, pN1, pMX. The malignant cells are positive for cytokeratin 7, TTF-1, Napsin-A, and show rare focal positivity for p63, but are negative for cytokeratin 5/6. There is no convincing penetration of the visceral pleural elastic layer by the tumor.

The patient has undergone an excision of a tumor located in the lung. The tumor measures 2.5 X 2 X 0.5 cm in size. The histological analysis reveals the tumor to be an adenocarcinoma, which is poorly differentiated. The tumor extends to the visceral pleura and there are other tumor nodules present. The status of lymph nodes, lymphatic invasion, venous invasion, and margins are not specified. There is no evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment. Additional pathological findings are not specified. The immunohistochemical profile shows the tumor cells are positive for CD15, CK7, and TTF1, but negative for CK20 and CDX2. The tumor is located in the right upper lung.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a lung tumor, which was histologically identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 5cm in all dimensions. The extent of the tumor, presence of lymphatic or venous invasion, status of the surgical margins, and any evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment or additional pathological findings were not specified.

The patient, with the subject ID 86-7713, underwent a lobectomy for a lung tumor. The tumor was of adenocarcinoma histologic type, moderately differentiated, with a size of 6 X 6 X 6 cm. The patient, identified as Subject ID, underwent a right lower lobectomy for a lung adenocarcinoma. The gross examination revealed a 2.1 cm subpleural tumor in the right lower lobe with a glistening white mucoid surface, located 12 mm from the nearest stapled margin. The tumor exhibited mixed subtypes including papillary, lipidic, acinar, and micropapillary. No satellite nodules were detected and the remaining lung tissue appeared brown and spongy. Microscopic examination confirmed the tumor to be a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with angiolymphatic invasion. Pleural involvement was noted with visceral pleura. One out of one subcarinal lymph node was positive for metastasis with the largest metastatic deposit measuring 0.25 cm. The pathological staging was pTNM: T2a N2 MX. No evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment was found.

The patient underwent a left-upper lobectomy for a bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 2.5 X 1.5 X 3 cm. The patient's right lower lobe of the lung, measuring 14.5 X 11.5 X 3.5 cm and weighing 162g, was examined. A firm tan subpleural mass of 2.7 X 1.0 cm was found near the base, approximately 5 cm from the bronchial margin. Three subpleural nodules ranging from 0.4 to 0.6 cm were also identified. Microscopic examination revealed the mass to be an invasive, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with a peripheral bronchioloalveolar pattern, involving the visceral pleura surface. No angiolymphatic space involvement by the tumor was observed. The separate subpleural nodules were identified as small foci of metaplastic epithelial proliferations (honeycombing). Immunohistochemical stains showed the malignant cells to be positive for Napsin A, CK7, and TTF-1, with focal positivity for CK20, and negative for CDX 2, supporting the diagnosis of a primary lung adenocarcinoma. The bronchial margin and 16 lymph nodes were found to be free of carcinoma. The TNM classification is pT2 (PL2),N0,MX.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy, with the tumor located in the lung measuring 4.5 X 3.8 X 3.5 cm. The histological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. The patient underwent a right-upper lobectomy for a lung tumor, which was histologically identified as a poorly differentiated acinar cell adenocarcinoma. The tumor measured 6 X 6 X 7 cm. The patient underwent a left-upper pulmonectomy for a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 3.5 X 3.3 X 3.3 cm. The tumor extended to the visceral pleura. The patient has two separate invasive adenocarcinomas located in the right lower lobe and right upper lobe of the lung. The patient underwent a left-upper lobectomy for a bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 4 X 4 X 3 cm. The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy for a lung tumor, which was histologically identified as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. The patient underwent a right-upper lobectomy for a lung tumor, which was histologically identified as a well-differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma, measuring 2.5 x 2.5 x 2.5 cm. The patient underwent a lobectomy for a mucinous adenocarcinoma located in the lung. The tumor, moderately differentiated, measured 3 X 2 X 2 cm and extended to the visceral pleura. The patient underwent an excision of a lung tumor, which was located in the right upper lung and measured 3cm x 3cm x 3cm. The patient underwent a pneumonectomy of the left lower lung. The tumor located in the lung measures 6 X 5 X 2 cm. The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor size is 2.6 cm with no evidence of angiolymphatic invasion or bronchial margin involvement. There is no evidence of lymphatic or venous invasion, and the margins are uninvolved. No neo-adjuvant treatment is evident and the TNM classification is T1 N0 MX. The histologic features suggest invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with no squamous component identified.

The patient underwent a lobectomy with the tumor located in the lung. The tumor measured 3.2 X 3.2 X 3.2 cm in size. The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lung, revealing a moderately differentiated muciparous adenocarcinoma of 12 x 10 cm, obstructing the distal portion of the lower lobar bronchus. The tumor is well-circumscribed, with areas of necrosis and hemorrhage, and mucous secretions on the surface. Microscopic examination shows tubular-papillary structures with moderate cellular pleomorphism and rare mitoses. The tumor stroma exhibits fibrous structure with numerous vessels showing stasis and moderate diffuse lymphocytic infiltrate. The surrounding pulmonary parenchyma shows diffuse interstitial moderate fibrosis, stasis, and macrophage accumulation in the alveoli, with small areas of subpleural emphysema. Examination of various lymph nodes reveals sinus histiocytosis and stasis, with no neoplastic infiltrates, except for the paraesophageal lymph node which shows metastasis of the adenocarcinoma. Lymphatic and venous invasion are present, but surgical margins are uninvolved.

The patient, identified by the case ID, underwent a lobectomy for a lung tumor. The gross examination revealed a solid adenocarcinoma tumor in the lung lobe, measuring 3.5 X 3 cm. There was no evidence of venous invasion or involvement of the margins. The histologic type was adenocarcinoma. No additional pathologic findings or evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment were specified. The tumor was located in the left upper lung.

The patient underwent a lobectomy with the tumor located in the lung, measuring 3 X 2.5 X 2 cm. The patient underwent a pneumonectomy with the tumor located in the lung. The tumor measures 3 X 2.5 X 2 cm in size. The patient underwent a lobectomy with the tumor located in the lung, measuring 4 X 3 X 6 cm. The histologic diagnosis is papillary adenocarcinoma, which is well differentiated. The patient underwent a pneumonectomy for a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 7.5x6 cm, classified as pT3 according to the 7th edition of the TNM classification. Ten lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastasis, but they demonstrated hyperemia, anthracosis, and reactive follicular hyperplasia. No evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment was specified.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a well-differentiated bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 8cm with focal necrosis. Out of six lymph nodes examined (bronchopulmonary, bifurcational, aortic window), none were positive for metastasis. There was no evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment. Additional pathological findings were not specified.

The patient underwent a pneumonectomy for a moderately differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma located in the lung lobe. The tumor measured 12x4x8 cm with a gray tumor of 4 cm in diameter. The tumor was localized with no venous invasion or margin involvement. Metastasis was found in one of the two examined paratracheal lymph nodes. Sinus histiocytosis was observed in the four examined subcarinal lymph nodes and three bronchopulmonary lymph nodes. No evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment was specified. The tumor site was the lung, with a size of 0 X 0 X 4 cm. Out of 9 lymph nodes, 1 was positive for metastasis.

The patient underwent a lobectomy, with the specimen revealing a well-differentiated papillary adenocarcinoma located in the lung, measuring 1.5x2x2cm. The tumor is characterized by papillary glands with elongated finger-like processes lined by moderately stratified cylindrical or cuboidal cells, supported by fibrovascular connective tissue cores. The nuclei are large and irregular, hyperchromatic with prominent nucleoli, and mitoses are present. The tumor has invaded the alveolar and the stroma shows infiltration of inflammatory cells. One lymph node was examined, with no evidence of metastasis. The extent of the tumor reaches the visceral pleura. Further details regarding other tumor nodules, lymphatic and venous invasion, surgical margins, and evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment were not specified.

The patient underwent an excision of a tumor located in the lung, which measured 6x6x6cm. The histological analysis revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma that has extended to the visceral pleura. No lymph nodes out of the six examined were found to be positive for metastasis. The immunohistochemical staining showed positivity for CK7, CD15, and TTF-1, while CK10 and P63 were negative. Further details regarding the presence of other tumor nodules, lymphatic and venous invasion, surgical margins, and evidence of neo-adjuvant treatment were not specified. The tumor is located in the right upper lobe of the lung.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing a 2.1 cm adenocarcinoma, histologic grade G3. The bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved, with the tumor located 4.6 cm from the bronchial margin. Lymphovascular invasion was present. Lymph node involvement was noted in stations 8, "Subcarina", 11, 4, and Peribronchial, with 10 out of 17 nodes positive for metastasis. The pathologic stage is pT1b pN2 pMx. EGFR with ALK reflex testing has been ordered and is pending. A discrepancy was noted between the resection and prior FNA specimen, likely due to incomplete sampling of the affected nodes.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, which revealed a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with cribriform architecture, measuring 1.8 cm at its greatest dimension. The tumor did not invade the visceral pleura and there was no evidence of lymph-vascular invasion. All margins, including bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal, were negative for malignancy. The tumor was more than 3 cm away from the closest margin. No treatment effect was observed. Pathologic staging was pT1a for the primary tumor and pNO for regional lymph nodes, with no distant metastasis (pM not applicable). Five lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed malignancy. Additionally, excisional biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 5, 6, 7, and 9 were all negative for malignancy. The intraoperative consult diagnosis confirmed adenocarcinoma.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing a poorly differentiated bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma of high nuclear grade, measuring 4.9 cm in its largest dimension. The pleura was not involved with malignancy and both bronchial and vascular resection margins were free of malignancy. Five peribronchial lymph nodes were benign with no evidence of metastatic malignancy and there was no lymphovascular channel involvement. The AJCC cancer stage is T2, N0, MX. The bronchial margin excision showed no evidence of malignancy. The gross examination of the right lower lobe showed a palpable mass with no gross invasion of associated bronchovascular structures. The bronchial margin was submitted for frozen section.

The patient underwent excision of left hilar lymph node, aortic pulmonary window lymph node, left upper lobectomy, and inferior pulmonary ligament lymph nodes. Pathological examination revealed metastatic non-small cell carcinoma with features consistent with adenocarcinoma in the left hilar lymph node and aortic pulmonary window lymph node. The left upper lobe lung showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, extensively necrotic, with a maximal tumor diameter of 2.8 cm. The resection and bronchial margins were free of tumor. The inferior pulmonary ligament lymph nodes showed sinus histiocytosis with no evidence of neoplasia.

The patient underwent a right bilobectomy, with excision of multiple lymph nodes and a biopsy of the right upper lobe. Pathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right middle and lower lobes, with a maximum tumor dimension of 6 cm. The bronchial margin was free of tumor. No significant pathologic changes were observed in the lower paratracheal, subcarinal, and right lobar/intralobar lymph nodes. However, follicular hyperplasia was noted in the inferior pulmonary ligament lymph node, and a calcified fibrous nodule was found in the intrapulmonary lymph node. The myocardium showed fibrous adhesions. The right upper lobe exhibited mild emphysema with respiratory bronchiolitis.

The patient underwent a right lung lobectomy, with the resected specimen showing a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.4x2.4cm in the right lower lobe. The tumor invaded the visceral pleura but did not extend to the bronchial, vascular, or parenchymal margins. The closest margin, the visceral pleura, was less than 1mm from the invasive carcinoma. No lymph-vascular invasion was identified. Fourteen regional lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. Distant metastasis could not be determined (pMX). Emphysematous changes were noted in the uninvolved lung parenchyma. Additionally, a total of fourteen benign lymph nodes were identified from the 4R subcarinal, inferior pulmonary, and lower paratracheal regions.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a diagnosed mass, which was confirmed as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with extensive necrosis, measuring 4 cm in its greatest dimension. The tumor was unifocal and did not invade the bronchial or vascular margins. Lymph-vascular invasion was not identified. The pathologic staging was pT2, pNO, with no distant metastasis assessed. Ten lymph nodes were examined, none of which were involved. Additional findings included obstructive pneumonia and benign anthracotic lymph nodes. The treatment effect could not be determined.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy, revealing a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.7 cm in greatest dimension. The tumor was confined to the lung with no evidence of visceral pleura invasion or lymph-vascular invasion. All margins, including bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal, were negative for tumor, with the closest margin being at least 4 mm away. Pathologic staging was pT1b, pNo, pMX. Additional findings included a calcified nodule consistent with an old granuloma, focal calcification, foreign body giant cell reaction, and emphysematous changes. Excised lymph nodes from levels 9R, 7, 10R, and 4R were all negative for metastatic tumor, though some showed calcified/fibrotic granulomas and rare yeast forms consistent with Histoplasma capsulatum. The true proximal bronchial margin was also free of malignancy.

The patient underwent an excision of multiple lymph nodes and a right lower lobe lung biopsy. The lymph nodes from various locations including 4R lower paratracheal, 5 AP window, 2R upper paratracheal, 8R para-esophageal, 9 inferior pulmonary ligament, and 10R tracheobronchial showed no significant pathologic changes, except for lymphoid hyperplasia in the 8R para-esophageal node. The right lower lobe lung biopsy revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma involving the pleura, but not the pleural margin, with the bronchial margin free of tumor. The right lobar and intralobar lymph nodes showed granuloma. The intraoperative consultation confirmed negative margins in the right lower and middle pleural margin.

The patient has a moderately to poorly differentiated non-small cell carcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, with a maximal tumor diameter of 10.2 cm. The bronchial margin, chest wall margin, soft tissues, resection margin, vascular margin, and peripheral margins of resection are all free of tumor. There is extensive tumor necrosis and no evidence of metastatic carcinoma in the inferior ligament lymph nodes, five excised lymph nodes, subcarinal lymph node, and four lower paratracheal lymph nodes. However, metastatic carcinoma is present in the anterior lymph node, hilar lymph node, and three AP window lymph nodes. The tumor has extranodal extension. The AJCC staging is pT2, pN2, MX. KRAS mutation analysis shows no mutations at codon 12 of the KRAS gene.

The patient has metastatic adenocarcinoma, with eight out of twelve lymph nodes in the left lung anterior and anterior left, and four out of four lymph nodes in the left lung tracheobronchial region showing positive results. The largest focus is 0.4 cm and 0.6 cm respectively, with no extranodal extension. The left upper lobe of the lung shows an invasive adenocarcinoma of 5.0 X 4.1 X 2.4 cm size, moderately to poorly differentiated, with extensive lymphovascular invasion and invasion into but not through the pleura. The bronchial resection margin is free of malignancy. There is direct extension into two intraparenchymal lymph nodes and metastasis to two peribronchial lymph nodes, with the largest focus being 1.0 cm. The left lower lobe anterior basal tissue shows adenocarcinoma of 1.0 cm, moderately to poorly differentiated, with no evidence of transpleural extension. Two out of two lymph nodes in the left lung AP window are positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma, with the largest focus being 0.6 cm. The AJCC Cancer Stage is T2, N2, MX for the larger tumor in the upper lobe and T1, N2, MX for the smaller tumor in the lower lobe. EGFR mutation analysis shows no mutation detected.

The patient underwent a resection of a mediastinal mass, which was diagnosed as a 1.6 cm type A Thymoma, completely excised. No malignancy was found in the resected lymph nodes. A lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung revealed a unifocal, well-differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 8.3 cm in the greatest dimension. No visceral pleura invasion or tumor extension was identified, and all margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The closest margin to the invasive carcinoma was the parietal pleural margin at a distance of 1 mm. No lymph-vascular invasion was present. Pathologic staging was pT3 and pN0, with no distant metastasis. Additional findings included focal emphysematous changes and a calcifying hyalinized granuloma. No evidence of malignancy was found in the resected lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a left thoracotomy and lobectomy, with multiple lymph nodes sampled. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with a predominantly bronchioalveolar growth pattern in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 3.7 cm in greatest dimension. The tumor was unifocal and did not show any signs of visceral pleura invasion or lymph-vascular invasion. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being the bronchial margin at a distance of 17 mm. No treatment effect was observed. Pathologic staging was pT2a, pNX, with no known TNM descriptors. A total of 13 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for metastatic carcinoma. No additional pathologic findings were noted.

The patient underwent a right da Vinci VATS procedure. The pathology report indicates an invasive adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with both mucinous and non-mucinous adenocarcinoma in situ. The tumor measures 5 cm in total, but the invasive component is less than 1 cm, corresponding to a pT1a classification in the AJCC/TNM staging system. The parenchymal margin is involved by carcinoma, and the surgical margin is focally positive for tumor. However, no lymph-vascular invasion was identified. Three lymph nodes were examined and all were negative for metastatic carcinoma, resulting in a pN0 classification. Distant metastasis could not be determined (pMX). Additional findings include patchy areas of fibrosis. The final diagnosis is confirmed by frozen section.

The patient underwent a left video assisted thorascopic lower lobectomy, with excision of multiple lymph nodes. The EGFR mutation analysis showed no mutations detected. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe, with tumor sizes of 2.7 cm and 1.0 cm. The tumor was high grade, with lymph-vascular invasion present, but no visceral pleura invasion identified. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being the parenchymal margin at a distance of 5 mm. The TNM descriptors indicated multiple primary tumors (pT1b), with no regional lymph node involvement (pNO). Additional findings included emphysematous change. All excised lymph nodes were benign. The tumor cells did not express synaptophysin, chromogranin or p63. The gross description of the left lower lobe revealed a well-delineated mass and a smaller endobronchial mass, both of which were firm and heterogeneous. The uninvolved parenchyma was red-pink, soft and homogeneous. Multiple anthracotic hilar lymph nodes were identified.

The patient underwent a right thoracotomy pneumonectomy. Pathological examination of the bronchial margin (FS) showed no evidence of tumor. The right upper lobe lung resection revealed two foci of invasive adenocarcinoma, with the larger tumor measuring 4.5 cm and the smaller tumor 1.9 cm. Both tumors were confined within the lung parenchyma, with the larger one abutting the visceral pleura. The bronchial margin was uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The right lower lobe showed a separate tumor nodule measuring 2.4 cm, with the bronchial and vascular margins uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The parenchymal margin was free of tumor. A total of 20 lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed metastatic tumor. Additional findings included emphysematous changes. The final pathologic staging was pT2b, pN0, pMX. The right lower and middle lobes showed benign congested lung tissue, with the resection margins free of tumor. Six lymph nodes from this area were also negative for metastatic tumor.

The patient underwent a left lower lobectomy for a well-differentiated, minimally invasive, non-mucinous adenocarcinoma located in the left lower lobe of the lung. The tumor was unifocal, measuring 2.8 cm at its greatest dimension, and did not invade the visceral pleura or extend beyond the pleura. All surgical margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being the bronchial margin at a distance of 20 mm. No lymph-vascular invasion was identified. Pathologic staging was pT1b, pN1, pMX, with one out of seventeen lymph nodes involved. Specifically, the peribronchial lymph node of the left lower lobe was involved, while the left inferior pulmonary ligament, subcarinal, AP window, and level 10 lymph nodes were negative for malignancy. No additional pathologic findings or treatment effects were noted.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for a lung mass. The histopathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchioloalveolar features, measuring 1.5 cm, in the right upper lobe. No definitive lymphovascular invasion was identified and the pleura was free of tumor. However, carcinoma was present at the inked staple margin. No evidence of malignancy was found in the nine lymph nodes examined. The tumor was classified as T1aN0Mx, indicating a tumor less than or equal to 2 cm with no regional lymph node metastasis and unassessable distant metastasis. The bronchial margin was free of tumor. Multifocal atypical adenomatous hyperplasia was also noted. The overall international stage of the cancer is T1aN0Mx.

The patient underwent a video-assisted thorascopic right upper lobectomy due to a lung mass. The histopathological examination revealed an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, acinar type, measuring 1.5 cm in the right upper lobe of the lung. No lymphovascular space invasion or pleural invasion was identified. The surgical margins were free of tumor. Additionally, seven lymph nodes from various stations were biopsied and all were negative for tumor, with some showing hyalinized granuloma. The overall international stage of the cancer is p T1a/N0/Mx, indicating a tumor less than or equal to 2 cm with no regional lymph node metastasis and unassessable distant metastasis.

The patient underwent a video-assisted lingulectomy due to a pre-operative diagnosis of a lung mass. The histopathological examination revealed an invasive, poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of 3.2 cm in the lingula of the lung, with arterial invasion and involvement of the visceral pleura, classifying it as T2aN0M1a, Stage IV. The tumor was found to be 0.5 cm away from the nearest inked margin. Additionally, hyalinized granulomas were identified in the non-tumoral lung and in the biopsied lymph nodes from levels 7 and 11, with no evidence of malignancy or fungal or mycobacterial species. A pleural deposit biopsy also showed adenocarcinoma. All surgical resection margins were free of tumor.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy due to two lung nodules. Pathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, mixed type (solid - 90%, acinar - 10%) of 1.5 cm in the right lower lobe of the lung, with no evidence of visceral pleura or lymphovascular space invasion. Resection margins were not involved. Additionally, a pulmonary chondroid hamartoma of 1.3 cm was identified. Subpleural pulmonary fibrosis with bronchial metaplasia, metaplastic bone formation, and mucous retention cyst formation were also observed. A total of 27 lymph nodes from various levels (VII, X, XI, XII, IVR) were examined, all of which showed no evidence of malignancy. The overall international stage of the cancer is T1a/N0/M0 (Stage IA).

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for lung cancer. Pathological examination revealed an invasive adenocarcinoma, acinar type, poorly differentiated, measuring 2.3 cm in the right upper lobe. The surgical resection margins were negative. No evidence of malignancy was found in the 28 lymph nodes examined, including those from levels 10, 11, IVR, IIR, 8, VII, and 10. The non-neoplastic lung tissue showed centrilobular emphysema. The tumor was staged as T1b/NO/MO (Stage IA). No lymphatic, venous, or arterial invasion by the tumor was observed. No distant metastasis could be assessed.

The patient has a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, extending through the pleura into the chest wall and superficially involving the adjacent bone of ribs. The tumor measures 3.3 cm in maximum gross dimension. Surgical margins including bronchial, vascular, soft tissue, and bone are free of tumor. Perineural and angiolymphatic invasion are identified. Nine lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for malignancy. The lung shows emphysematous changes, alveolar hemorrhage, and hemosiderin-laden macrophages. The tumor is classified as pT3 under the AJCC TNM Staging, 7th Edition, indicating a tumor greater than 7 cm or a tumor of any size that directly invades certain structures. The tumor is 7 cm from the bronchial margin, which is negative for tumor. Vascular invasion is absent, but lymphatic and perineural invasion are present. EGFR mutation analysis is pending.

The patient underwent a right upper and lower lobe wedge resection, revealing two separate primary adenocarcinomas of the lung. The right upper lobe tumor is a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, mixed subtype with solid and acinar patterns of growth, measuring 1.5 x 1.3 x 1.1 cm, with angiolymphatic invasion and tumor extension to the inked edge. The right lower lobe tumor is a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, mixed subtype with micropapillary, acinar and lepidic patterns of growth, measuring 0.7 x 0.6 x 0.5 cm, also with angiolymphatic invasion and tumor extension to the inked edge. No visceral pleural or perineural invasion was identified in either tumor. Both tumors showed positive immunohistochemical staining for CK7, TTF1, and Napsin, indicating a lung primary. However, the CK20 immunoprofile differed between the two tumors, suggesting they are separate primaries. Both tumors also exhibited marked emphysematous changes. The resection margins may not represent the true margin of resection, so clinical correlation is recommended.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy for lung cancer, with a history of prostate cancer and tobacco use. The excised lung lobe contained a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 3.5 x 3.1 x 2.1 cm, invading the visceral pleura with lymphovascular invasion. Bronchial and vascular margins were clear of carcinoma. One of three peribronchial lymph nodes was positive for metastatic carcinoma. A total of 37 lymph nodes were examined from various levels, with only one showing involvement. The tumor is classified as pT2a and pN1, indicating a tumor size greater than 3 cm but less than 5 cm, with metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial and/or hilar lymph nodes. No distant metastasis was identified.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy for adenocarcinoma of the right lung. The tumor, a mixed subtype adenocarcinoma with solid and micropapillary patterns, measured 6.3 x 6.3 x 5.0 cm. Perineural and visceral pleural invasion were identified, but resection margins were negative for carcinoma. Metastatic carcinoma was found in one of seven peribronchial lymph nodes. Emphysematous changes were also noted. Multiple excised lymph nodes were negative for metastatic carcinoma. A skin excision from the right posterior chest revealed seborrheic keratosis. The TNM staging is pT2b, pN1, pMx, indicating a tumor greater than 5 cm but less than 7 cm, metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial and/or ipsilateral hilar lymph nodes, and distant metastasis not assessed.

The patient underwent a left lower lobe wedge resection, revealing a non-small cell carcinoma, specifically a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, measuring 1.4 x 1.2 x 1.1 cm. No lymphovascular invasion was identified and the resection margins were negative. Examination of lymph nodes #9, #7, #6, and #10L showed no metastatic carcinoma. The extended wedge resection of the left lower lobe was negative for carcinoma. Immunohistochemical stains for TTf-1, p63, and Ck5 were negative. The tumor was classified as pT1a, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. No regional lymph node metastasis was identified (pN0).

The patient underwent a left upper lobe wedge resection of the lung, revealing a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, with acinar, papillary, and micropapillary growth patterns. The carcinoma measures 1.5 x 1.1 x 0.7 cm, with angiolymphatic invasion identified, but no visceral pleural invasion. The surgical parenchymal margin is negative for carcinoma. Additionally, five lymph nodes (#6), three lymph nodes (#7), one lymph node (#9), and one lymph node (10L) were excised and all were negative for metastatic carcinoma. The left upper lobe also showed bullous emphysematous changes but was negative for carcinoma. Immunohistochemical staining was positive for CK7, TTF1, and Mucicarmine (focal), but negative for CK20, Napsin A, and Pax 8, suggesting a lung primary. The TNM staging is pT1a, pN0, indicating a tumor of 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient underwent a right VATS lobectomy, with excision of multiple lymph nodes and segments of the right lung. Pathological examination revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, predominantly papillary and micropapillary, in the right lower lobe. The tumor measured 4.0 x 4.0 x 2.0 cm, with identified angiolymphatic and visceral pleural invasion. However, bronchial and vascular margins were negative for carcinoma. A total of 23 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for metastatic carcinoma. Other lung segments showed benign lung parenchyma and fibrosis. Immunohistochemical staining was positive for CK7, TTF1, Napsin, and Elastic, indicating a lung primary. The tumor was classified as pT2a and pN0, with no evidence of distant metastasis.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 1.7 x 1.7 x 2.5 cm, with no pleural involvement and complete excision. The tumor was unifocal, located in the upper lobe, and did not invade the visceral pleura or bronchial margin. The surrounding parenchyma showed signs of emphysema. Additionally, multiple lymph nodes (10R, 11R, 4R, #7, 9R) were excised and examined, all of which showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The TNM staging is pT1b, pN0, indicating a tumor greater than 2 cm but less than 3 cm without regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient underwent a right middle lobe lobectomy due to a pulmonary mass. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed an invasive adenocarcinoma in the right middle lobe of the lung, with the greatest dimension of the tumor being 4.5 cm. The tumor was found to invade the visceral pleura but not the bronchial margin. The lymph node biopsies showed varying results: lymph node 10R and 2R were free of tumor, lymph node 11R was positive for metastatic carcinoma, and lymph node 7R showed invasive adenocarcinoma with some tumor involvement in the lung. The TNM staging is pT2a, pN1, pMx, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but less than 5 cm, metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial and/or ipsilateral hilar lymph nodes, and distant metastasis not assessed. Additional findings included obstructive pneumonitis.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a lung mass. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, predominantly micropapillary pattern with lesser proportions of acinar and lepidic patterns of growth, measuring 6 x 5.1 x 4.1 cm. Lymphovascular invasion was identified, but no perineural or visceral pleural invasion was detected. Bronchial and vascular margins were negative for carcinoma. The uninvolved lung parenchyma showed no significant pathologic changes. Metastatic carcinoma was found in one of one lymph node (1/1), two of two lymph nodes (2/2), and five of five lymph nodes (5/5). However, one lymph node each from 4R and R7 were negative for carcinoma. The right lower lobe showed benign lung tissue with mild emphysematous changes. The EGFR analysis was negative for detectable EGFR alteration. The TNM staging is pT2b, pN2, indicating a tumor greater than 5 cm but less than 7 cm in greatest dimension, with metastasis in ipsilateral mediastinal and/or subcarinal lymph node(s).

The patient, a female, underwent a right lower lobe wedge resection due to lung cancer. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed two separate primary tumors. Tumor A, located in the right lower lobe #2, was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, predominantly solid type, measuring 3.5 x 3.3 x 3.2 cm. No visceral pleural or vascular invasion was identified, but metastatic carcinoma was found in one of two lymph nodes. Tumor B, located in the right lower lobe #1, also showed metastatic carcinoma involving one of two lymph nodes. Tumor C, located in the right lower lobe #3, was identified as a well-differentiated acinar predominant adenocarcinoma, measuring 1mm. No visceral pleural or vascular invasion was identified, and three intraparenchymal lymph nodes were negative for carcinoma. The tumors in part A and C are histologically different and likely represent separate primary tumors, especially with the background of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia.

The patient, a female, underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung. The final pathologic diagnosis revealed papillary mesothelial hyperplasia in the lung and pleural diaphragm with no evidence of adenocarcinoma. However, metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one lymph node at left level 9 and two of five lymph nodes at left level 11. The left lower lobe of the lung showed a moderately differentiated acinar adenocarcinoma measuring 6.9 x 4.7 x 4.1 cm, extending to the visceral pleural surface with lymphangitic invasion. Bronchial and vascular resection margins were negative for carcinoma, but four of eight peribronchial lymph nodes were positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. The tumor was diffusely positive for TTF-1 and focally positive for synaptophysin, confirming the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma. No adenocarcinoma was found in lymph nodes at left levels 7 and 5.

The patient underwent a wedge resection and lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, revealing two foci of invasive adenocarcinoma mixed with bronchioloalveolar carcinoma, ranging from 2.1cm to 1.4cm, moderately differentiated. No angiolymphatic invasion was observed. Immunohistochemical studies showed tumor cells positive for cytokeratin-7 and TTF-1, but negative for CK-20 and CDX-2. Surgical margins were free of carcinoma. Additionally, four peri-bronchial lymph nodes and multiple lymph nodes from stations 13, 9, 5, and 7 were negative for malignancy. The lung parenchyma showed foci of atypical alveolar hyperplasia and emphysematous changes. The intra-operative consultation confirmed the presence of adenocarcinoma in the resected lung tissue, with tumor-free margins.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a lung mass. The pathological examination revealed a well to moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung with acinar, papillary, and bronchioloalveolar patterns, measuring 4.5 cm at its greatest dimension. The carcinoma was invasive into the visceral pleura, but the bronchial margin was free of tumor. No venous or arterial invasion was observed. Additional findings included obstructive bronchitis. Lymph nodes from stations 4, 7, 9, 10, and 11 were dissected and found to be negative for carcinoma. The pathological stage is IB (pT2 N0 Mx).

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung due to a mass. The mass, measuring 5.2 cm, was identified as a mixed invasive adenocarcinoma and mucinous type bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, well to moderately differentiated (G1-G2). No direct extension of the tumor, lymphatic invasion, or large vessel invasion was identified. The surgical margins were uninvolved by carcinoma. Biopsies of lymph nodes at stations 12, 11, and 7 were negative for carcinoma. The tumor stained positively for CK7 and CK20, but not for TTF-1 and CDX-2. The pathologic staging is pT2 N0 Mx.

The patient underwent a wedge resection and lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, and biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 5, 6, and 9. The pathology report reveals a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of mixed type, measuring 2.5 cm, confined to the lung parenchyma with no lymphovascular invasion. The tumor was located in the left lower lobe and showed no direct extension to the pleura. Surgical margins were negative, indicating no residual carcinoma. A total of 28 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for carcinoma. The pathologic staging is Stage IA (pT1 N0 Mx). The lung parenchyma showed congestion, but the bronchial and vascular margins were unremarkable. The pre-operative diagnosis was a nodule in the left lower lobe of the lung.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, with biopsies of the pleura and multiple lymph nodes. The pleural biopsy showed benign mesothelial hyperplasia. The lymph nodes at levels 9, 11, and 5 were anthracotic and negative for carcinoma, with one showing focal non-necrotizing granulomatous inflammation. However, two of the three lymph nodes at level 7 showed metastatic carcinoma. The left lower lobe showed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 4.7 cm, with no carcinoma found in the fifteen lymph nodes examined. The tumor was unifocal, with no identified visceral pleura invasion or tumor extension. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. Lymph-vascular invasion was present. The tumor was positive for TTF-1 and CK7, indicating a lung origin. The patient's pT stage is pT2a and the pN stage is pN2, with no distant metastases identified.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe wedge resection and completion lobectomy for a lung mass. The histopathological examination revealed a micropapillary predominant adenocarcinoma of 3.5 cm in size, with clear resection margins and no lymph node involvement. The tumor was composed of micropapillary (70%), acinar (10%), lepidic (10%) and giant cell (10%) components. Molecular studies were performed, with KRAS and EGFR mutation analysis showing wild-type genes, indicating no mutations. Fluorescence In-Situ Hybridization (FISH) for ALK gene rearrangement was negative. The tumor was staged as pT2a, pN0, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but less than 5 cm, with no regional lymph node metastasis. Additional pathological findings included emphysema.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, with biopsy of level 9, 7, and 4 lymph nodes, and resection of a rib. The pathology report reveals a 1.5 cm adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, predominantly bronchioloalveolar (lepidic) in nature, with a 0.9 cm focus of invasive adenocarcinoma of acinar and micropapillary patterns. The bronchovascular margin is negative for carcinoma. Additionally, fibronecrotizing granulomas were identified, with special stains negative for fungi and acid-fast organisms. Pleural fibrosis and benign anthracotic lymph nodes were also noted. The additional right upper lobe margin and rib were negative for carcinoma, but a carcinoid tumorlet was identified in three foci in the lung. Molecular studies revealed a positive p.G12C (c.34G>T) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, which is associated with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies in non-small cell lung cancer. No EGFR mutations were detected. The final staging is pT1a pN0, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy due to a 2.6 cm nodule in the left upper lobe of the lung. The histopathological examination revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, lepidic predominant, with no evidence of tumor at the bronchial and vascular margins. The tumor was composed of lepidic (60%), acinar (20%), papillary (10%), and micropapillary (10%) components and showed mucinous features. Lymphovascular invasion was present. A total of 11 lymph nodes were examined from various stations, all of which were negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed a p.G12A (c.35G>T) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, which is associated with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. No mutations were detected in the EGFR gene. The final pathological staging was pT1bN0, indicating a tumor greater than 2 cm but 3 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus, and no regional lymph node metastasis. Additional non-tumor findings included emphysema.

The patient presents with a 4.5 cm metastatic adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype histology, involving the pleura and the middle and upper lobes of the right lung, characterized by papillary, acinar, lepidic, and micropapillary components. The tumor exhibits visceral pleural invasion, lymph-vascular invasion, and extranodal extension, with metastasis to station 10, 12, and 4 lymph nodes on the right side, showing papillary and acinar patterns. The tumor is moderately differentiated (G2) and staged as pT2aN2M1a, indicating multiple lymph node involvements and distant metastasis. Molecular analysis reveals a wild-type KRAS gene at codons 12 and 13, and a positive EGFR mutation (E746 A750del5 in Exon 19), suggesting potential responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies for non-small-cell lung carcinoma. The patient has a clinical history of COPD and underwent a bilobectomy of the middle and upper lobes of the right lung. Further molecular oncology testing is in progress to identify other potential mutations or gene amplification.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy due to a diagnosis of adenocarcinoma, acinar predominant, measuring 3.5 cm. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. A total of 32 lymph nodes from various stations were examined and all were negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed a p.G12V (c.35G>T) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, which is associated with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies in non-small-cell lung cancer. No mutations were detected in the EGFR gene. The tumor was staged as pT2a and pN0, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but 5 cm or less in greatest dimension surrounded by lung or visceral pleura without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus, and no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, an ex-smoker with a history of asbestos exposure, presented with a 6.1 cm mass in the right upper lobe of the lung. A lobectomy was performed and the specimen was examined. The tumor was identified as a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, predominantly papillary, measuring 7cm in greatest dimension. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. No lymph node metastasis was identified in the 31 examined nodes. Molecular studies revealed no mutations at codons 12 and 13 of the KRAS gene and no mutations in the EGFR gene. Fluorescence In-Situ Hybridization (FISH) analysis showed no rearrangement involving the ALK gene. The tumor was staged as pT2b, pN0. The patient's prognosis and response to targeted tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies should be further evaluated considering these findings.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung due to a 4 cm mass. The resected specimen revealed a solid predominant adenocarcinoma measuring 3.2 cm, with bronchial and vascular margins free of tumor. Seven lymph nodes were examined and found to be negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies were conducted, including EGFR, KRAS, and ALK (FISH) mutation analysis. No mutations were detected in the EGFR and KRAS genes, and the ALK gene was found to be negative for rearrangement. The tumor was staged as pT2a and pN0, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but 5 cm or less in greatest dimension surrounded by lung or visceral pleura without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus, and no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history, presented with a 6 cm mass in the right lower lobe (RLL) of the lung. Pathological examination revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, acinar predominant, measuring 7 cm with direct invasion into the diaphragm. The tumor was unifocal and exhibited lymph-vascular invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. Histological subtypes included acinar (50%), papillary (30%), micropapillary (10%), and solid (10%) components. Molecular studies revealed a positive p.G12S (c.34G>A) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, which is associated with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies in non-small-cell lung cancer. Examination of multiple lymph nodes from various levels showed metastatic adenocarcinoma involving three lymph nodes, while others were negative for carcinoma. The patient's pathological staging is pT3N1, indicating a tumor greater than 7 cm with metastasis in ipsilateral peribronchial and/or ipsilateral hilar lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung and biopsies of lymph nodes at stations 5, 7, 11, and 12. The lymph nodes were negative for carcinoma, with some showing anthracotic changes. The lung lobectomy revealed a 4 cm adenocarcinoma of mixed subtype, moderately differentiated, with no carcinoma at the bronchovascular margin. The tumor was unifocal and showed lymph-vascular invasion. EGFR mutation analysis was positive for the L858R mutation in Exon 21, suggesting potential responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. KRAS mutation analysis showed a wild-type gene, indicating no mutations at codons 12 and 13. The tumor was staged as pT2a and pN0, indicating a tumor greater than 3 cm but 5 cm or less in greatest dimension, with no regional lymph node metastasis. Additional pathologic findings included emphysema and a small intraparenchymal scar.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung due to a unifocal adenocarcinoma, acinar predominant, measuring 1.2 cm. The tumor was moderately differentiated (G2) and showed no signs of visceral pleura invasion, lymph-vascular invasion, or extranodal extension. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. Nine lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed no mutations in the KRAS and EGFR genes, and Fluorescence In-Situ Hybridization (FISH) showed no rearrangement involving the ALK gene. Additional pathologic findings included emphysema. The patient's clinical history includes being an ex-smoker with a 60 pack-year history and multiple bilateral ground-glass nodules.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy for a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung, measuring 4cm with micropapillary (60%), acinar (30%) and lepidic (10%) patterns. The tumor invaded the visceral pleura and showed lymph-vascular invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. Metastatic carcinoma was found in the right level 11 and level 7 lymph nodes. The right level 4 lymph node was negative for carcinoma. A segment of the rib showed no diagnostic abnormality. Molecular studies revealed a wild-type KRAS gene and a positive E746 A750del5 mutation in Exon 19 of the EGFR gene, suggesting potential responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. The tumor was positive for TTF1 and negative for PAX-8, indicating a primary pulmonary neoplasm. The final pathological staging was pT2a, pN2.

The patient, a never-smoker, underwent a segmentectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung due to a 1.5 cm nodule. The histopathological examination revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, lepidic predominant, measuring 1.5 cm with an invasive component of 0.7 cm. The tumor was unifocal and located in the lower lobe, with no evidence of visceral pleura invasion or lymph-vascular invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. Four lymph nodes were examined, all of which were benign. Molecular studies revealed a wild-type KRAS gene and a positive E746 A750del5 mutation in Exon 19 of the EGFR gene, which is associated with responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor in patients with non-small-cell lung carcinoma. The tumor stage is pT1a, pN0, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, a male ex-smoker with a significant smoking history, presented with a 1.6 cm nodule in the right upper lobe, a 3.7 cm ground-glass mass in the left lower lobe, and a 1 cm lingular nodule. Pathological examination of the resected lung specimens revealed two distinct adenocarcinomas. The lingular nodule was a solid predominant adenocarcinoma measuring 1 cm, with tumor cells positive for TTF-1 and Napsin-A. The left lower lobe mass was a micropapillary predominant adenocarcinoma measuring 3.5 cm. Both tumors were free of bronchial and vascular margins and lymph nodes were negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed a p.G12A (c.34G>C) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, associated with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. No EGFR mutations were detected. The patient was diagnosed with synchronous primary lung adenocarcinomas, staged as pT2a, pN0, with no evidence of distant metastasis. Additional findings included emphysema.

The patient, a former smoker with a 35 pack-year history, underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy for a 1.3 cm adenocarcinoma. Pathological examination revealed a 2.2 cm acinar predominant adenocarcinoma with visceral pleural invasion, confirmed by elastin stain. The tumor was composed of acinar (40%), papillary (30%), micropapillary (20%), and lepidic (10%) components. The bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. Eight lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed a positive KRAS mutation (p.G12C) but no EGFR mutation was detected. The tumor was staged as pT2a, pN0. Additional non-tumor findings included emphysema.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe wedge resection, completion right upper lobectomy, and right lower lobe wedge resection of the lung, along with excision of lymph nodes at stations 2, 4, and 11. The histopathological examination revealed a lepidic predominant adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, with a tumor size of 1.3 cm. The tumor was unifocal, with no identified visceral pleura invasion or tumor extension. Both bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. No lymph-vascular invasion or extranodal extension was identified. The lymph nodes from stations 2, 4, and 11 were all negative for tumor metastasis. A pulmonary hamartoma measuring 0.8 cm was found in the right lower lobe, which was completely excised. The tumor was staged as pT1a, indicating a tumor of 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The regional lymph nodes were staged as pN0, indicating no regional lymph node metastasis. An additional non-tumor finding was a subpleural fibroelastotic scar, consistent with an apical cap.

The patient, a heavy smoker with a history of prostate cancer and COPD, underwent a right middle lobectomy for a 1.1 cm adenocarcinoma, papillary predominant, in the right middle lobe of the lung. The tumor was unifocal and moderately differentiated (G2). All margins were free of tumor and no lymph node involvement was detected. Molecular studies revealed no mutations in the KRAS and EGFR genes. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization (FISH) testing showed no rearrangement involving the ALK gene. The patient's tumor was staged as pT1a, pN0, indicating a tumor of 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, with no regional lymph node metastasis. The significance of extra copies of the ALK gene in lung carcinoma is unclear at this time.

The patient has adenocarcinoma with papillary and micropapillary patterns in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.9 cm in greatest dimension. The bronchial and vascular margins are free of tumor. Molecular studies reveal no mutations in the KRAS and EGFR genes. Fluorescence in-situ hybridization (FISH) testing shows no rearrangement involving the ALK gene. The tumor is well differentiated (G1) and shows no signs of visceral pleura invasion or lymph-vascular invasion. No regional lymph node metastasis is observed. The tumor is unifocal and surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The patient's clinical history includes a long-term smoking habit.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy due to a 2.5 cm invasive mucinous adenocarcinoma located in the right upper lobe of the lung. The tumor was composed of acinar (40%), micropapillary (30%), and papillary (30%) components. The staple line margin was free of tumor. Lymph nodes at levels 7, 10, and 4 were biopsied and found to be negative for carcinoma. No residual tumor was seen in the completion lobectomy, and the bronchial and vascular margins were also free of tumor. Immunohistochemical stains showed the tumor cells were positive for CK7, TTF-1, and Napsin-A, and negative for CK20 and CDX-2. Molecular studies revealed a p.G12C (c.34G>T) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene, but no mutations were detected in the EGFR gene. The tumor was classified as pT1bN0, indicating a tumor greater than 2 cm but 3 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus, and no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, a female non-smoker with a history of rheumatoid arthritis, presented with a 1.5 cm sub-solid nodule in the right lower lobe of the lung. A right lower lobectomy was performed, and the resected specimen was found to contain a 1.4 cm adenocarcinoma, lepidic predominant, with no evidence of tumor at the staple line margin. The tumor was composed of lepidic (40%), papillary (30%), micropapillary (20%), and acinar (10%) components. No residual tumor was seen in the completion lobectomy, and the bronchial and vascular margins were free of tumor. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 4, 7, 8, and 9 were all negative for carcinoma. Molecular studies revealed a wild-type KRAS gene and a positive E746_A750del5 mutation in Exon 19 of the EGFR gene. The tumor was classified as pT1a, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The regional lymph nodes were classified as pN0, indicating no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, a former smoker with a history of 40 pack-years, presented with adenocarcinoma in the right middle and lower lobes of the lung. Molecular oncology analysis revealed a p.G12C (c.34G>T) mutation in codon 12 of the KRAS gene in the right lower lobe, correlating with poor prognosis and resistance to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. No mutations were identified in the right middle lobe. EGFR mutation analysis showed no mutations in the right lower lobe, indicating less than 5% responsiveness to EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapies. The tumor in the right lower lobe exhibited lepidic and acinar patterns, while the right middle lobe tumor was morphologically distinct, suggesting separate primary tumors. No visceral pleural invasion or lymph node metastasis was identified. The tumors were moderately differentiated (G2) with sizes of 1.6 cm and 2.7 cm in the right lower and middle lobes respectively. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were free of tumor. The patient's TNM staging is pT1bN0Mx.

The patient has a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchioloalveolar features in the superior segment of the right lower lobe and the anterior basilar right lower lobe, as well as bronchioloalveolar carcinoma in the posterior segment of the right upper lobe and an unspecified site in the right lower lobe. Multiple carcinoid tumorlets and leiomyomas are also present. The tumor is multifocal, leading to a stage pT3 pNO pMx. No evidence of malignancy was found in the lymph nodes. The bronchioloalveolar carcinoma is present at the surgical resection margin. The carcinoid tumorlet is reactive with chromogranin and synaptophysin.

The patient, a female with a history of lung cancer, underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe. The pathology report reveals a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with bronchoalveolar features in the right upper lobe, with two tumor nodules measuring 5.5 cm and 1.0 cm. The tumor involves peribronchial soft tissue and perineural invasion is identified. The overlying pleura is uninvolved by the tumor. Adenocarcinoma is present in the shaved stapled line. One lymph node was found to be negative for malignancy. The pathologic stage is pT3 (m) / N2.
