Additionally, multiple lymph nodes from various levels were excised and found to be negative for malignancy, except for one lymph node at level IV which was positive for metastatic carcinoma.

The patient, a female with lung cancer, underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe. The excised lobe measured 14.5 X 9.3 X 3.3 cm and contained a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of 2.0 cm in greatest dimension, which was not invading the pleural surface or the bronchial margin. Ten lymph nodes were also excised and all were found to be negative for malignancy. The pathologic stage of the cancer is 5T1a/N0/Mx. The bronchial margin was also negative for malignancy. The patient's prognosis will depend on further clinical correlation and treatment response.

The patient, a male with a lung nodule, underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe. The excised specimen revealed a unifocal, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.0 cm in greatest dimension, with no involvement of the pleura or surgical resection margin. No lymph-vascular invasion was identified. Multiple lymph nodes from various levels (VIII, IX, VII, II, IV-R, XI) and the bronchial margin were also excised and found to be negative for malignancy. The pathological staging is pT1a, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The regional lymph nodes (pN) staging is pN0, indicating no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient, a female, underwent a wedge excision of the right upper lobe of the lung. The gross examination revealed a well-defined tan mass measuring 1.4 cm at its greatest dimension, located approximately 1.0 cm away from the staple line margin. The mass was identified as a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, a type of non-small cell carcinoma, with evidence of lymphovascular invasion. However, the margins were found to be negative for malignancy. The specimen was received fresh for frozen section diagnosis and later preserved in formalin. The microscopic examination confirmed the initial diagnosis.

The patient, a year-old black female, presented with a lung nodule. A lobectomy of the left lower lobe was performed, revealing a 1.2 cm moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. The tumor was unifocal and did not involve the pleura or surgical margins. Thirteen lymph nodes were excised and examined, all of which were negative for malignancy. The bronchial and vascular margins were also uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The final pathological staging is pT1a, indicating a tumor 2 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The regional lymph node staging is pN0, indicating no regional lymph node metastasis.

The patient underwent a left upper lobectomy due to a mass in the left upper lobe of the lung. Pathological examination of the resected lymph nodes and lung tissue revealed no tumor in most lymph nodes (4R #1, 4R #2, Station 7, 4L #1, 4L #2, 4L #3, Station #5, Hilar Node #1, Hilar Node #3). However, metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in the Hilar Node #2. The left upper lobe of the lung showed invasive adenocarcinoma, graded 2/4, unifocal, with a tumor size of 3.5 cm. No visceral pleura invasion, atelectasis/obstructive pneumonitis extending to hilum, lymphatic (small vessel) invasion, or large vessel invasion was observed. Two of two peribronchial nodes were positive for metastatic tumor. The TNM stage was pT2a, pN1, pMX. No tumor was seen at resection margins. Genetic testing revealed high expression of EGFR, ERCC1, RRM1, and an EGFR E19DEL mutation. No KRAS mutation or ALK rearrangement was detected.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy due to the presence of an invasive adenocarcinoma in the right lower lobe of the lung. The tumor, which exhibited an extensive papillary and bronchoalveolar pattern, was unifocal and measured 4 cm. It was found to invade through the visceral pleura and involve the superficial diaphragmatic soft tissue. However, no signs of atelectasis, obstructive pneumonitis, lymphatic or large vessel invasion were observed. Ten lymph nodes were examined, none of which showed signs of tumor involvement. The tumor was staged as pT3, pNO, pMX. The resection margins were clear of tumor. KRAS mutation was detected, but no EGFR alteration was found. No tumor was seen in the wedge resection of the right upper lobe, lymph nodes at stations 4R, 7, 9, and 10, or tissue on the pleural surface abutting the middle lobe.

The patient underwent a series of tissue biopsies from various sites, including the lymph nodes and the left upper lobe of the lung. The lymph nodes showed no signs of tumor presence. However, the left upper lobe lung wedge showed invasive carcinoma, specifically adenocarcinoma, limited to the lung. The tumor was unifocal, measuring 1.8 cm, located in the left upper lobe. There was no evidence of visceral pleura invasion, obstructive pneumonitis, atelectasis, or lymphatic and large vessel invasion. The tumor was not seen at the resection margins. The TNM stage was pTla, pNo, pMX. The specimen was a wedge resection, with completion lobectomy, measuring 9 x 2.5 x 2.0 cm. The hilar nodes and interlobar node were negative for malignancy. The left upper lobe completion lobectomy showed no significant abnormality and no carcinoma.

The patient underwent a lingular segmentectomy due to a mass in the left upper lobe of the lung. Multiple lymph nodes were examined, including 4R-1, 3R-1, 2K-2, 11-1 FS, 1L-2 FS, Station 3, Station 7 PS, Hilar Node #1, Hilar Node #2, and Hilar Node #13, all of which showed no signs of tumor. The lingular segment of the left upper lobe showed a microfocus of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia but no tumor. An extended lingular segment revealed a minimally invasive adenocarcinoma, limited to the lung, with a histologic grade of 3/4. The tumor was unifocal, measuring 1.5 cm, with the invasive component measuring 0.4 cm. No visceral pleura invasion, significant obstructive pneumonitis, atelectasis, lymphatic (small vessel) invasion, or large vessel invasion was seen. No tumor was seen at the resection margins. The TNM stage was pTla, pNO, pMX. The gross description of the specimens was consistent with the microscopic findings.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, with multiple lymph nodes sampled. No tumor was identified in the lymph nodes, including the 4R, IL, left lower lobe bronchial, interlobar, pulmonary ligament, and AP window nodes. However, invasive adenocarcinoma was identified in the left upper lobe of the lung. The tumor was unifocal, measuring 2.5 cm, and was of histologic grade 2/4. There was no evidence of treatment effect, visceral pleura invasion, atelectasis/obstructive pneumonitis extending to the hilum, lymphatic (small vessel) invasion, or large vessel invasion. None of the 11 peribronchial nodes examined were positive for metastatic tumor. The TNM stage was pT1b, pNo, pMX. The resection margins were clear of tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe due to a lung mass. The histopathological examination revealed a unifocal, moderately differentiated (G2 of 4) adenocarcinoma measuring 2.7cm, with no direct extension of the tumor to the visceral pleura or adjacent structures. There was no evidence of lymphovascular space invasion or tumor-associated atelectasis/obstructive pneumonitis. All margins were negative for carcinoma, with the nearest margin being the bronchial margin at a distance of 3cm. Seven lymph nodes were evaluated, all of which were benign. The AJCC staging is pT1, pN0. An elastic (WG) stain confirmed the absence of pleural invasion. The diagnosis was agreed upon in a retrospective review.

The patient underwent a wedge excision and right upper lobectomy for a mass in the right upper lobe of the lung. The histopathological examination revealed a poorly differentiated (G3 of 4) adenocarcinoma, measuring 2cm, located subpleurally and unifocal in nature. There was no invasion of the visceral pleura or adjacent structures, and no tumor-associated atelectasis or obstructive pneumonitis was observed. Venous invasion was noted. All margins were clear of carcinoma, with the nearest margin being the bronchial margin at a distance of 4.5cm. Six lymph nodes were evaluated, all of which were benign. According to the AJCC staging system, the primary tumor is classified as pT1 and the lymph nodes as pN0. The intraoperative touch preparation diagnosis confirmed non-small cell carcinoma. Immunohistochemistry was positive for p63. The bronchial margin was negative for malignancy.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung. The specimen was intact and weighed 200 grams, measuring 15.0 x 7.5 x 3.5 cm. A moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma was identified, measuring 1.2 cm in greatest dimension and confined to the lung without visceral pleural involvement (pT1a). The surgical margins of resection were free of tumor. Five peribronchial lymph nodes were examined with no tumor identified and no lymph vascular invasion was observed. An incidental minute peripheral carcinoid tumorlet of approximately 1 mm was also found. Biopsies of lymph nodes at levels 5, 6, 8, and 10 showed no evidence of metastatic carcinoma. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. The pathologic staging was pT1a for the primary tumor and pN0 for the regional lymph nodes. Nine lymph nodes were examined with none involved. An additional finding was a minute carcinoid tumorlet.

The patient, diagnosed pre-operatively with Lung CA, underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe. The resected specimen was intact and measured 16.5 x 8.5 x 4.0 cm, with a tumor size of 1.5 cm. Histological examination revealed a unifocal, moderately differentiated (G2) adenocarcinoma. No visceral pleural invasion or lymph-vascular invasion was identified. The bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. Pathologic staging was pTla for the primary tumor and pNO for regional lymph nodes, with no lymph nodes involved out of the six examined. No distant metastasis was applicable. The gross description of the lung showed a circumscribed tumor mass, possibly within a vessel, and an adjacent smaller nodule. No additional masses or lesions were identified. The lymph nodes at levels 4, 7, and 10, and R4 were reactive.

The patient underwent a lobectomy for a pre-operative diagnosis of left lung cancer. The surgical pathology revealed a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left lower lobe of the lung, measuring 2.5 cm in greatest dimension, with no visceral pleural invasion or bronchial margin involvement. No metastasis was found in three peribronchial lymph nodes. However, metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in the left level 8 lymph node, while the left level 11 lymph node was negative for metastasis. The tumor was unifocal, with no lymph-vascular invasion identified. Pathologic staging was pT1b for the primary tumor and pN1 for regional lymph nodes, with one out of five examined nodes involved. No distant metastasis was applicable. The gross description of the specimen indicated a firm tumor at the base of the lobe, with a smooth overlying pleura. The tumor was 2 cm from the bronchial margin and extended to within 1 mm of the inked pleural surface.

The patient underwent a right pneumonectomy due to a pre-operative diagnosis of right lung hilar mass and lung carcinoma. Microscopic examination revealed an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma involving the right upper lobe, lower lobe, and mainstem bronchus, measuring 5.5 cm. There was perihilar nodal and soft tissue involvement with perineural and vascular invasion. Metastatic carcinoma was found in at least 2 of 3 hilar lymph nodes and all 3 peribronchial lymph nodes. The bronchial margin was microscopically positive for carcinoma and grossly measured 1.5 cm from the endobronchial component. The clipped vascular margin was positive for carcinoma within soft tissue and blood. Respiratory bronchiolitis and right middle lobe atelectasis were also noted. Metastatic adenocarcinoma with perinodal lymphatic invasion was found in the right level 4 lymph node. All 3 right level 10 lymph nodes were positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma with extranodal capsular extension. The tumor was positive for CK7 and negative for TTF1, CK5/6, and P63. Pathologic staging was pT3 for the primary tumor and pN2 for regional lymph nodes.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with squamous cell carcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung. Multiple lymph node biopsies were performed, with the 4R, level 5, and level 7 lymph nodes showing no signs of metastasis. However, metastatic carcinoma was found in the level 10 lymph node. The left upper lobe lobectomy revealed an adenocarcinoma measuring 4.5 cm in greatest dimension, with metastatic carcinoma present in 3 of 5 peribronchial lymph nodes and extranodal extension. Vascular and visceral pleural invasion were also observed, but surgical margins were uninvolved. The tumor was poorly differentiated (G3) and showed lymph-vascular invasion. Pathologic staging was pT2a for the primary tumor and pN1 for regional lymph nodes, with 4 out of 10 examined nodes involved. No distant metastasis was applicable. The bronchial and parenchymal margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma and carcinoma in situ.

The patient was diagnosed with lung adenocarcinoma, located in the lower lobe of the left lung, with a size of 3.7 cm. The tumor was unifocal and showed lymph-vascular invasion. The histologic grade was G2. All margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being 3 mm. The tumor was staged as pT2a and regional lymph nodes as pN1, with 15 lymph nodes examined and 1 involved. No distant metastasis was identified. Additional findings included emphysematous changes. The specimen was received intact from a lobectomy procedure. The reactive lymph nodes were found at levels 4, 5, 6, 7, 10, and R4, and non-neoplastic lung tissue at level 10. The left lower lobe bronchial margin showed adenocarcinoma. The left upper lobe lesion was an apical scar with calcifications.

The patient was pre-operatively diagnosed with adenocarcinoma. The specimens obtained for examination included a left upper wedge, left pleural biopsy, and level 5 lymph node. Microscopic diagnosis revealed an invasive poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the left upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.7 cm and invading the visceral pleura (pT2). Large vessel invasion was identified within the tumor, but the parenchymal margin was negative and measured 8 mm. The left pleural biopsy showed cauterized chest muscular wall and pleural tissue with chronic inflammation, but no carcinoma. The resected level V lymph nodes were anthracotic and negative for metastatic carcinoma. The tumor was unifocal, with visceral pleura invasion and lymph-vascular invasion present. Pathologic staging indicated a primary tumor (pT2a) and no regional lymph node involvement (pNO). No distant metastasis was applicable. The gross description of the specimens is detailed, with the tumor extensively involving the pleural surface and showing a tan-white to mottled gray-black and anthracotic appearance. The lung parenchyma adjacent to the tumor showed possible emphysemic changes.

The patient underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy, revealing a unifocal, invasive adenocarcinoma of 2.6 cm in greatest dimension, with lepidic and focal papillary pattern. The tumor is poorly differentiated (G3), with identified visceral pleura invasion and lymph-vascular invasion, but no perineural invasion. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins are uninvolved by invasive carcinoma, with the closest margin being the parenchymal margin at 1.7 cm. No treatment effect is applicable. Pathologic staging is pT2a and pN0, with 21 lymph nodes examined and none involved. No distant metastasis is applicable. Additional findings include tumor necrosis, emphysematous changes, congestion, focal interstitial fibrosis, and alveolar hemosiderin-laden macrophages in the non-neoplastic lung. All excised lymph nodes from various stations are negative for malignancy. Molecular studies reveal no mutations within the analyzed region of the EGFR gene and no ALK gene rearrangement.

The patient underwent a left upper lobe lobectomy for lung cancer. The gross examination revealed a 2.3 x 2.0 x 1.0 cm, tan to dark brown, circumscribed mass in the lung, extending to the pleura, located 6.2 cm from the bronchial margin, 4.9 cm from the vascular margin and 9.6 cm from the staple line margin. Microscopic examination confirmed the mass as a poorly differentiated (high grade) adenocarcinoma, with lymph-vascular invasion identified. However, the bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by invasive carcinoma. A total of 22 lymph nodes were examined, all of which were negative for malignancy, but granulomas were present. The tumor was staged as pT1b, pN0. No definitive fungal organisms or mycobacteria were identified in the granulomas. The tumor approaches, but does not extend through the visceral pleura. Clinical correlation is recommended.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a 1.6 cm poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The tumor was unifocal and did not show any signs of visceral pleura invasion, tumor extension, lymph-vascular invasion, or perineural invasion. The bronchial and vascular margins were uninvolved by the invasive carcinoma. The closest margin to the invasive carcinoma was the vascular margin at a distance of 3.6 cm. A total of 31 lymph nodes were examined and none were involved. Additional findings included non-neoplastic lung with interstitial fibrosis and lymph nodes with granuloma. Immunostains were positive for CK7, TTF-1, and focally positive for P63, consistent with adenocarcinoma. Molecular studies for EGFR and ALK gene were negative. The tumor cells were also negative for ALK protein. A small "tumorlet" was identified on the staple line margin.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe and lingula of the lung. The excised tissue weighed 475 grams and measured 17 x 9.7 x 6.3 cm. The pathological examination revealed a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a peripheral mass of 3.2 x 3 x 2.5 cm, which extended to but did not invade the visceral pleura. The bronchial margin and seven intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes were free of malignancy. Additionally, multiple excised aortic, inferior mediastinal, and N1 lymph nodes, including 4 aortopulmonary, 1 anterior mediastinal, 2 subcarinal, 2 inferior pulmonary ligament, and 4 interlobar nodes, were all negative for tumor involvement.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 3.5 x 3.2 x 3 cm subpleural mass, located 2 cm from the bronchial margin. The tumor does not involve the overlying pleura and surgical margins are clear of tumor. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in 2 out of 10 intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes, with no extranodal extension. Excised superior and inferior mediastinal, N1 lymph nodes, including tracheobronchial, subcarinal, paraesophageal, and interlobar nodes, were all negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower lobe of the lung, which revealed an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 5 x 4 x 3 cm centrally located mass. The bronchial margin was tumor-free. One out of six intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes tested positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma. A wedge excision from the right upper lobe showed a necrotizing granuloma. Multiple excised lymph nodes from the inferior and superior mediastinal, N1, bronchus intermedius, right upper lobe bronchus, and middle lobe bronchus showed necrotizing granulomatous lymphadenitis. However, multiple lymph nodes from the superior mediastinal and inferior mediastinal were negative for tumor. Special stains for microorganisms on the subcarinal lymph nodes were also negative.

The patient underwent a wedge excision of the left lower lobe of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a peripheral mass measuring 2.1 x 2 x 1 cm. The visceral pleura is uninvolved and the surgical margin is free of tumor. Additionally, multiple superior (8 right lower paratracheal) and inferior (4 subcarinal) mediastinal lymph nodes were excised and found to be negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lobectomy, revealing an invasive grade 4 adenocarcinoma forming a 3.0 x 3.0 x 2.8 cm mass, located 6 cm from the bronchial margin and invading the visceral pleura. The remaining lung parenchyma exhibits organizing pneumonia. The bronchial margin and four intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes are tumor-free. A wedge excision from the right upper and lower lobes shows organizing pneumonia and subpleural scarring. Metastatic grade 4 adenocarcinoma is present in a single right interlobar lymph node. However, multiple lymph nodes from the superior and inferior mediastinal, N1, and right middle lobe are negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, which revealed an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 2.5 cm subpleural mass. The tumor does not involve the pleural surface and the bronchial resection margin is tumor-free. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in a single lymph node from the left upper lung and in multiple intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes (3 of 4). Additionally, metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in multiple subcarinal lymph nodes (3 of 25). However, no tumor was found in the left lower paratracheal lymph nodes (5 nodes) and a single para-aortic lymph node.

The patient has undergone a wedge excision of the right middle and lower lobes of the lung, as well as biopsies of the right pleura and diaphragm, and an excision of a mediastinal lymph node. The right middle lobe contained a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 3.0 x 2.5 x 2.0 cm subpleural mass with pleural invasion, but the excision margins were free of tumor. The first wedge excision from the right lower lobe also contained a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 1.5 x 1.5 x 1.2 cm intraparenchymal mass, with tumor-free excision margins. The second wedge excision from the right lower lobe was negative for carcinoma. Both biopsy specimens from the right pleura showed invasive Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma, as did the biopsy from the diaphragm. No tumor was identified in the excised mediastinal lymph node.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a bronchocentric mass measuring 4.5 x 3.0 x 1.5 cm, without pleural involvement. Angiolymphatic invasion was observed. The bronchial margin was tumor-free. Metastatic Grade 3 adenocarcinoma was found in one left subaortic lymph node (station 5L), but no tumor was identified in the left paraaortic lymph node (station 6L), multiple subcarinal lymph nodes (station 7), or the left pulmonary ligament lymph node (station 9L). Metastatic adenocarcinoma was also found in two out of six intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes, but not in the left interlobar lymph node (station 11L). The site of the primary tumor is the upper lobe of the lung (C34.1).

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 3.0 x 2.0 x 1.4 cm subpleural mass, 2.5 cm from the bronchial resection margin. The tumor involves the overlying visceral pleura with tumor presence on the pleural surface, but the bronchial resection margin is tumor-free. Metastatic invasive grade 3 adenocarcinoma was found in two subaortic lymph nodes (station 5L) with extranodal extension. No tumor was identified in multiple left subcarinal (station 7L), left pulmonary ligament (station 9L), left upper lung major fissure, left hilar (station 10L), and left lower lobe bronchus lymph nodes. However, metastatic invasive grade 3 adenocarcinoma was found in three intraparenchymal peribronchial lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, which revealed a Grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 2.0 x 2.0 x 0.9 cm subpleural mass. The tumor does not involve the overlying visceral pleura and is located 4.2 cm from the bronchial margin. The resection margins are negative for neoplasm. Examination of multiple lymph nodes from various stations (2R, 4R, 4L, 7, 9, 10R) showed no presence of tumor. Similarly, no tumor was identified in multiple intrapulmonary peribronchial and right hilar lymph nodes, as well as in interlobar lymph nodes.

The patient underwent a bilobectomy of the right middle and lower lobes of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 4 adenocarcinoma forming a well-circumscribed 1.6 x 1.5 x 1.5 cm subpleural mass. No visceral pleural invasion was observed, but angiolymphatic invasion was present. The bronchial margin was tumor-free by 8.2 cm. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in multiple intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes and extended through the major fissure. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was also found in a single right lower paratracheal lymph node and a single subcarinal lymph node. No tumor was identified in right hilar, right upper paratracheal, and right pulmonary ligament lymph nodes. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in a single bronchus intermedius lymph node. The right upper lobe lung superior pulmonary vein lymph node was tumor-free. The pathological staging is AJCCpT1pN2.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, which revealed an invasive grade 2-3 adenocarcinoma forming a 12.5 x 6.0 x 4.1 cm mass. The tumor extended to the visceral pleura but did not penetrate it, and no angiolymphatic invasion was observed. The bronchial margin was tumor-free. Two intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes were also free of tumor. However, metastatic adenocarcinoma was found in one left hilar lymph node (station 10L) and in one subcarinal lymph node (station 7). Additionally, two left pulmonary ligament lymph nodes (station 9L) showed metastatic adenocarcinoma. No tumor was found in the prevascular and retrotracheal (station 3), right lower paratracheal (station 4R), left lower paratracheal (station 4L), and sub-aortic (station 5) lymph nodes. A right tracheobronchial angle lymph node was also tumor-free.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left lower lobe of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 6.6 x 6.2 x 5.8 cm peripheral mass with visceral pleural invasion. The bronchial margin is tumor-free by 3.7 cm. Angiolymphatic invasion is absent. Multiple lymph nodes from various stations (7, 4L, 4R, 9L set #1, 9L set #2, 11L set #1, 11L set #2, 10L, 7 set #2, 11L set #3, 5) were biopsied and all were negative for tumor. A k-ras mutation analysis will be performed on paraffin-embedded lung tissue. The AJCC staging is T2bN0MX, corrected from a previous typographical error of T12.

The patient has been diagnosed with a grade 4 invasive non-small cell carcinoma, specifically adenocarcinoma, in the right upper lobe of the lung. The tumor forms a well-circumscribed, solid mass measuring 6.2 x 6.0 x 5.7 cm with visceral pleural invasion, but no involvement of the parietal pleura or angiolymphatic invasion. The bronchial margin is clear of the tumor by 3.2 cm. Multiple lymph nodes from various stations (4R, 4L, 2R, 7, 9R) were biopsied and all were negative for tumor. The AJCC staging based on the available surgical material is pT2bN0 (7th edition). The gross examination and histologic evaluation of the specimen confirmed these findings.

The patient underwent a wedge resection of the left lower and upper lobes of the lung, along with biopsies of the left interlobar (station 11L) and subcarinal (station 7) lymph nodes. The left lower lobe showed an invasive adenocarcinoma, with a prominent lepidic growth pattern, forming a 2.0 x 1.5 x 1.2 cm mass. No visceral pleural or angiolymphatic invasion was observed. The surgical margin was tumor-free by 0.5 cm. The left upper lobe showed a necrotizing granuloma, with stains for microorganisms pending. All lymph nodes biopsied were negative for malignancy. The left lower lobe #2 was negative for residual malignancy, with bronchial margin also negative for tumor. Multiple intrapulmonary/peribronchial lymph nodes were negative for malignancy. A single benign lymph node with an adjacent calcified granuloma was found in the subaortic (station 5) region. GMS stain revealed fungal organisms consistent with Histoplasma species, while AFB was negative. The final pathology report was based on gross/macroscopic examination and frozen section histologic evaluation, with any changes to be reflected in a revised report.

The patient underwent a right lower lobe lung wedge resection, revealing an invasive grade 4 adenocarcinoma forming a well-circumscribed, necrotic mass measuring 4.0 x 2.2 x 2.0 cm. There was no visceral pleural involvement or angiolymphatic invasion, and the surgical margin was tumor-free. Biopsies of multiple lymph nodes from stations 4R, 9R set #1, 7 set #1, anterior mediastinal, 7 set #2, and 9R set #2 were all negative for tumor. However, one lymph node from station 7 set #1 contained a necrotizing granuloma. Metastatic adenocarcinoma was identified in a single lymph node from the bronchus intermedius. The completion lobectomy of the right lower lobe showed no residual tumor, but a matted mass of intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes was metastatically involved. The final pathology report, based on gross/macroscopic examination and histologic evaluation, is AJCCpT2aN1 7th edition. Special stains were negative for organisms. K-ras and EGFR mutation analyses will be performed on paraffin-embedded tissue and results will be issued in an addendum.

The patient underwent a wedge excision and completion lobectomy of the right upper lobe of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 3 adenocarcinoma with signet ring cell features, forming a 2.5 x 2.4 x 2.4 cm mass. The tumor focally involves the stapled margin, but the pleura is uninvolved and no residual tumor was identified post-lobectomy. The bronchial margin is also negative for malignancy. Examination of multiple mediastinal and intrapulmonary/hilar lymph nodes, including right lower paratracheal (station 4R), subcarinal (station 7), and lobar (station 12) nodes, showed no presence of tumor. However, necrotizing granulomatous inflammation was identified in some nodes. Special stains (AR and GMS) performed on the lymph nodes were negative for organisms.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the right lower and middle lobes of the lung, revealing an invasive grade 4 adenocarcinoma with sarcomatoid differentiation, forming a 3.5 cm mass centered on the interlobar fissure. The bronchial margin and multiple intrapulmonary peribronchial lymph nodes were tumor-free. A wedge excision of the right middle lobe showed an atypical lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate, raising suspicion for low-grade B-cell lymphoma. However, immunoperoxidase studies indicated a diagnosis of reactive lymphoid hyperplasia. Multiple N1 interlobar lymph nodes were involved by metastatic adenocarcinoma, while superior and inferior mediastinal lymph nodes were tumor-free. Further classification will be reported in an addendum.

The patient underwent a lobectomy of the left upper lobe of the lung, which revealed an invasive grade 2 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a well-circumscribed central mass measuring 4.0 x 3.0 x 2.6 cm. The tumor did not invade the visceral pleura and the bronchial margin was tumor-free by 4.0 cm. Examination of multiple intrapulmonary and hilar lymph nodes, as well as a single left hilar (station 10L) lymph node, revealed no presence of tumor. Similarly, no tumor was identified in multiple left interlobar (station 11L) lymph nodes, multiple para-aortic (station 6) lymph nodes, multiple subcarinal (station 7) lymph nodes, and a single left pulmonary ligament (station 9L) lymph node.

The patient underwent a right lower lobectomy for lung cancer. The pathology report indicates an invasive adenocarcinoma with papillary features, grade 3, located adjacent to the main bronchus, measuring 3.4 cm. The tumor margins are free of involvement, indicating successful resection. There is no evidence of lymphatic vascular invasion or extension into other structures. Lymph nodes from levels 7, 9R, 10R, and 11R were negative for malignancy. The TMN stage is pT2aNO. Non-neoplastic pathology includes post obstructive pneumonia. The intraoperative consultation confirmed adenocarcinoma with focal mucinous features, with bronchial margin negative for tumor.

The patient underwent a right upper lobectomy due to an invasive adenocarcinoma, grade 1, with mucinous features, measuring 2.6 cm in the right upper lobe of the lung. All bronchial, vascular, parenchymal, and visceral pleural margins were free of tumor. However, one of five peribronchial lymph nodes was positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma, measuring 0.4 cm with no extracapsular extension. The remainder of the lung showed benign meningothelial-like rest. The tumor cells were strongly positive for CK7, positive for TTF-1, and negative for CK20 and CDX-2, supporting a lung primary. No tumor was found in the right paratracheal tissue and subcarinal lymph nodes. The final staging was pT1bN1 (PLO).

The patient underwent a pneumonectomy of the left lung, which revealed an invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in the upper lobe, measuring 10 cm, with extensive lymphovascular invasion extending into the parietal pleura. Multiple tumor nodules were identified in the left lower lobe. Metastatic carcinoma was found in 10 of 21 peribronchial lymph nodes. However, the margins of resection were free of malignancy. The tumor was staged as pT4N1. Additionally, three excised lymph nodes (Level 4R, AP window node level 5, and Level 6) were all negative for carcinoma. The bronchial and vascular margins were also negative for malignancy. The tumor infiltrates into the parietal pleura, indicating pleural invasion. The TMN stage is pT4N1.

The patient underwent a left lower lobe basilar segmentectomy, which revealed a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with Clara cell features. Immunohistochemistry showed strong positive expression (3+) of the epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) and negative (0) for overexpression of HER2/neu oncoprotein. Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) analysis showed an average EGFR copy number of 3.4 in tumor cells, with 95% of cells showing an increased copy number of the EGFR gene. The average chromosome 7 copy number was 5.2, with 95% of cells showing an increased copy number. The EGFR to chromosome 7 ratio was 1.11+/-0.35, with 74% of cells showing an increased ratio. The tumor was 2.6 cm in diameter, with negative margins and no evidence of vascular invasion or regional lymph node involvement. Additional findings included mild centrilobular emphysema and a small, focal non-necrotizing granuloma.

The patient, a female, underwent a right upper lobe lobectomy and lymphadenectomy due to a pre-operative diagnosis of lung cancer. The post-operative diagnosis confirmed the presence of an invasive mucinous adenocarcinoma in the right upper lobe of the lung, measuring 2.5 x 1.5 x 1.0 cm. The tumor was well-differentiated (G1) and unifocal, with no identified visceral pleura invasion or lymph-vascular invasion. The bronchial, vascular, and parenchymal margins were uninvolved by the invasive carcinoma. No tumor was found in the 14 examined lymph nodes from various levels and the hilar region. Additionally, atypical adenomatous hyperplasia was noted. The tumor was classified as pT1b, indicating a tumor greater than 2 cm but 3 cm or less in greatest dimension, surrounded by lung or visceral pleura, without bronchoscopic evidence of invasion more proximal than the lobar bronchus. The regional lymph nodes (pN) were classified as pN0, indicating no regional lymph node metastasis.
